<HEAD>City Awaits Report of Whether Rivalry Impeded Rescue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-9 ``A police'' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
police and fire commissioners' comments. Picks up 10th graf pvs
``Mayor Edward.'' DELETES outdated 12th graf pvs ``Fire
Commissioner.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City officials have asked for reports on whether police prevented Fire Department divers from joining the search for a victim trapped in a sightseeing helicopter that crashed and sank in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. A fire lieutenant was quoted as saying he had eight divers at the scene Sunday morning, but police kept them away at a time when only two police divers were in the water. It took 90 minutes to find the helicopter in the river's murk and free the trapped passenger, <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Oyama </PERSON>, a Japanese businessman. <PERSON> Oyama </PERSON>, 29, was taken to <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he died nine hours later. The pilot and three other passengers, none seriously injured, escaped to the surface and were taken to hospitals. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> also said it would look into the issue of whether rescue was impeded by police-firefighter rivalry if it received information that such a dispute had occurred. Police Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said two police divers were in the water by 10:37 a.m., 14 minutes after the first report of the crash. By 10:45, nine divers were conducting a pattern search of the area, he said. Fire Commissioner <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said two Fire Department divers were there at 10:37 and that eight were on the scene by 10:45. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> dismissed as a personal opinion an earlier statement by Fire Lt. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> 1 that the search was impeded because his divers were not allowed to join it. `` It was the feeling of the police commander on the scene and in fact the common practice of all experienced water rescuers that uncoordinated search teams in the water at the same time is dangerous and unproductive,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said in explaining why the <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s offer was declined. <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said the rescue effort was `` within the purview of the Police Department and I have no problem with that. I do have a problem with reports saying we are not needed and unnecessary. Our feeling is that if resources were available, they should be utilized.'' Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said he has asked for a report to `` find out whether all of the assistance on the scene was properly used.'' The mayor said he would not speculate before he got the information. In line with rules laid down by <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> last year to end jurisdiction disputes, police were in charge at Sunday's crash site, a non-fire emergency. The Fire Department calls the shots at fire emergencies. First Deputy Mayor <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezenoff </PERSON> said `` The only question is were there enough divers in the water'' to make the rescue without using fire divers. The crashed helicopter, a Bell Jet Ranger operated by <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, plunged from 1,400 feet after a 15-to-20-minute tour of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghiorsi </PERSON>, chief of the federal safety board's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office, said particular attention would be given seat belts and the pontoons, which separated from the craft on impact. <PERSON> Oyama </PERSON> was snarled in his belt and had to be cut free, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivadeneyra </PERSON>, one of divers who found the helicopter in 35 feet of water.
