<HEAD>Popular Art Show Prints Disappearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People have been stealing poster ads on commuter-train platforms promoting an art exhibit of <PERSON> Georgia </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s work, authorities said. `` They keep bringing them in here, razor-bladed out,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dilger </PERSON>, service director with <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the billboard company that installs the posters. `` People must find it very attractive if they will take the time to cut the things out.'' Posters of the painting `` Red Poppy'' have been displayed in many parts of the city to advertise a showing of the late Ms. <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s work at the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. At least 35 of 200 posters on rapid-transit platforms are missing. When cut, only white borders and the words `` <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> O'Keeffe 1887-1986'' remain. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is sponsoring the exhibit, said he considers the thefts a form of flattery for the artist, who was known for her large and precise designs of flowers and the skulls of animals.
