<HEAD>Chicago's Political Picture Muddled Since Death Of Mayor
Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Lu is cq in 14th graf, `There'll be ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Image is everything in the rough-and-tumble world of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> politics, says Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>. But after four months surrounded by the trappings of power, he admits his image is n't what it should be. His enemies gripe about his willingness to reward friends. And his friends gripe about his unwillingness to punish enemies. `` I might become a little more aggressive, harder than I used to be, but that's because the job will make me so,'' the soft-spoken mayor said during a recent interview. `` Everything you do or say in this office is political, or somebody will couch it that way and force you to respond in a political manner. You try to be a statesman, but hey, you better be a politician, too,'' he added. `` Otherwise you wo n't be around very long.'' `` People have all kinds of plans for you, and I just say that if I'm going to make a mistake, it will be one I made myself, not something that somebody suggested to me,'' said <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, 58. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> became embroiled in a new controversy this weekend when religious leaders accused mayoral community liaison aide <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cokely </PERSON> of repeatedly using racial and religious slurs against Jews and Christians in a series of tape-recorded lectures to followers of Nation of Islam leader <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON>. Mayoral spokesman <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> planned to ask <PERSON> Cokely </PERSON>, 35, to `` tune down his rhetoric,'' but did not plan to fire him. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> became mayor following the death in November of <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, who became the city's first black mayor in 1983 and had consolidated his power over the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had served only eight months of his second term and <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> must at some point face an election if he wants to stay in office. But the date of the next mayoral election is up in the air. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> ruled last week that an election would be held in 1989 if City Clerk <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozubowski </PERSON> declared the mayor's office vacant. <PERSON> Kozubowski </PERSON> said he would n't do so unless ordered by a court. His opposition virtually assures the controversy will be resolved in court. Already, competing lawsuits arguing for either a 1989 or 1991 election are pending. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> has said he is prepared to run whenever the next election is scheduled. No matter what the date, observers say, the absence of a political giant like <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> or the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> will show how splintered this city's once-vaunted Democratic machine has become. `` There'll be so many people running _ black, white, green ... that nobody will know what to do,'' said black activist <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, credited with organizing the grass-roots campaign that elected <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to his first term. `` And there's scores of people talking about running for everything from dogcatcher to mayor and nobody's got the power to tell them no,'' he continued. `` Machines move with precision. If there was a chief like <PERSON> Harold </PERSON>, things would still be done with precision,'' he said. `` But now you've got a lot of little chieftains and everybody's throwing things in the way.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> has had a difficult time shouldering the mantle since he was elected by a <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> coalition made up mostly of white, anti-Washington aldermen. `` Some people were with <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> because they believed in him, some because they feared him and some because he proved he could win,'' said <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` Everybody knew there would be some slippage after he died,'' added <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, `` but nobody knew how much.'' The coalition that put <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> in office already has shown a tendency to fray at the seams. His bloc held together long enough to pass <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s record budget, but grumbling set in almost immediately afterward and many of <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s legislative proposals are languishing in the council. And during the primary elections in March, several black aldermen who were among <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s most identifiable supporters got clobbered in races for party committeeman positions. Normally, aldermen are shoo-ins for those posts. `` What that told me is that the voters in my ward do n't like him,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Beavers </PERSON>, one of the aldermen, `` and they may not be crazy about me standing behind him either.''
