<FIRST>r a PM-MississippiWorkfare     05-02 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Workfare,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Welfare Officials Turn Workfare Jobs Into Paying
Employment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Welfare officials celebrating the first anniversary of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s workfare program say they've shown that even the nation's poorest state can take those who have never had a steady job or who have n't worked in years off the dole. While <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> debated the most comprehensive welfare reform bill in 50 years, <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> officials lauded their program for turning workfare jobs into paying employment for 109 of the 765 food stamp recipients participating so far. Welfare recipients, they said, may be pulling themselves up by their own bootstraps largely because of the state's poverty. `` We're not distressed by the current economic situation. In fact, I get a personal kick from trying to do more with less,'' Welfare Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has the lowest per capita income in the nation at $ 10,204; 20 percent of its residents rely on food stamps. `` A lot of people, including some who work here in this department, said workfare ca n't work in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> recalled. `` The reasons they gave me for that is it's a rural-based state, that we have high unemployment.'' But <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said he knew workfare could work in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> because, although local governments and private non-profit groups were short of revenue for needed services, there were `` tremendous numbers of people on welfare who in my opinion were able to work.'' <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>, a regional food program specialist in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> office, agreed that <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s poverty has contributed to its workfare success. `` I do n't know that this would have worked so well in some other place,'' <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said of the program, which requires clients to work for government the number of hours times the minimum wage that equals the value of their food stamp allotment. She said because so many <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> agencies ca n't afford to hire people to perform necessary tasks they'll give workfare participants doing those jobs more responsibility and training than they would otherwise. She also noted that <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> workfare participants can more easily be recommended to private industry as solid, proven employees because they work an average of six months before <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> personally presents their resumes at a meeting of local business owners and managers in their community. <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said that with 16 counties participating so far, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> probably has the largest-scale food stamp workfare program in the Southeast. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said he hopes to include all of the state's 82 counties within a few years. Each county's board of supervisors must opt to join <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s version of the federally authorized program. Participating counties pay $ 12.50 monthly to cover each workfare client's travel and other miscellaneous expenses, with the federal government matching that amount. Food stamp recipients in participating counties must sign up for workfare, Job Find or educational programs. In the past year, 1,972 of 5,448 clients in the participating counties opted to discontinue receiving food stamps rather than meet the requirements of one of the three options. Forty-four states have a workfare program tied to the Aid to Families with Dependent Children program, according to federal officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Among the workfare success stories provided by <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> is the case of <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a longtime unemployed off-shore oilfield worker. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> began his workfare assignment as a novice in the Welfare Department's printing office. His workfare training later allowed him to select from among several print shop job offers _ at what he said is a livable salary. `` It's something when your children say, ` I want this and I want that, Daddy,''' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` Now, I ca n't get everything they want, but I get everything they need and some of the things they want.''
</TEXT>
