<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-Soldiers     05-02 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Soldiers,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Military Base, Soviets Surround Themselves With Signs Of Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Except for the thunder of aircraft taking off and the showers of flares overhead, Soviet soldiers serving at a base near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport could almost convince themselves they are in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The corrugated metal huts and wooden barracks are typical of bases in their native land. Beside each cot in the bunkhouses are tubes of Soviet toothpaste, Soviet soap and Soviet mirrors, purchased at the base store. Russian women like <PERSON> Oksana </PERSON> <PERSON> Okulova </PERSON> serve breakfast, lunch and dinner to the soldiers on Soviet crockery. Afterward, the women wash up while the men go off to train Afghan government troops and help them defend the city against attack by anti-communist rebels. The hearty breads cherished by Soviets are baked at the base each day, and familiar foods like ham, cheese and apples are flown in for the soldiers, who eschew the spicy Afghan dishes. But the flares, which are released by aircraft to deflect heat-seeking Stinger missiles, serve as a reminder that the soldiers are in danger, even inside the closely guarded confines of the base. `` Of course it's dangerous flying here,'' <PERSON> Tiit </PERSON> <PERSON> Tommela </PERSON>, an army major from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, told visiting foreign journalists. `` We have to take precautions against your Stingers.'' Afghan guerrillas, who have been fighting the pro-Soviet government for 10 years, use the U.S.-supplied missiles effectively against government aircraft. Ms. <PERSON> Okulova </PERSON>, a 25-year-old who sought an escape from the industrial Russian city of <LOCATION> Voronezh </LOCATION>, said the aviation dangers are the only aspect of her life in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> she finds frightening. `` We hardly ever leave the base, so it's easy to just keep occupied and not think about the fact that there is a war going on,'' she said. `` We are forbidden to go to the markets, and when we go on touring trips we travel as a group.'' Officers refused to say how many soldiers serve at the sprawling complex that provides security for the capital, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and the aircraft serving it. It appears to house at least 1,000 Soviets. On Saturday, as the noon sun burst through rainclouds in the mountains ringing <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, a squad of Soviet paratroopers in camouflage jumpsuits lined up on the sports field to teach Afghans the art of hand-to-hand combat. Nearby, soldiers worked with two German shepherds trained to sniff out explosives hidden in items like canteens and matchboxes. `` There are occasional problems with the men,'' Ms. <PERSON> Okulova </PERSON> admitted when asked how she and several dozen other service workers deal with so many lonely soldiers far from home. But several factors limit the potential for romantic problems. Strict rules forbid intimate relationships, there is little privacy in the dormitories and barracks, and the women must work long hours, Mrs. <PERSON> Okulova </PERSON> said. The Soviets plan to start pulling out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15, under an accord signed last month in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. However, the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> base may be one of the last closed by the Soviets. Because there is no firm exit date, the soldiers at the base have a business-as-usual attitude, although they admit to being eager to return home. `` We will go when we are told to go,'' said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> of the Ukrainian city of <LOCATION> Kharkov </LOCATION>. `` Everything here is normal for the time being, although we are of course happy that a settlement has been reached in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>.'' Soviet soldiers intervened in December 1979 to support the government, and about 115,000 remain in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In keeping with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s official contention that <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s army is now strong enough to defend the country without <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> fighting power, the soldiers had high praise for the forces loyal to President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> `` They will resolve their own problems,'' said <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarelkin </PERSON>, a paratrooper from the Russian city of <LOCATION> Ivanovo </LOCATION>. He was one of several decorated heroes turned out in full parade uniform Saturday for the benefit of the visitors. `` The Afghan army is young, but it should be able to defend itself.'' Some Western observers here expect the rebel forces based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to move north and take control of parts of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> as the Soviets retreat. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s regular army numbers only about 40,000 soldiers, many of them underage conscripts likely to flee if government positions becomes indefensible.
</TEXT>
