<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The top aide to a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> congressman jumped to his death from a hotel window Sunday after <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported he had made bizarre demands of male staff members, including asking one to do a striptease. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>, 46, chief assistant to Rep. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, fell 18 stories to a seventh-floor roof of the Helmsley Palace Hotel, said police spokesman Lt. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. The death appeared to be a suicide, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> left a note on hotel stationery, he said, but he declined to disclose its contents. The Post article quoted former staff members as saying <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> had ceded control of his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office to <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>. The newspaper said <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> used money from <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s re-election campaign to recruit for a company <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> owned, offering salaries up to $ 50,000 for single young men, then coerced them to socialize with him. <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, a 39-year-old Democrat, was registered in a different room from Pappas Sunday at the hotel, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. The congressman was interviewed by detectives, who would not comment on the questioning. A hotel operator said a <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> was registered but was not answering his phone. <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in 1980, unseating Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauman </PERSON>, a conservative Republican who was caught in a scandal when the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported he was seen in public with young male prostitutes. The Post's front-page article about <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> Sunday came as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> investigates allegations his campaign disclosure reports concealed $ 6,650 in payments to <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>, paid $ 72,200 as <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s administrative assistant last year, also owns a company, <ORGANIZATION> Pappenbauer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, that received $ 119,642 in fees and expenses since 1980, a revised <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> campaign reports shows. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON>, Republican chairman in <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s district, told the Easton -LRB- Md. -RRB- Star-Democrat he filed the complaint that led to the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> investigation, but it was the Post that had raised questions about sexual discrimination and what <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> called `` the apparently established preference for young males in the recruiting and hiring practices.'' The newspaper quoted <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> staff members as saying <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> told one male employee that he would have to perform a striptease at a 1987 office retreat. The unidentified aide refused. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Ourth </PERSON>, was quoted as saying that when he was recruited to be <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s press secretary in December 1986 he was told he could not date for a year and should devote all his time to the office. Ourth quit within six months. The article also quoted <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hira </PERSON>, 22, a special assistant to <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>, as saying he was fired for refusing to stay at a party in <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> hotel suite last November, after <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> announced he would run for re-election in 1988. Fellow staff member <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> quit because of similar demands, <PERSON> Hira </PERSON> was quoted as saying. The newspaper quoted a memo from <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> dated Nov. 14 as saying, `` ... it is important for everyone on this staff to remember that <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> is the chief of staff, responsible for everyone's paycheck When he expresses a wish, however slight, it should be taken seriously.'' Those interviewed were quoted as saying they did not believe the pressure went beyond attending dinners and parties organized by <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>. Former aides also were quoted as saying <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> excluded female staff members from his social activities. The newspaper said <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON> issued a statement saying <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s office `` has been run in an efficient and well-structured manner The office has been managed in a way which has served the people of the 1st Congressional District of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> well for many years.'' Neighbors and former staff members told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> frequently stays at <PERSON> Pappas </PERSON>' large frame house in <LOCATION> Accokeek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>'s residence is further south in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mary </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.
