<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELINSGROVE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stakes in world-champion banana-split making got a bit higher _ er, longer _ thanks to the determined residents of this central <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> town. Using 33,000 bananas, 2,500 gallons of ice cream and 150 gallons of chocolate syrup, <LOCATION> Selinsgrove </LOCATION> made a 4.5-mile-long banana split Saturday in a bid to regain a place in the Guinness Book of World Records. `` It's something for the town to say, ` When we work together, anything is possible,''' said <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoops </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Selinsgrove </LOCATION> teacher who organized the event to raise money for a community development organization. About 24,000 people standing and sitting in front of one-foot sections of the 12.6 million-calorie dessert dug in at 4:30 p.m. Each paid $ 2 for the privilege. `` It was getting pretty soupy after a while,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Linn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, who was standing near the middle of the giant split, made in three sections up Market Street through the center of this town of 5,500 residents. Selinsgrove set the record for the world's longest banana spilt in 1982 with a 1.5-mile concoction, winning a place in the 1983 Guinness Book. But in 1983, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> high school students created a banana split a tenth of a mile longer. <LOCATION> Selinsgrove </LOCATION> on Saturday outdid <ORGANIZATION> Zeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sorority </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which created a 4-mile banana split in 1985, organizers said. A surveying company would verify the length of the banana split and send the results to <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION>. Six hundred captains each produced 40-foot sections of the dessert, made in a cardboard trough from empty carpet rolls. In addition to the ice cream, bananas and chocolate sauce, organizers sprinkled on 600 pounds of chopped nuts, 150 gallons each of strawberries and pineapples and 24,000 cherries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If all the quarters given away to casino customers here last year were combined in one roll, the package would stretch from <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to the outskirts of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, more than 917 miles. Customers received more than $ 218.4 million, or 10.9 million pounds, in complimentary quarters last year just for walking in the doors of the city's 12 casinos, according to financial reports the gaming halls filed with the state <ORGANIZATION> Casino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. That translates into more than 873.6 million quarters _ more quarters than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mint made in 1978, the year the first casino opened here. `` No wonder we ca n't get change people,'' one casino official, speaking on condition of anonymity, quipped, referring to the industry's difficulty in finding enough workers to sell coins on casino floors.
