<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They tasted, tossed, and generally touted horseradish at an outdoor bash in this Southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> community to honor the tangy root. `` We grow one-half to two-thirds of the world's crop in this area. We think that's something,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Tri-County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegetable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsored the first International Horseradish Festival on Saturday to promote <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> as the horseradish capital of the world. Both horseradish connoisseurs and novices strolled past the food booths and displays in a <LOCATION> Collinsville </LOCATION> park. `` I love horseradish,'' said <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lytle </PERSON>, 67, of <LOCATION> Edwardsville </LOCATION>. `` It clears the sinuses. And they say it's an aphrodisiac.'' `` Honey and horseradish makes a good cough medicine,'' added his wife, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, 66. In addition to tasting recipes made with horseradish, some people participated in the Horseradish Olympics _ which included a root toss, where contestants tried to lob foot-long horseradish roots farther than anyone else, and a hot dog eating contest. The dogs, of course, were slathered with horseradish.
