<HEAD>Jackson: Campaign a Success, With or Without Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> gazed from a balcony over the sunny, riverfront lawn party where a well-dressed crowd sipped wine. `` No one ever told us it was going to be easy,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> shouted to the 300 partygoers. But the candidate wanted his predominately black audience to remember something: `` When you consider what we came from, we do n't have the ability to get tired `` This is not just <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. This is from the back of the bus in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> to being within one of three to being the next president.'' It is a theme that has become increasingly prominent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in recent days after his heavy losses in the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primaries. He is sounding a twofold message as he trails <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> down the home stretch of the primary season: First, he vows to fight on to win the nomination and raise issues. But second, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> highlights the historic aspect of his candidacy, casting it in terms that spell victory whether he wins or loses the nomination. In the face of a new poll showing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with a 40-point lead in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, whose primary is Tuesday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> appeared to be dwelling increasingly on this over the weekend. By pointing to his unquestioned successes and the wide acceptance his candidacy has received, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> paints his effort as an outgrowth of the civil rights struggles of the 1960s and another step on the road to full equality for blacks. He contrasts his bid for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with the grim days more than two decades ago when people died fighting for just the right to vote. So as he campaigns across <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, he tells church crowds and rallies that his candidacy is far more than a journey from the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses in February to this summer's Democratic convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. It's a journey that began when blacks began rebelling in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, against being forced to ride in the back of the bus, he said. And it's a mission that must be carried forward by people like the well-heeled crowd at the estate of physician <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> in this <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> suburb, he told them. He said reporters are asking him after his string of losses, `` How can you go on?'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s answer: `` Do you know how far we've come? ... We're almost to the top of the hill We've come too far. We must press forward.'' The crowd laughed with acknowledgement when he pointed to the strides they have made financially, saying, `` Most of us standing here today are one generation out of chitlins.'' To dramatize his point, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> related as he often does the story of his humble <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> beginnings _ born to a teenage mother and the married man next door, living in a house with wallpaper for warmth not decoration, waiting to eat Thanksgiving dinner until his mother came home with leftovers from the table of the white people whose meal she had prepared. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> sometimes seems amazed himself as he tells the story. `` When I win, there are no more impossible dreams,'' he often says. But in keeping with his portrayal of his candidacy as part of a historical continuum, he told his <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> audience that he expects them to carry on the movement. He said they must `` translate this movement'' into demands for blacks in positions of authority at banks and universities and corporations where there are still barriers, as well as in government. `` When I shake apples from the tree, you must pick up these apples and make them into jelly and take them to the market,'' he said. `` To have continuity in our struggle we must establish a heritage of success in the government for all coming generations.''
