<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gunther </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON> said he planned to resign as conductor of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> because of numerous violations of his contract, a newspaper reported today. <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON>, the orchestra's conductor since 1984, told musicians about his plans during intermission of Saturday night's concert. On Sunday, he declined to discuss his resignation, effective when his contract expires in 1990, The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. Several musicians told newspaper that <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON> cited several complaints, many of them related to the orchestra's financial troubles. Among <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON>'s complaints, they said, were cancellation of a 1989-90 tour of the Far East; refusal to guarantee frequent domestic tours; reduction of the number of guaranteed musicians from 103 to 97; and refusal to promise the orchestra will move in 1989-90 from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auditorium </ORGANIZATION> to Orchestra Hall. `` <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON> told us that virtually the only thing they honored in the contract was payment, and that even that was sometimes late,'' said <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Janowsky </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> DSO </ORGANIZATION> bassist. Orchestra board Chairman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said in a statement Sunday that the orchestra's financial troubles caused the board to fail to meet some terms of <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON>'s contract. But it was the board's `` intention and hope to honor Maestro <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON>'s contract in every detail,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Herbig </PERSON> said he would complete a second three-year term under a contract he signed in 1987, leaving 28 months to work with management in finding a replacement. The orchestra in November, while musicians were in the midst of a 12-week work stoppage, announced a deficit of $ 1.4 million for the 1986-87 season, raising its cumulative deficit to $ 4.1 million against an annual budget of $ 14 million. A deficit reduction campaign has been launched. But The News, citing an unidentified source close to the orchestra, said musicians were told last week an additional deficit of $ 400,000 was anticipated for this season.
