<FIRST>r w PM-OverseasVoters     05-02 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overseas Voters,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Overseas to Get Blank Ballots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ballots without the names of specific candidates will be available for the first time to an estimated 3 million Americans in other countries who are eligible to vote on Nov. 8 for the next president. The new, fill-in-the-blank ballots are for people who may not be able to get a regular absentee ballot submitted in time _ from a remote mission in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, for example, or a submarine at sea for months. But mostly they are for the victims of slow mail deliveries. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said a million of these write-in ballots will be sent in July to all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies and consulates and to the voting officers attached to each military unit overseas. The object is to increase the number of Americans who vote, even if they are working, traveling or living abroad. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> have the largest number of such civilians. The biggest numbers of military are in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> estimates that in the 1984 election, about 55 percent of the overseas military and 35 percent of civilians cast ballots. For civilians, that was much lower than the national average of 53.1 percent. He also estimates on the basis of polls that 8.5 percent _ roughly 250,000 _ tried to vote but failed to get in a regular absentee ballot and have it counted by voting authorities at home. There were many causes, including failure to write the proper office in time, failure of local authorities to mail the ballot in time, failure of the voter to mail it back, or failure of local deliveries abroad. Absentee ballots that arrive too late are not counted. `` We just got a court order Monday to make election officials in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> count absentee ballots received up to 10 days after the April 26 primary,'' <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Most <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> election officials began mailing their absentee ballots only two weeks before the election.'' One reason for slow mailing by local authorities is that they have to wait until candidates are named before they can start printing. The blank absentee ballots will be usable only for federal positions in the general election on Nov. 8. The voter must first write for a regular absentee ballot from his or her district at home, getting the application in at least 30 days before Election Day. If the absentee ballot does not reach the voter in time, he or she can write in the name of a choice for president, for senator if there is a senatorial election in the state and for a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>. The names of political parties can be written instead, and such tickets may be split. `` You can write the name of one party as your choice for president and another party for the senator, if you do n't write individual names,'' <PERSON> Valentino </PERSON> explained. State authorities will have to count the write-in ballot as they do regular absentee ballots. The write-ins are not to be used or distributed within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>. But they will be sent to units deploying to overseas assignments and to ships and submarines expected to be at sea on Election Day.
