<HEAD>PAC Contributions to House, Senate Races Up A Quarter in Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Special interest groups have supplied $ 53 million to congressional candidates in the last 15 months, with the chairman of the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> making the biggest haul. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, who faces a challenge this fall from Republican Rep. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>, led the list of recipients of political action committee money with $ 1.4 million. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> also ranked as the largest overall fund-raiser among candidates so far, with just over $ 5 million by March 31, compared with <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>'s $ 365,000. The figures were released Sunday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which said congressional candidates raised $ 180 million overall in the first 15 months of the two-year cycle that culminates with November's elections. Of that, it said, $ 53 million _ or 29 percent _ came from the special-interest groups known as PACs. At the comparable time in 1986, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> contenders had raised $ 167 million, of which $ 41 million was in PAC money, a 24 percent share. The growing clout of special interests in congressional elections has prompted <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> critics to seek voluntary restraints on the amount of such money that can be spent by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates. The Democratic push has been stymied by Republican filibusters. Overall, the 143 candidates for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats raised $ 79 million during the 15-month period, about $ 1 million less than at the comparable time two years ago. The decrease was due in part to a smaller number of candidates than in 1986. The 1,201 candidates for <ORGANIZATIO