<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four months after he completed a 25-year prison term, <PERSON> Modesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON> has yet to taste freedom. The former army captain was convicted of killing a cadet in 1962 who allegedly learned of his involvement in a plot to overthrow President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>'s longest-reigning leader <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON>, 56, said in an interview in March that he was never allowed to appear in court to plead his innocence and that his confession was extracted by torture, including electric shocks on a grill. `` When you are defenseless under the torturers, 10 in my case, you give in and say what they want you to,'' <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON> was released from prison on Dec. 20 but was put under police custody in the town of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estanislao </LOCATION>, 85 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>. He was brought to <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION> in February, where two round-the-clock guards prevented him from leaving the home of his invalid mother. The government said without elaboration that the guards were protecting Ortigoza. He escaped March 25 with the help of an opposition leader. Both fled one block to the residence of Colombian Ambassador <PERSON> Vicente </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Emiliani </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> granted both political asylum but the <LOCATION> Paraguayan </LOCATION> government has refused to act on <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s request for safe-conduct passage out of the country for <LOCATION> Ortigoza </LOCATION> and the dissident, <PERSON> Hermes </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Saguier </PERSON>. <PERSON> Emiliani </PERSON> recently said he has had `` no news'' on the pending requests for safe passage. Interior Minister <PERSON> Sabino </PERSON> <PERSON> Montanaro </PERSON> says his country is in no rush to grant <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON> safe passage, calling him a `` common criminal.'' Government officials have branded <PERSON> Saguier </PERSON>, 40, a subversive and compared <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON>'s escape to the embassy `` a terrorist action.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Saldivar </PERSON> declined to say when the government would respond to <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON>'s request for safe passage. `` It looks like it will be one of those things that will go on and on and on indefinitely,'' said a European diplomatic who has followed the situation closely. The diplomat spoke on condition of anonymity. Neither Ortigoza nor <PERSON> Saguier </PERSON> are allowed to speak to reporters or to leave the ambassador's residence. Their lawyers, family and close friends are the only ones permitted to visit. <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON>'s treatment is meant to be a lesson to those who would conspire against <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, in power since 1954. <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Digno </PERSON> <PERSON> Britez </PERSON>, says the May 16-18 visit to <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s trip to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in June could help <PERSON> Ortigoza </PERSON> and <PERSON> Saguier </PERSON> gain safe passage out of <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> would not want something like that to be brought up while he visits the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Britez </PERSON> said, adding: `` Our gover