<SECOND>PM-Poland-Strike Scene,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Strikers and Families Embrace at Plant Gate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the strike at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> steelworks entered its sixth day, 120 haggard workers appeared at the facility's gate to receive flowers, food and words of support from tearful family members. Most of the 50 wives, children and parents of the striking workers remained outside the partially opened gate on Sunday, but a some weeping wives stepped a few feet inside to embrace their husbands. `` I know that my voice is breaking,'' strike leader <PERSON> Andrezej </PERSON> <PERSON> Szewczuwaniec </PERSON> told the group. `` But I'm very moved. There is lot of optimism in me because there is only one Polish heart, and it can not be split.'' He told the families that the strike, which began Tuesday for higher pay and union recognition, would continue today. `` We will not disappoint our wives, our sons, our mothers nor you behind the gate,'' he said. When he stopped speaking, the crowd began chanting, `` God bless you! God bless you!'' The family members passed plastic bags of food and bunches of flowers through the gate to the strikers, and the group sang patriotic hymns from both sides of the fence. Earlier in the day, police had stopped some people from marching to the plant. But police were nowhere around the main plant gates at midafternoon, when the family members began arriving on foot or by public transportation. The families offered words of support: `` We are with you. ... We support you. ... Long live the mill.'' `` We are all moved here,'' said another member of the strike committee, <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Handzlik </PERSON>. `` Here we are seven years after martial law and again we raise our hands, we raise our heads, we raise our backs. `` We want to demand human and social rights that we deserve. We want to assure you that we will go on with the strike.'' After the speeches, the workers said `` Do widzenia'' _ `` Until we see you again'' _ and marched back inside the plant.
