<SECOND>PM-Cable TV,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Growing Into `Goliath'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After years of being considered the little sibling of broadcast television, some say the cable TV industry is beginning to look more like Goliath than <PERSON> David </PERSON>. Cable TV, now watched by more than 50 percent of all American households, has become a $ 12 billion industry that is gaining viewers steadily, mostly at the expense of the broadcast networks. But with prosperity comes increased scrutiny, and in cable's case <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been raising questions about concentration of ownership within the industry, complaints of poor service and rising rates Some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> say it may be time to reregulate cable TV. `` We have to pay attention to this,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mooney </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, told an audience at the opening session of the group's annual convention Sunday. `` We ca n't rebuff our friends,'' he said. `` An important part of good business is good politics.'' More than 13,000 people are expected to attend the convention, which runs through Tuesday. Most governmental regulation has been lifted from the industry. The most recent deregulation came in January 1987 when most cable systems were freed of municipal rate control. They now have more control than ever on what viewers see and how much they pay. Deregulation brought increases in rates. The industry says the average subscriber's bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months after price control was lifted, but critics in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cite instances of rates going up by as much as 400 percent in some systems. Despite the increase, subscribers continued to sign on. Cable systems added more than 4 million subscribers in 1987, putting the percentage of households receiving cable to nearly 52 percent _ about 45 million households. Now that many cable companies have finished building their systems _ wiring more than 80 percent of the nation's households _ cable companies are starting to pay off their debt and are putting their cash into programming. `` Programming is going to drive penetration,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cownie </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moines </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> NCTA </ORGANIZATION> chairman. `` That's going to move us up to the 70 percent saturation level from 52 percent where we are now.'' The industry has been encouraged by the success of its early efforts, like <PERSON> Showtime </PERSON>'s `` It's <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shandling </PERSON>'s Show,'' a comedy series now on <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The show is one of only a few that have moved from cable to broadcast. Most of the migration is still from broadcast to cable, which has become home to many an old syndicated rerun. But cable executives say that will change as cable systems pour more money into developing their own programs. `` We should be more concerned with what the content will be than where it comes from,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuchs </PERSON>, chairman of Home Box Office. <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> received praise for its recent program `` Dear America: Letters Home from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' Cable TV, particularly the Entertainment and <ORGANIZATION> Sports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION>, also has been landing some big sports contracts. Exclusive cable contracts for big sports events, though, have been criticized for denying viewing of these games to those who do n't subscribe to cable Before cable came along, these games could be seen free on broadcast TV. But cable is likely to continue its foray into sports programming. `` There are more first run movies and sports on cable, and that's going to continue,'' said <PERSON> Fuchs </PERSON>. `` The only things that will get some protection -LRB- from cable-exclusive contracts -RRB- are big sports events like the Superbowl.''
