<SECOND>PM-Coalinga Quake,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feelings Mixed Whether Rebuilt Downtown Is Better</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALINGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Coalinga </LOCATION>'s downtown business district, devastated five years ago by one of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s strongest earthquakes this century, is still struggling to recover. In one terrifying moment, the town's turn-of-the-century stores buckled under the force of the quake. The 6.7-magnitude temblor on May 2, 1983, dealt its heaviest toll to two blocks that held most of the community's retail stores. All had to be razed. Today on the same land, modern one-story block buildings house the merchants who hung on during the hard times after the quake in the town of 8,000 residents about 200 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. But vacant lots also mark much of downtown, raising concern that there are too few shops left to attract enough customers to be profitable. `` If there were other businesses, things would be working tremendously; there are too many empty lots,'' said <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, who moved all the clothes from her dress shop to her less-damaged home after the earthquake until she could get back in business, first in a gymnasium, then a house trailer and now in the rejuvenated downtown. Downtown businesses now include two dress shops, two banks, two drug stores, a furniture store, a combination bicycle-computer shop and a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> mail order store. Other downtown offices house a weekly newspaper, a lawyer, accountant and real estate agent. `` There are no coffee shops, so people do n't come downtown as much,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>. `` We need more retail in these two blocks, not offices.'' The city government, which aggressively secured a variety of financing to recover from the quake, owns the rebuilt stores and is trying to find more financing and more businesses to fill the empty lots. The city subsidizes rents, charging about 34 cents a square foot, said <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a councilman and <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> director. That's a sharp increase from the 10-20 cents per square foot merchants paid for space in the structures wiped out by the quake. Those increases make survival difficult for store owners who were just making it under the old rents. Mrs. <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON> said the owners of a jewelry store decided to retire after the earthquake, a television store closed and one business owner died of stress while struggling to keep going in a house trailer. Not all merchants have been hurt, however. The operators of Service Pharmacy owned their building and it was fully insured, enabling them to rebuild large enough for their needs and allow space to rent out offices. Sales taxes, which indicate how much retail business a community is doing, have n't climbed back to the level before the earthquake, which left 47 injured and caused an estimated $ 31 million in damage, said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, the public works director. But 2,873 building permits were issued in the five years since for $ 41 million worth of new construction or rehabilitation, he said. `` That's about one permit per building in town,'' <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. There has been a net gain of 384 dwellings in <LOCATION> Coalinga </LOCATION> since the earthquake, allowing the population to increase from 7,000 to 8,000, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> said. The city also has a new natural gas system, new sewer lines, a new fire station, bus terminal, day care center, senior citizens center, fitness center and community swimming pool. Despite the personal and financial trauma, <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> feels the earthquake `` was a real positive thing in making us clean up some problems we had in buildings _ safety and that type of thing.'' The quake was one of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s 10 strongest quakes this century. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale.
