<HEAD>Rightist Leader Refuses to Endorse Chirac</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s extreme right leader, refused to endorse conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> but told supporters not to vote for President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the May 8 presidential runoff election. `` We are in a position of choosing between the bad and the worst,'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> told 30,000 of his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> followers in the Tuileries Gardens in the heart of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on Sunday. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, who ran on an anti-immigration, `` French first'' platform, was eliminated along with six other candidates in first-round voting April 24, but his surprisingly strong showing means his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> followers could influence the outcome of the runoff. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> called the runoff vote on May 8 `` a formality'' _ the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mitterrand </ORGANIZATION> is widely considered a cinch to win. The right-wing candidate told his supporters to organize for the future. `` Once the people of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> are informed, we will be the majority,'' he said. Hundreds of riot police sealed off the area, fearing clashes with tens of thousands of unionists protesting <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> in countermarches. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> called his rally to honor May Day and <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Arc, advancing her traditional feast day by a week because of the May 8 election. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> has appropriated <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Arc as a National Front symbol. Supporters first marched through the center of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, then moved