<HEAD>Japanese Stocks Close At Record High; Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices rose across the board today in the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> while the dollar closed stronger. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the market's main barometer, closed at a record high of 27,669.72, or 160.18 points higher than Saturday's close. Volume was estimated at a moderate 900 million shares. Traders said electronics shares, such as <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>, were rising. `` Many institutional investors are on vacation so today's bullishness is largely caused by private investors,'' said a broker at a major Japanese securities firm `` They -LRB- private investors -RRB- are expecting share prices to soar after Golden Week. So, they want to make sure they buy shares beforehand,'' said the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity. Golden Week is the seven-day stretch that began Friday in which <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> celebrates four national holidays. The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market was closed Friday and all banks, financial institutions, markets and most businesses will be closed Tuesday through Thursday for the holidays. `` The major shift will show up after the holiday,'' the broker added. Meanwhile, the dollar also rose to close the day's dealings at 125.33 yen, up 0.51 yen from Thursday's close of 124.82 yen. `` The general trend is the strong dollar, but there are hardly any major moves at all,'' said <PERSON> Hiroaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Shukuzawa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The market saw recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators as favorable and the dollar regained the losses it suffered after the poor showings of the last month's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures.''
