<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode In Barcelona; 16 Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two bombs exploded early today in this northeastern port city, injuring 16 people, two of them seriously. A separatist group told a local newspaper it had planted the bombs. Police said one bomb placed near a window of a branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> exploded at 2:05 a.m. -LRB- 8:05 p.m. EDT Sunday -RRB- and shattered the bank's windows. Soon after authorities arrived, a second bomb with more than four pounds of shrapnel exploded in a nearby garbage container, injuring 16 people. Two of them, a national policeman and a paramilitary civil guard, were hospitalized with serious leg injuries. The other 14, including four firemen and ten civilians, were treated for cuts at a local hospital and released. The group Free Land, which supports independence for the four-province region of <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION>, of which <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> is the capital, took responsibility for the two blasts in a telephone call to the local Avui newspaper. The group has claimed responsibility for several attacks in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>, including a March 17 explosion at the British Consulate, a bomb blast outside the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> last October and two attacks on American businesses in 1987.
