<ORGANIZATION> ATF </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> turned up evidence that the bombings were retaliatiory. <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> is about 25 miles north of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Those arrested include <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON>, age unknown, of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, identified by authorities as the <ORGANIZATION> Bandidos </ORGANIZATION>' national president; <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmick </PERSON>, 44, of <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>, national vice president; and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pruett </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Mansfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, national secretary-treasurer. <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said all face federal explosives and related conspiracy charges and some may face further charges. The maximum federal penalty for receiving or possessing destructive devices is 10 years imprisonment and a $ 250,000 fine on each count. The maximum penalty for the conspirarcy charge is five years and a $ 250,000 fine.
