<HEAD>San Francisco Starts Water Rationing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New water rules have started for <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s 750,000 customers, but it will be at least two weeks before residents find out how much water they will be alloted without penalty. `` I would encourage -LRB- residents -RRB- to start saving water now and not panic until they see how much they will get,'' said city Water Department Manager <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>. Eventual penalties could include higher rates. The water rationing plan that has a goal of a 25 percent cutback in useage started on Sunday, a day of dazzling spring sunshine. The water rules adopted last week by the city's <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> prohibits hosing down sidewalks, using hoses without shutoff valves to wash cars, operating decorative fountains and automatic service of water to restaurant customers. The water-conservation regulations are the first for <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> since the 1976-77 drought. The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> voted 4-to-0 for the rationing plan on Thursday, joining other <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> regulators who have moved to curtail water use in homes, businesses and on farms. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> received about three inches less rainfall than normal this season. It gets its water from the snow-fed Hetch Hetchy system in Yosesmite National Park, where for the second straight year the snow pack has been far below normal.
