<HEAD>March Gain Biggest in Almost a Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending, powered by a big gain in government projects, shot up 1.5 percent in March, the biggest increase in almost a year. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that construction spending rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 401.8 billion in March following a 0.4 percent increase in February. The March advance was the biggest since a 2 percent gain in April 1987 and reflected increases in all of the major categories. The advance was led by a 5.4 percent surge in spending on government building projects, which climbed to an annual rate of $ 82.3 billion, 8.1 percent higher than a year ago. Highway construction, the biggest single government category, posted a 7 percent increase to an annual rate of $ 27.6 billion. Residential construction rose 0.8 percent in March to an annual rate of $ 191.4 billion as a 2 percent increase in single-family construction was nearly offset by a 3.6 percent decline in multi-family construction. Non-residential construction edged up 0.3 percent to an annaul rate of $ 92.3 billion with industrial construction, office building and hotel construction all recording gains. The February and March increases followed declines of 2.3 percent in January and 0.02 percent in December. Analysts are looking for only moderate strength in construction this year because of widespread over-building of offices and apartments.
