RGANIZATION> would refer the case to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for criminal prosecution. `` We do not believe that requiring the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> to make such a statement will unduly restrict the service's summonsing authority or impede enforcement of summonses,'' the appeals court said. But administration lawyers said the ruling could hinder <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> treaty obligations and impair the ability of investigators here to obtain foreign financial records. The ruling `` requires a treaty partner's tax investigation to meet standards grounded in domestic policies that have no application in the treaty partner's jurisdiction,'' the government's appeal said. `` It unnecessarily hinders investigations that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has pledged by treaty to assist and that are entirely proper under the laws of the treaty partner,'' the appeal added. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has such tax treaties with 31 foreign governments and also exchanges information under other agreements reached with <LOCATION> Carribean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> nations. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, 87-1064.
