<HEAD>Sharansky Leads Immigrants' Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Soviet emigres applauded <PERSON> Natan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> when they elected him chairman of a group of fellow former Soviet refuseniks that plans to challenge <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s immigration policies `` The recent arrival of a few thousand immigrants showed how bad the immigrant absorption system is,'' <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said at the meeting Sunday. `` How can we talk about attracting tens of thousands of immigrants to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> when we ca n't even deal with the few thousand who came last year?'' The 40-year-old human rights activist, who spent nine years in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> labor camps, conducted a three-week campaign to unite about 20 groups representing Soviet Jews into an umbrella lobbying forum. About 400 activists at the meeting spoke in Russian and proudly displayed round blue badges designating them as delegates. There are about 200,000 former Soviet Jews in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said he wants to set up a private fund to provide low-interest housing loans for immigrants and create a company that immigrants can go to for help in building low-cost housing. He also proposed an employment agency to help find work for immigrants and clubs to help immigrants adjust to life in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said American Jewish organizations are ready to donate funds directly to the immigrants on condition that they speak with a single voice. His attempt to unite the emigres is not the first in the 19 years of Soviet Jewish emigration. Others have ended in failure, among them an all-Soviet Jewish party that did not gather the necessary votes to win a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> seat. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> has the support of many activists and has succeeded in bypassing political differences by declaring his forum a non-political, non-affiliated group. `` We shall try to speak in one voice about the issues we agree upon without involving political arguments,'' he said. But he dismissed the notion that his movement may become a political party. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> played a similar role among Soviet Jews refused permission to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the 1970s. The best known Soviet dissident after <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, he was arrested in 1977, convicted of being a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy and sentenced to 13 years in Soviet prisons. He and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> denied he was a spy. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> was released in February 1986 and came to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to meet his wife <PERSON> Avital </PERSON>, who left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> a day after they were married in 1974. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> was seen as a prize for political parties, but he has called <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> politics `` nightmarish.'' `` For a long time I was very cautious about getting involved,'' he said. `` But now it's time to unite.'' Others at the meeting expressed concern about the high number of Soviet Jewish `` dropouts,'' Jews who decided to settle in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or West European countries instead of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Of more than 8,000 Jews permitted to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1987, only 20 percent settled in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. In April, 1,088 Jews left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and only 180 came to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> reports said.
