Journal's lawyers said the lack of permission was illegal. Federal law requires the solicitor general, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s top-ranking courtroom lawyer, to file virtually all <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeals for the government unless he authorizes someone else to do so. Just why <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> was not authorized by Solicitor General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fried </PERSON> to file the appeal was not explained in briefs submitted to the justices. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported that sources close to the case `` blame the solicitor general's office, which, they say, showed little interest in the case despite efforts by the special prosecutor to maintain contact.'' Writing for the court today, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said, `` Absent a proper representative of the government as a petitioner in this criminal prosecution, jurisdiction is lacking and the -LRB- appeal -RRB- heretofore granted is now dismissed.'' Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> dissented. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not participate in the case, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 87-65.
