<HEAD>Court Refsues to Let States Tax Some Pension Fund Income in
Vermont Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to let states tax pension fund income from investments in federal government securities. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials who said they should be allowed to tax the income after it is distributed to retirees. The <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last December upheld a ruling by a state judge who said the pension fund money is tax-exempt. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Mathhew </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ruled that interest on federal obligations _ such as short-term government borrowing _ is immune from state taxation even when the income is passed on by a pension fund to a retired investor. `` In practical operation, the tax in question was in fact a state tax on interest derived from federal obligations,'' <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> said. The fact that pension money was passed on to someone other than the fund itself does not eliminate the exemption enjoyed by investments in federal securities, he said. The judge rejected arguments by state officials that interest on a government security is exempt `` only in the hands of the original recipient unless there is a specific federal statute to pass through the tax-exempt character of such income.'' <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> ruled in favor of <PERSON> Loren </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keys </PERSON>, who when he retired in 1981 received a lump-sum distribution of $ 141,000 from a savings plan in which he had invested. The money included $ 35,000 in interest on federal securities. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials said Keys owed an additional tax of $ 1,246 on the income from the government obligations. The court rulings in Keys' favor meant he received a tax refund of $ 203 plus interest. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials said a lot more was at stake. They said the state court rulings could force them to examine the source of payments from pension and mutual funds, corporate dividends and even bank deposit interest and then eliminate from the state's tax base any income traced to investments in federal obligations. The case is <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> vs. Keys, 87-1583.
