<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers went on strike today at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, birthplace of the Solidarity independent trade movement, government and opposition spokesmen said. Government spokesman <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Augustynowicz </PERSON> said he did not know how many shipyard workers were taking part in the strike. It followed an appeal by Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> on Sunday for a `` day of action'' to support striking steelworkers in southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. A banner at the shipyard gate said `` Sit-In Strike,'' said <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Gwiazda </PERSON>, a local Solidarity leader in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, speaking by telephone. He said the strike began between 1:30 p.m. and 2:30 p.m. The strike was proclaimed in all departments of the shipyard and at least 3,000 people were participating, according to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize laureate who is employed as an electrician at the plant. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s remarks were reported by <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, a senior Solidarity adviser in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. Also today workers at an electronics factory in southwest <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> ended a one-day work stoppage after they obtained a promise for a $ 15 a month pay increase and possible further increases later in the year, opposition spokesmen said. The work stoppage at the Dolmel electronics plant in Wroclaw involved about about half of the plant's 3,500 workers, said opposition and government spokesmen. At a rally held at 2 p.m., workers were told that management promised the raise after two hours' negotiations, said <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinior </PERSON>, a Wroclaw Solidarity leader at the plant. The workers then decided to return to work Tuesday, he said. In <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, authorities locked the gates to the medieval <ORGANIZATION> Jagiellonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> after students scheduled a rally there in support of the striking steelworkers. Despite heavy police presence, dozens of students gathered briefly at two locations in the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> with banners and leaflets, said <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Surdy </PERSON>, a spokesman for the strike. Police detained 10 people, he said. Sunday, thousands of people heeded Solidarity's call for a national day of protest and scores of demonstrators were arrested in clashes with police in at least 19 cities. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said 90 people were detained during the May Day protests. Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON> said authorities detained at least 200 people. There were scattered reports of injuries but figures were not available. Meanwhile, steelworkers striking for a seventh day near <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> awaited an answer to a request for negotiations with the deputy prime minister in charge of the economy. A secretary to Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Zdzislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadowski </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s economic and planning chief had not received a letter sent Sunday by striking steelworkers. The letter invited <PERSON> Sadowski </PERSON> to negotiate with them at the Lenin steelworks in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>. A strike committee at the plant says it represents 16,000 of the plant's 32,000 employees and is demanding recognition of their union rights and a 50 percent raise on the average salary of $ 105 a month. Management said that fewer than 1,000 strikers were at the Nowa Huta plant Sunday. In Polish strikes, workers come to the plant during their scheduled shifts but do no work. Urban said at least 12,000 people took part in illegal demonstrations Sunday. Reports from witnesses and opposition spokesmen put the number at more than 30,000. The demonstrations followed a week of strikes and the worst labor unrest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the communist government suspended Solidarity in December 1981. It later outlawed the trade federation. Solidarity had called for the demonstrations to protest a lack of union freedom and the government's austerity policy which has caused prices to rise by 42 percent recently. <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON>, the Solidarity spokesman who kept track of arrests, complained of `` exceptional brutality'' by police in <LOCATION> Wroclaw </LOCATION>. He said 84 demonstrators were detained there and claimed that that even passive protesters were repeatedly beaten. In <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> on Sunday, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told 6,000 supporters they must support strikers at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> steel mill. `` I demand from you solidarity with <PERSON> Nowa </PERSON> <PERSON> Huta </PERSON> tomorrow, in your shipyards, in your ports and in your factories. I want it to be effective. Show me tomorrow what you can do,'' he declared. After the rally, police with clubs attacked 500 militants who tried to march through <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. During the 40-minute melee, protesters hurled rocks and police beat demonstrators. At least four people were seen bleeding. Dozens were herded into police vans. The state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said more than 9 million people attended official May Day ceremonies nationwide.
