<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered further lower court hearings to determine whether a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> man accused of helping Nazis kill more than 2,000 Jews in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> should be stripped of his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship. By a 6-2 ruling, the court set aside a lower court ruling that revoked the citizenship of 71-year-old <PERSON> Juozas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON>, a retired dental technician from <LOCATION> Clifton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The decision means at least a temporary postponement in the government's likely effort to deport <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON>. The justices also provided some guidelines for determining when the government may strip the citizenship of those accused of lying to gain entry to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and to win citizenship. Revoking citizenship _ a process called denaturalization _ is a preliminary step leading to deportation. Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, in his opinion for the court, said citizens generally may be denaturalized if their alleged misstatements or concealments of facts `` had a natural tendency'' to influence decisions by immigration officials. Moreover, <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said another provision of immigration law permits denaturalization if the misstatements demonstrate lack of good moral character. The court ordered the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON>' case in light of the standards the justices outlined today. The 3rd Circuit court stripped <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> of his citizenship in 1986, clearing the way for his likely deportation. <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> has lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1948 and became a citizen in 1954. The government said he lived in <LOCATION> Kedainiai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, in 1941 when <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s Nazi forces invaded that area, and that he aided in atrocities against Lithuanian Jews. Government lawyers said <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON>, as a member of a miltiary organization known as <LOCATION> Sauliai </LOCATION>, helped force more than 2,000 Jewish men, women and children to undress and walk into ditches, where they were shot. The 3rd Circuit court had ruled that <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> made `` material misrepresentations'' when applying for entry into this country and when applying for citizenship. <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON>' lawyers said the alleged lies _ mispresentations about his age and place of birth _ were not significant enough to cost him his citizenship. Government officials said <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> also lied about where he lived during World War II in an effort to conceal his true identity. Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said in a dissenting opinion that they would uphold the 3rd Circuit court ruling stripping <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> of his citizenship. The case is <PERSON> Kungys </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 86-228.
