<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sightseeing helicopter that crashed into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, killing a Japanese businessman and injuring the four other people aboard, fell out of the sky `` like a stone,'' a survivor says. The Bell 206-B Jet Ranger plunged 1,400 feet into the river Sunday minutes before it was to land. It quickly sank to a depth of 35 feet in the 40-degree water. The 22-year-old pilot had been trying to make an emergency landing and had radioed that the helicopter was experiencing `` performance difficulties,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempster </PERSON>, whose company owns the aircraft <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghiorsi </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office, said the aircraft was taken to Island Helicopter's <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> base for a mechanical investigation. Passenger <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelikan </PERSON> said he heard a `` loud, whistling noise,'' then the helicopter fell `` like a stone into the water.'' The pilot had activated emergency flotation pontoons, but they apparently separated from the craft on impact, <PERSON> Dempster </PERSON> said. The cabin darkened and filled with water, <PERSON> Pelikan </PERSON> said. `` I could n't open the seat belt,'' the 55-year-old West German businessman said. `` After about 45 seconds, I slipped out of the safety belt and found a hole in the door, perhaps it was a window. I do not know. I could not see.'' <PERSON> Pelikan </PERSON>, the pilot and two other passengers who made their way to surface were pulled out of the water by police. They were not seriously hurt. A police scuba