<HEAD>Race Car Accident Kills One Spectator, Injures Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A witness said a stuck throttle may have caused a race car to spin out of control, killing one person and injuring five at the state fairgrounds. `` There was general chaos, a lot of dust, screaming and running,'' <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, who was taking pictures at the event, said Sunday. `` The driver walked away from the accident in tears.'' State Police Trooper <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Capitano </PERSON> said the car, equipped with large wheels, hit spectators who were watching the `` mud bog'' event of the General Tire 4-Wheel and Off-Road Jamboree Spring Nationals. `` The vehicle going through the mud bog lost control and went through a fence that was 350 feet from the end of the bog, and hit spectators who were 95 feet back of the fence,'' <PERSON> Capitano </PERSON> said. `` He just could n't stop. We do n't know if something mechanical broke or what. We're investigating,'' he said. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said that when the car got out of the mud bog it made a loud noise as though the throttle was stuck. The car crashed sideways through a wire and wood fence that was erected for crowd control, then `` rocketed'' toward a group of 30 to 50 spectators at a high rate of speed, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. The mud bog is a heavily watered route, 200 feet long, that includes steep hills. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Huntley </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Moline </LOCATION>, died of massive multiple injuries, said <LOCATION> Sangamon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Richter </PERSON>. <PERSON> Huntley </PERSON> was apparently run over by the car, <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luber </PERSON>, 9, of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> was in critical condition today at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </O