<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Productivity     05-02 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Productivity,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Efficiency Gain Nearly Reverses Previous Quarter's Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The efficiency of the nation's businesses in churning out goods and services improved at an annual rate of 0.9 percent in the first quarter of 1988, nearly reversing a deterioration of 1 percent in the last three months of 1987, the government said today. Despite an increase of nearly a million new jobs from January through March, non-farm businesses raised the total number of hours worked by only 1.7 percent while achieving a 2.7 percent increase in output. And for the first time since late 1986, workers overall are keeping up with inflation, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. Wages and benefits increased at an annual rate of 3.4 percent in the first quarter, raising the labor costs associated with each service or product by 2.4 percent. Those labor costs had skyrocketed at an annual rate of 4.5 percent in the final quarter of 1987 on a massive employment surge. However, after taking inflation into account _ as measured by relative changes in total output and prices _ the wage gains yielded not a penny more of purchasing power. The 0.9 percent improvement in productivity for non-farm businesses, which are responsible for about three-fourths of the nation's economic activity, is only slightly ahead of the 0.8 percent increase for all of 1987. Earlier figures had shown a 0.3 percent increase in the fourth quarter of last year, but those were revised in today's report to a 1 percent deterioration. Manufacturing, which still accounts for about one-fourth of the country's gross national product, continued to lead the effort in restoring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness. Manufacturers' productivity increased at an annual rate of 2.9 percent in the first quarter with a 4.3 percent increase in output on only a 1.3 percent increase in the number of hours worked in the nation's factories. For the first time since early 1986, factory workers actually kept ahead of inflation. Nominal wage gains averaging 3.9 percent annually in the first quarter _ the biggest jump in about three years _ increased the purchasing power of manufacturing employees by one-half of 1 percent after dropping 2.2 percent in 1987. It also raised the labor costs associated with each item coming off the assembly lines by 1 percent, compared with a nearly 2 percent drop in labor costs in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
