<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four senators who hold sway over <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spending say they will not authorize a $ 700 million scheme to lease an unmanned robot space factory from the private developers who would build and own it. In a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the senators said that neither the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration nor <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has done the studies to justify such an expenditure. They directed the space agency to contract with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> to `` undertake a thorough and independent review'' to be completed by next March. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed that the government agree in advance to lease 70 percent of the so-called Commercially Developed Space Facility at $ 140 million a year for five years. The private facility would be carried into orbit by the space shuttle and revisited periodically by astronauts who would service the factory and bring back its products. `` The committee feels that a $ 700 million budget commitment, especially in these times of severe budget constraints, should be based on a detailed assessment of the nation's microgravity research requirements and capabilities,'' the senators told <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>. The letter, dated last Thursday, was signed by the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>; the panel's ranking Republican, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, and by senators <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, the chairman and ranking <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> member of the space subcommittee The administration has sought the facility, which could be ready for launch in the next decade, as an interim facility to be used until the proposed manned space station is in orbit in the mid - to late-1990s
