<HEAD>Vietnam Asks For Aid As It Heads Into Another Year of Bad Harvests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is asking for urgent assistance from the West because its staple crop, rice, is being ravaged by bad weather, disease and insects. Top Vietnamese government officials told representatives of foreign embassies and relief agencies on April 14 that these same problems had caused a shortfall of more than 1.6 million tons of foodgrain last year. According to a Western diplomat who attended the meeting in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, the Vietnamese said there was a risk of famine in some provinces and that some villages in the northern part of the country had n't had rice for weeks. Two days before the meeting, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s official domestic radio said the first crop of 1988 was developing poorly because of lack of sunlight in the first three months. Twenty percent of the cultivated area can be rated poor, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanoi </ORGANIZATION> said in a broadcast monitored in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. The broadcast said nearly 74,130 acres were affected by insects and diseases and 247,000 acres by root suffocation disease. Another 321,100 acres lacked sufficient water, and the water level of ponds, lakes and reservoirs has dropped 6.5 to 19.5 feet compared with previous years, it said. Storms and typhoons also are expected to take their annual heavy toll on crops after the rainy season arrives in a few months. Communist-ruled <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, one of the world's poorest nations, annually suffers from a combination of stagnant food production and high population growth. The new pragmatic leadership has stressed reforms based on material incentives to try to boost agricultural production. Western relief officials interviewed last year said there were no signs of starvation on any significant scale among the country's 63 million people, but that there was widespread and serious malnutrition, especially among children In the April 14 meeting, the Vietnamese asked for insecticide and fertilizer which the Western diplomat estimated would cost $ 100 million. He said he doubted the international community would provide the full amount. On April 26, <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas fighting Vietnamese troops occupying <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> said the West should exploit <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s food plight by increasing pressure for a Vietnamese pullout. `` If aid is given ... it would be like a transfusion of fresh blood into the body of a blood-starved <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> writhing in its death throes, thus reviving it and enabling it to carry on its war of aggression in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' a guerrilla radio broadcast said. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the strongest of three anti-Vietnamese guerrilla groups, massacred millions of people when it ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> from 1975 until 1978, when the Vietnamese invaded.
