<FIRST>r w AM-IndianEducation     05-02 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Education,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>BIA Seeking Advice from Indian Parents on Upgrading Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, concerned about the weak education its schools are delivering, is asking Indians how it should strengthen the instruction of their children. A new report from the bureau documenting test scores worse than those of 79 percent of the nation's students calls on tribal school boards, councils and others to consider an improvement strategy emphasizing strong principals held accountable for results. Of the bureau districts, what it calls `` agencies,'' only one showed children scoring above the national median for their grade. Tribal leaders and school boards have had access to their own scores before. But the new report commissioned by <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Swimmer </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary for Indian affairs, provides the first opportunity for one tribe or area to compare its standing with another, said an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who discussed the document on condition of anonymity. The authors conceded that it will be difficult to install new leaders and revitalizing a system that appears too often to be going through the motions. Calling the system `` in dire need of improvment,'' the report said: `` It is no secret that <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> education is today an organization lacking in a sense of direction.'' `` Its most productive members often feel that any successes they achieve occur despite the system, rather than with its support. `` Collegiality, the act of putting aside vested interests and working for the good of the whole, is found in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s best educational institutions but is often missing in the <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> system, where administrators are sometimes more interested in shoring up and expanding their administrative domain.'' Drawing on research findings being promoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, the report said: `` It is the principal above all who needs to insist on high standards of achievement for students and teachers and to communicate the firm expectation that these standards will be met. Some <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> teachers seem to begin with the expectation that their students will do poorly.'' The bureau educates 37,917 Indian students, about 10 percent of the nation's young Indians and about as many pupils as the public schools of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. About 30 percent attend boarding schools and about 30 percent are in schools run by tribes under contract with the bureau. Few of the students even approached national averages on standard tests administered in the 1985-1986 school year. The highest scores appeared in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s Northern Pueblo agency, where 27 second-graders averaged in the 52nd percentile. This means they did better than 52 percent of all students taking the test. The <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> agency, also in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, showed an average in the 46th percentile for its 63 second-graders, and schools not affiliated with an agency in the eastern states showed 73 sixth-graders in the 49th percentile. The worst scores were recorded in the <LOCATION> Chinle </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, where 202 fourth-graders and 154 fifth-graders, mostly from rural <LOCATION> Navajo </LOCATION> families, wound up in the 7th percentile. The report highlights some success stories but says the system needs a systematic way of spreading knowledge of successes to other areas. For instance, the Dilcon and <LOCATION> Chuska </LOCATION> boarding schools for Navajo in the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Defiance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, district use a special curriculum requiring students to write something every day. Their eighth-graders do well, with <PERSON> Dilcon </PERSON>'s two months ahead of the national average and <LOCATION> Chuska </LOCATION>'s a year above the bureau average, though a year behind the nation. Because of the isolation of the schools, administrative demands, pay falling behind the public schools and other reasons, the bureau system has an annual turnover rate of 33 percent per year among principals and 20 percent among all professionals. Among other recommendations, the report calls for consideration of education loans for prospective teachers, with a larger fraction forgiven the longer the teacher stays in the system; for recruiting retired people with valuable knowledge who might like a second career; and for easing the requirement that Indians be given preference as principals.
