 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales abroad could jump by $ 3.3 billion, to more than $ 15 billion this year, with much of the increase going to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today. But <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the Times report was misleading because a confidential report on which the story was based does not reflect anticipated sales. He said it considers only sales which are `` eligible'' for approval during the calendar year. Since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law requires inclusion of all sales that might be approved, many of which will not take place, `` it would be wrong to characterize the report in any way as a sales plan or to attribute any significance to changes in dollar amounts from one year to another,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. The report cited by the Times, sent by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, lists potential sales to 33 countries. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would get $ 3.6 billion worth of arms and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> $ 2.7 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said. The request gives more attention to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> region than requests of previous years, with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration asking for advanced arms and equipment for <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> to counter threats from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the newspaper said. Elsewhere, one of the biggest possible purchasers is <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, with a potential $ 3.3 billion in arms, the report said. The president is required to submit an arms sale proposal to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> each year, but the master list has rarely become public. In the last fiscal year, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> delivered $ 11.7 billion in military equipment and services to foreign governments and $ 2 billion more was sold directly by manufacturers, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Arms sales abroad peaked in 1982 at $ 17.7 billion. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> was the biggest gainer this year, having bought $ 378 million last year, the Times said. Most of that was in tanks, it said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would receive nearly $ 2.8 million worth of helicopters and F-16 jet fighters under the proposal, the newspaper said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is listed as a potential buyer of $ 797 million in equipment this year, compared with $ 138 million last year. Military sales to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> would decline to $ 45 million from $ 108 million, according to the Times.
