<HEAD>Court Says Retailers' Agreements Don't Always Violate Antitrust
Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Removes penultimate graf, The justices, which extraneous.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said today a manufacturer does not always violate federal antitrust law when agreeing with one retailer to stop doing business with another who sells at discount prices. The justices, by a 6-2 vote, said such a `` vertical restraint'' imposed by a manufacturer on a retailer becomes illegal only when `` it includes some agreement on price or price levels.'' The decision, a significant one for antitrust law, is a victory for <ORGANIZATION> Sharp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and a setback for a former <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> retailer of Sharp calculators. <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, owned and operated by <PERSON> Kelton </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrensberger </PERSON>, was the exclusive retailer of Sharp calculators in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> from 1968 to 1972. During that period, <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> became dissatisfied with <ORGANIZATION> BEC </ORGANIZATION>'s performance <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> contended that it was unhappy with <ORGANIZATION> BEC </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to meet sales quotas but a federal jury found that <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> was dissatisfied with <ORGANIZATION> BEC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of selling calculators at prices lower than those suggested by <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>. Sharp in 1972 appointed <PERSON> Hartwell </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> as a second retailer of its calculators in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, and in 1973 terminated <ORGANIZATION> BEC </ORGANIZATION>'s dealership. <PERSON> Hartwell </PERSON> had told <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> that it o the best possible job at home before expanding coverage elsewhere, he said. <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON>, who took over the family newspaper business when he was 27, has focused on buying newspapers and turning them around by modernizing and streamlining their operations and targeting their markets. `` Lean, capable management is at the heart of all successful companies,'' said <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON>, whose company has a 1988 revenue projection of $ 706 million with an operating cash flow of about $ 180 million. <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> said one of his corporate goals is to take advantage of opportunities in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries and eventually to turn the company into an American-owned international publishing company.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Judge Bans Press In Surrogate Case</HEAD>
<TEXT>
