<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> BRUSSELS </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> _ Five parties reached agreement Monday on forming a new government, which would end an impasse that began when the last coalition fell in a language dispute Oct. 19. <PERSON> Wilfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Martens </PERSON>, prime minister of the last government and now serving as caretaker, also would lead the new coalition. <PERSON> Jean-Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Dehaene </PERSON>, a Dutch-speaking Christian Democrat who spent more than four months negotiating an accord, said he expected approval at meetings of the five parties Thursday. Involved are the <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> - and French-speaking wings of the Socialists and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and the nationalist, Dutch-speaking Volksunie Keeping <PERSON> Martens </PERSON> as head of the 35th Belgian government since World War II `` is the best guarantee for continued stability,'' <PERSON> Dehaene </PERSON> told reporters. He said the coalition should be installed `` within three weeks.'' It will continue the previous center-right administration's economic austerity program, including tax reform and reductions in public spending, he said `` The most immediate problems to which government policies must respond are those of employment and the budget,'' he said. The <PERSON> Martens </PERSON> coalition dissolved Oct. 19 in a linguistic dispute between wings of both his <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and conservative coalition parties from <LOCATION> Flanders </LOCATION>, the Dutch-speaking northern half of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Wallonia </LOCATION>, where the language is French. In the Dec. 13 elections, the government parties won only 110 of the 212 Parliament seats, a loss of five, and negotiations on forming a new government have continued since. If the five-party coalition comes together it will control 150 sea