<HEAD>Hall Of Fame To Feature Famous North Dakotans</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It has <PERSON> Angie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> scripts, a <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Vee </PERSON> sweater and a replica of the bubble machine that became a trademark of bandleader <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Welk </PERSON>. But the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fame </ORGANIZATION>, despite years of effort, is still short of the money it needs to display its exhibits to the public. The hall, conceived as a way of recognizing prominent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakotans </LOCATION> in fields of endeavor ranging from dairy production to sportswriting, resembles nothing so much as the cluttered attic of an eccentric relative. It takes up most of a columned office building north of the state Capitol, but it's not officially open and a visitor is greeted by an expanse of empty floor space. Piles of logs, stacks of bricks and bags of dried leaves rest in one corner. A potbellied iron stove stands near an old-fashioned white porcelain sink. A 1950s-style malt shop booth and five <PERSON> Welk </PERSON> bandstands, painted with the <PERSON> Strasburg </PERSON> native's `` LW'' script, sit incongruously in the center of the main display floor. Most of the Hall of Fame's possessions are locked in eight small rooms, from plaques to books to a mannequin dressed in the uniform of former <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vikings </ORGANIZATION> standout <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborn </PERSON>. A life-size cutout of <PERSON> Welk </PERSON>, holding his conductor's baton, stands next to the football player. The white-suited <PERSON> Welk </PERSON> likeness was once stationed on the main floor, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the hall's executive director. But it was moved into a room `` because when I'd come in here, -LRB- if -RRB- it was a bit dark, he'd kind of startle me,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` It is pretty realistic looking.'' Also stashed away are a number of wax dummies, some dressed in Indian garb, that once were the property of the defunct <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Mandan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, a broadcast executive who first thought of the hall of fame idea five years ago, concede its development has been slower than expected. But <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, who has been meeting recently with a number of non-profit groups in an attempt to obtain contributions, said he remained optimistic. `` We're continuing to move ... except it's taking us a little bit longer than we thought,'' <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said. `` At this point, we need to work harder at it. We have been.'' The hall has been adept at publicity, organizing high-profile <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> appearances by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> _ a native of <LOCATION> Kulm </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION> _ and former <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> commentator <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevareid </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> Velva </LOCATION>, several miles southeast of <LOCATION> Minot </LOCATION>. But promoters have been unable to translate the exposure into enough money to put the hall into shape. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> estimates it will take $ 200,000 to $ 250,000 to organize and staff it for a year. So far, the hall has raised $ 10,000 through a car raffle and a small sum from selling memberships, said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. `` We do n't have very much -LRB- money -RRB- at all,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said last week. `` We're just squeaking.'' Once the hall is set up, <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> believes it could draw as many as 90,0