<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 200 people gathered in a central <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> restaurant on May Day to form communist <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s first network of activist groups, a participant said Monday. The Network of Free Initiatives was formed after 45 dissidents issued a petition on March 17 calling for the formation of an umbrella organization of independent political, ecological, religious and youth groups in support of democracy in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. `` We seek to achieve changes in ways already contained in the constitution,'' the participant quoted dissident writer <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiss </PERSON> as telling the Sunday meeting at the <LOCATION> Hagi </LOCATION> restaurant. The participant spoke by telephone from <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity. Speakers at the gathering, which included leading Hungarian dissidents, emphasized that the Network of Free Initiatives wants to work for change by peaceful means. The participants elected about 50 representatives to a council that will lead the new network. In addition to Kiss, they include leading dissident <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON>, Olympic pentathlete <PERSON> Andras </PERSON> <PERSON> Balczo </PERSON>, writer <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Esterhazy </PERSON>, and historian <PERSON> Gyorgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Litvan </PERSON>. Also elected were representatives of a youth group and of a newly formed independent union of intellectuals, as well as members of religious and ecological organizations. The meeting adopted a four-point resolution protesting government attempts to crack down on the Democratic Forum, a loose association of several hundred intellectuals, the participant said. The resolution also protested the recent expulsion of four liberals from the Communist party, the exclusion of independent ecology groups from a government-sponsored environmental organization and the death of Czechoslovak dissident <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wonka </PERSON> in a Czech jail last week, the participant said. Sunday's statement echoed most of the points introduced in the March 17 petition, which called on the communist government to overcome <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s current economic and social crisis by engaging in dialogue `` in good faith'' with representatives of Hungarian society. The statement also called for a multiparty parliamentary democracy in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. The March document, obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, appealed for `` good neighborly relations'' with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> should remain a sovereign nation as well as `` an equal member of the European family of nations.'' The petition has been signed by 726 people since it was issued. In recent months, the number of independent activist initiatives has mushroomed in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Several of these groups have defied police warnings and continued to organize meetings. The participant said the 50-member network council would meet Wednesday night to thrash out a position paper entitled `` There Is a Way Out,'' which reflects the network's views on how to solve <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s current problems. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is burdened by a gross hard currency debt of $ 16 billion, the highest per capita in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. Austerity measures introduced by the communist government this year have meant widespread belt-tightening for the country's 10.6 million citizens.
