<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NENZEL, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crossbreeding between prairie chickens and grouse is common, but one prairie chicken has taken things a step further by courting a brown pickup truck as the object of his affections. He arrived at the J.B. and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> ranch 23 miles south of here in late March and has stayed, probably hoping he can convince the pickup to agree to a mixed marriage of sorts. `` He likes my pickup,'' <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. `` He runs toward it whenever I drive across the meadow, stamps his feet and performs his ritual for me. I have seen a few grouse near where he stays, but he tends to ignore them.'' Prairie chickens `` boom'' and grouse `` dance'' as they gather for their spring courtship rituals, which are common to both species and are similar. Prairie chickens inflate large orange air sacs on their neck, erect tufts of neck feathers and produce a deep resonant `` boom'' that can be heard for nearly a mile in calm weather.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WOODLAND PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the halls of <ORGANIZATION> Woodland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> became a little too gnarly for Principal <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutgen </PERSON>, he thought it was time students gave him a lesson in the slang of the day. `` I'd hear things,'' he said, `` and I'd think, gosh, is that good or bad or indifferent?'' The principal found his answer in `` Slang Struck: A Handbook for Parents To Better Understand What We're Talking About,'' a 137-word, student-compiled guide. The idea for the handbook came from English teacher <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Heintzman </PERSON>. Encouraged by the principal, she tacked a piece of poster board on the classroom wall and invited students to write in and `` keep it clean.'' Included in the handbook are such terms as babe -LRB- nice-looking -RRB-; stud muffin -LRB- nice-looking male -RRB-; majorly -LRB- very, very important -RRB-; sweetness -LRB- special -RRB-; and gnarly -LRB- cool -RRB-. But the new handbook is in danger of obsolescence already. Some of the words in `` Slang Struck'' already have different meanings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
