<HEAD>`Romance Romance,' A New Musical, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds four grafs with what other critics said. No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Romance Romance'' is a hit and a miss. The show, which opened Sunday at the <ORGANIZATION> Helen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hayes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>, is made up of two one-act musicals, a form of song and dance rarely seen on Broadway. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Harnick </PERSON> tried it more than 20 years ago with `` The Apple Tree,'' musical versions of short stories by <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> Feiffer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockton </PERSON>. They had varying degrees of success. So do the creators of `` Romance Romance.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Harman </PERSON>, who supplied the book, lyrics and direction, and <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, who wrote the music, have gone to a short story by <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnitzler </PERSON> and a play by <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> Renard </PERSON> for their double bill. It's the curtain raiser, `` The Little Comedy,'' that proves to be the more agreeable. The witty <PERSON> Schnitzler </PERSON> short story, set in turn-of-the-century <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, adapts well to the stage. The tale is told in the form of letters to old friends. The format is not as confining as one might think because the missives are acted out by the two main characters. The letter writers, <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> and <PERSON> Josefine </PERSON>, are bored, jaded members of the Viennese upper crust. They toss away lovers like yesterday's strudel. For a little excitement, the two of them go slumming and meet in a park. He pretends to be a penniless poet. She becomes a poor shopgirl. Poverty attracts, at least for a while. Reality finally sets in, and both are relieved to discover they are from the same wealthy social set. The two lovers will get married. But do n't expect the union to last, they both say at the fadeout. <PERSON> Harman </PERSON> keeps the slender story spinning and although his rhymes are often predictable, they at least illuminate the characters or advance the tightly focused plot. <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>'s music has the appropriate old world charm, especially a lilting title song. `` The Little Comedy'' is a crisp confection topped with just the right amount of sour cream. But things turn soggy in Act 2, a moist little musical called `` Summer Share.'' The locale is a trendy Hamptons beach house shared by two married couples. <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> is <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>'s best friend, even though they are married to other people. So how long will it be before they have an affair? Well, they think about it for a long time. So do their mates. And so does the audience, left squirming while the two would-be lovers make up their minds. The characters are sketched so skimpily that it's impossible to work up interest in any of them, especially after they keep insisting how wonderful their marriages are. Although `` Summer Share'' claims to be the more modern of the two shows, it is also the more sentimental and shopworn. The evening ends with the characters urging theatergoers to `` cherish your romantic notions.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> is an ingratiating, handsome leading man. He's rakish and debonair in the first musical, pensive and appealing in the second As the unrepentant coquette, <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> is perfection in the first act, but the sappy material defeats her in the second musical. <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoshour </PERSON> are properly morose as the left-out spouses in Act 2. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s modest settings are in keeping with the modest tone of the whole evening, while <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' costumes capture the spirit of both eras. The musicals, originally done last fall at a tiny off-off-Broadway theater, have undergone some reworking in their transfers to the larger <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>. `` Summer Share'' received the biggest rehab, but the fixing did n't do much good. `` Romance Romance'' offers two looks at love, one lively, the other leaden. Stay until intermission and you'll have an entertaining time.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 What other critics said: In the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> said `` ` Romance, Romance,' lately the littlest musical off-off-Broadway, has made it uptown, in a slightly enhanced production that loses nothing of the charm and intelligence of the original ... In a Broadway season so full of pretentiousness, this show is delightfully small scale ...'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> wrote, `` For all its virtues, ` Romance, Romance' is a show that keeps you at a distance ... Ultimately, the material is arch and clever. You do n't feel you're rediscovering simple affection Rather, you feel you're being let in on a joke.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> said, `` Just as the evening is a pair of sketches, the show's joys and disappointments are mixed.'' <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> praised the two leads, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakula </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, but added, `` The sad thing is that the musical _ or at least the music _ does n't really support them.''
</TEXT>
