<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Monday urged the Polish government to negotiate with its labor unions and to refrain from using force against striking workers. `` The current strikes in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> demonstrate more clearly than ever that successful economic reform and recovery require genuine dialogue between the government and society,'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` In our view, such dialogue must allow for the expression of working peoples' concerns and rights.'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> added that `` the use of force ... can not contribute to national reconciliation.'' The Solidarity trade union movement complained of `` exceptional brutality'' by police in clashes with protesters Sunday in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Thousands of Polish workers are striking to back demands for increased pay to offset price hikes of 42 percent caused by the government's austerity program. The week-long work stoppages are described as the worst labor unrest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the communist government suspended Solidarity in December 1981. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> supports the Polish government's economic reform program and is willing to help in its implementation But he added that `` such help is feasible only if the difficult economic changes needed are supported by a broad spectrum of Polish society.'' The reforms that began in 1986 have included a thinning of the government bureaucracy and encouragement of private enterprise. One <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was willing to help <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> _ if agreement is reached between the government and the unions _ by supporting its loan requests to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> owes some $ 40 billion, the largest chunk to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and a `` significant'' sum to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the official said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which is the largest contributor to both institutions, would be willing to support loan programs `` if <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is serious'' about future reforms, said the official, who spoke only on condition he not be named. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> improved its ties with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> after the Polish government released all political prisoners at the end of 1986. Cultural and economic ties were restored, and both countries exchanged ambassadors in March.
