<HEAD>Militants Reject Offer To Trade Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Melanesian separatists rejected an offer Monday by three rightist elected officials to trade places with nearly two dozen police hostages being held in a cave. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ukeiwe </PERSON>, who represents this <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island territory in the French <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, announced at a meeting of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s new regional assembly that he and two <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> members, <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafleur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Nenou </PERSON>, wished to `` take the place of the hostages to bring an end to their ordeal.'' <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, minister for overseas territories in Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s conservative government, praised the offer and said it could bring movement in the stalemated hostage drama. <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Leques </PERSON> ordered all offices, shops, schools and bars closed at 4 p.m. in support of the idea. Even taxi drivers stopped work in the capital, a stronghold of pro-French, anti-independence sentiment. But the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> rejected the offer and repeated its demand for a mediator to negotiate terms for a referendum on independence for the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island territory. `` We want someone who would be representative of the colonial power, who would have authority to commit the colonial power,'' <PERSON> Hnalaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Uregei </PERSON>, a member of the front's political bureau, told a news conference. He said the proposal from the three officials was `` at the same time grotesque, ridiculous and indecent'' and said they knew it would not be taken seriously. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> has become an issue in next Sunday's presidential election between Socialist President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who urges dialogue with the separatists, and <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who calls them a small band of terrorists. A recent opinion poll in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> found 41 percent in favor of independence for the territory, 34 percent opposed and 25 percent giving no opinion. But among those who voted for <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> in the first round April 24, only 24 percent back independence and 58 percent want to keep <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> part of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Ukeiwe, <PERSON> Lafleur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nenou </PERSON> are members of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s rightist party, the Rally for the Republic, and are prominent opponents of the separatist movement. About 43 percent of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s 145,000 people are native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, and many of them favor independence. About 36 percent are Europeans, who generally want to remain part of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The rest are mostly Asian or Polynesian. On April 22, the rebels raided a rural police post on the island of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION>, seized 27 military policemen and killed four others. They released 12 hostages but took eight more, including the head of an anti-terrorism squad and an assistant prosecutor. The remaining hostages are being held in a cave in a remote part of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION>, which lies off the east coast of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s main island, La Grande Terre. The prosecutor and the anti-terrorism squad leader were allowed to leave the cave hideout and ordered to negotiate on behalf of the terrorists, but were old the remaining hostages would be killed if the two did not return. Because of that threat, authorities still consider them hostages for a total of 23. The front, which calls the 23 `` prisoners of war,'' said in a statement Monday that they were `` in good health and well cared-for.''
