<HEAD>U.S. Jewish Conference Schedules Pre-Summit Vigil in Helsinki</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American Jewish leaders said Monday they will hold a religious service and a vigil in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit as a way of drawing attention to the plight of Soviet Jews. The events, organized by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewry </ORGANIZATION>, will take place May 27-28 while President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who is scheduled to fly to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on May 29 for the three-day summit with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, has been invited to the Friday night service at the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> synagogue. Organizers said they did not know if he would attend. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abram </PERSON>, chairman of the national conference, told reporters the activities in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> are designed to impress upon Soviet leaders the conference's commitment to seeing Soviet Jews accorded more freedom. He said his group will continue the campaign `` to free Soviet Jewry so they can emigrate ... and to permit those who wish to remain to live as Jews without any limitations and without any discrimination against them.'' The conference estimates that as many as 400,000 Jews are seeking to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but have been denied exit permits. There are more than 2 million Jews in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which has about one-fifth of the world's Jewish population. Jews have been persecuted for practicing their faith in the state-controlled society and are often discriminated against. Soviet Jews are planning an event in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during the summit, but conference officials refused to provide details, fearing organizers might be subjected to harassment by Soviet officials. When <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a summit last December, supporters of Soviet Jews staged a massive demonstration near the White House. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> attended that rally. <PERSON> Abram </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Maass </PERSON>, head of the conference's <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> task force, also said they want the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to abide by the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Final Act that proclaimed that people have a right to leave a country freely. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other Soviet officials have voiced irritation at the attention the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> focuses on human rights. In recent speeches <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has urged the Soviets to allow more freedom of speech and religion, and his aides say he will revisit that subject in a talk Wednesday in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The conference will hold a day-long `` Summit Action Day for Soviet Jews'' Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is to speak. Also attending will be <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Begun </PERSON>, a mathematician who was allowed to emigrate in January after spending many years in Soviet labor camps. The American Jews say that under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the treatment of Soviet Jews has been mixed. On the one hand, there has been some improvement in cultural life, such as the creation of a Hebrew study group in one region. But the number of Jews allowed to emigrate is still a trickle compared with the 1970s, and some emigration laws have been tightened.
