<HEAD>Not Enough AID Money Going to Third World Women, Studies Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> does n't pay enough attention to women in the Third World, despite their roles in farming and other areas of commerce, two studies say. Reacting to the independent studies, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have introduced a bill they say would redress the situation by requiring the AID office that oversees women in developing nations to spend $ 10 million annually. Last year the office spent about $ 2 million. The bill _ introduced by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Reps. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> in one chamber and Sen. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> in the other _ also would order AID to place women in 50 percent of positions in training programs abroad. `` Much has been said and written about incorporating women in development efforts, but far too little has been done,'' <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said in a joint letter to colleagues. The bill, which has 89 co-sponsors in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, is being promoted by Bread for the World, a Christian group that lobbies against hunger and poverty. That group plans a letter-writing campaign to encourage AID to increase benefits given to women in developing countries, said president <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, the brother of Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill. AID opposes the bill, even though <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, the agency's new director, is `` committed to AID's efforts to integrate women into developing economies,'' spokesman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipson </PERSON> said Although the agency believes more needs to be done for women in developing countries, the legislation would create an additional layer of bureaucracy and cut down on AID's flexibility, he said. Agency officials think the legislation is like `` using an elephant to deal with a fly,'' he said. Moreover, he said that while Americans recognize the importance of women in the Third World, AID officials sometimes run into roadblocks in developing countries where women frequently have inferior status. What prompted congressional interest were two independent studies _ commissioned by AID and completed in 1987 _ that said AID programs often are inattentive to women. `` AID's women in development policy is not being implemented fully or vigorously, and there is little enthusiasm and few incentives for doing so,'' <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a consulting group, wrote in a December report. Unless there is agency-wide acceptance of the policy of incorporating women, it will be `` marginally useful at best,'' the study said. While lip-service is given to the importance of women's roles in development, the policy is not a `` serious concern'' for many AID managers, the study said. Numerous studies have demonstrated the vital role women play in a developing nation's economy. In <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, for instace, it is estimated that women are responsible for growing more than 80 percent of the food consumed in the home. Case studies in <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, for example, show that when there is widespread male migration, women's earnings are the mainstay for subsistence expenditures. Women also play a large role in informal commerce, serving as traders and merchants in countries like <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. In a community in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, women's earning from handicrafts tided families over during a drought. The failure to take women into account can undermine some development projects, according to a report written by <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Carloni </PERSON> for AID in April 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Botswana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> Expansion project was rated highly successful in developing an agricultural training institution. But the project may not ultimately improve the lives of farm families if the extension service continues to bypass female farmers who play a major role in agriculture, the study said. In another project in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, architects focused too narrowly on the domestic role women play, the study said. The women were taught to use a different type of stove designed to reduce deforestation, but were not educated on broader conservation topics.
