<HEAD>Factory Orders Surged 1.6 Percent In March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories registered a surprising 1.6 percent upward surge in March as strong export demand and heavy defense orders reversed weakness in the previous two months, the government reported Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that orders for durable and non-durable goods climbed to $ 216.08 billion, an increase of $ 3.43 billion from the February level. The 1.6 percent advance was the first increase this year after orders had shown no improvement in February and actually fell 0.6 percent in January following a 2 percent December gain. Analysts had expected a much smaller March advance of around 0.3 percent. They said the report showed demand was rebounding following a brief period when businesses cut back to work down a high backlog of unsold goods. At the beginning of the year, economists had been so worried about the big rise in inventories that they were forecasting order cutbacks and job layoffs could topple the country into a recession. But the orders report on Monday, following strong employment gains and big rises in consumer spending, showed that the economy regained its footing in the early part of this year. `` It is clear that we have a stronger economy than people had been expecting. The crash had much less effect than people had feared,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The government reported last week that the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product, rose at a healthy 2.3 percent annual rate from January through March, far better than the recession many had predicted. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION> had boosted its economic forecast for the entire year to show growth of 2.8 percent, very close to the administration's prediction of 2.9 percent GNP growth this year. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfro </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Alphametrics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting firm in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said manufacturing orders should continue growing as stronger growth in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the weaker dollar boosts export demand even more. The administration is counting on rising export demand to account for nearly half of all GNP growth this year. `` We are still a very important high-technology economy, producing goods that the world needs, and the strength in orders reflects that,'' <PERSON> Renfro </PERSON> said. The March increase was particularly surprising in view of the fact that only 10 days ago the government had reported that orders for durable goods, items expected to last more than three years, were unchanged in March. In Monday's report, that was revised to show a healthy 1 percent gain in durable goods, reflecting new-found strength in machinery, steel and transportation. Orders for non-durable goods climbed at an even faster pace, rising by 2.3 percent to $ 100.6 billion. The overall increase of 1.6 percent reflected a big 17.4 percent jump in demand for military equipment, following a 6 percent drop in this volatile category in February. Without the rise in military orders, total orders would have climbed a smaller 1 percent, still the sixth gain in non-defense orders in the past seven months. The key category of non-defense capital goods fell 3.8 percent to $ 32.5 billion, but analysts discounted the setback and said they were still looking for strength as businesses boost spending to expand production facilities to meet rising demand. Orders for transportation equipment climbed 3.4 percent while orders for primary metals such as steel were up an even larger 6.1 percent in March. Shipments of manufactured goods increased 2.6 percent to a record high of $ 214.4 billion following a 0.8 percent February increase.
</TEXT>
