<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> struck back Monday at critics who charge he is too negative about the nation's educational system, saying it has not made sufficient progress in the last five years. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he gave `` a fair amount of praise'' to improvements in a report issued last week on the fifth anniversary of `` A Nation at Risk,'' the devastating analysis issued by his predecessor, <PERSON> Terrel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>. `` We can show some progress since 1983,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` Despite that progress, I can not come candidly before the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people and say that everything's great.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said the five-year update, `` American Education: Making it Work,'' had provoked a firestorm of criticism although `` no one has challenged any facts in it.'' In the report, released last week, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said progress has been too slow and `` we are still at risk.'' He told the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> that the `` educational establishment'' gave him grades of C's and D's on the report, but `` I do n't give a tinker's damn what they give me as long as they get to work improving American education.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said fewer than 2 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students can write a clear, detailed, coherent narrative and only 3 percent of high school seniors scored above 600 on their verbal SATs last year. He said middle-class kids usually can survive the decline of an education system but lower-class children end up losing their only chance for a better life. `` So if I seem a bit edgy at times about improving our education system, there's a good reason,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> told the audience they should go to see the film `` Stand and Deliver'' for an example of how American education can be made to succeed without huge infusions of cash. The movie, based on the true story of <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>, is about an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> calculus teacher who tames a class of inner city Hispanic teen-agers through force of personality. The kids end up learning calculus and going to college. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, often at odds with teachers' groups, said <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON> had never been nominated by anyone for a teacher-of-the-year award. `` Why?'' he asked. `` Because he's an embarrassment. He proves you can do it.''
