<HEAD>Government Work Boosts Construction Spending in March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending surged 1.5 percent in March, the biggest increase in almost a year, as government spending offset weakness in other areas, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The department said construction projects were being built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 401.8 billion in March, following a 0.4 percent increase in February. The March advance, which was the biggest since a 2 percent rise in April 1987, was a bit puzzling to economists, who have been forecasting generally sluggish activity in the building industry this year. `` Construction is doing considerably better than anyone was expecting. It is simply remarkable,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumichrast </PERSON>, an economist and publisher of a construction industry newsletter. The strength last month came in large part from a 5.4 percent boom in government construction projects, which analysts said reflected increased outlays for highway construction that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved last year over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto. In March, the increase of 7 percent pushed highway spending, the largest category in the government sector, to an annual rate of $ 27.6 billion, 16.9 percent higher than a year ago. Residential construction rose a modest 0.8 percent in March to an annual rate of $ 191.4 billion, as a 2 percent increase in single-family construction was largely offset by a 3.6 percent decline in multi-family construction. Non-residential construction edged up 0.3 percent to an annual rate of $ 92.3 billion, with industrial, office building and hotel construction all recording gains. Industrial construction posted a strong 7.7 percent increase, reflecting expansion projects by businesses experiencing high operating rates. The February and March increases in total construction followed declines of 2.3 percent in January and 0.02 percent in December. `` After a period of weakness, construction is coming back, largely because of the strength in the government sector,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said the rise in spending confirmed reports by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that showed jobs have increased by 200,000 over the past two months in the construction industry. Analysts said they were still not looking for much strength in private construction this year because of the high vacancy rates for apartments and office buildings and the continued adverse effects of the 1986 tax overhaul legislation on these types of investments.
