<HEAD>Reagan Says Plant-Closings Provision of Trade Bill a Sure Loser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vowed anew Monday to veto a major revision of trade laws and said a controversial provision requiring advance notification of plant closings was `` like playing Russian roulette with a machine gun.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto promise, in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting, drew loud applause from the audience of about 2,000 people. They also cheered his statement that capital gains taxes should be cut sometime in the future. The trade bill, expected to reach the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> this week, won final congressional approval in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last Thursday on a 63-36 vote, three votes short of the margin needed to overturn a veto. One provision would require all but the smallest businesses to provide a 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The bill specifies exceptions for companies in serious financial trouble. `` The plant-closing restriction is the bill's worst provision, not the only bad one,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. He did not cite any other features he considered objectionable, although the administration has complained about the bill's curbs on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil exports. He said some supporters of the notification provision say it will not hurt, noting that many European countries have similar restrictions. `` Yep, and that's among the reasons for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s poor job performance over the last six years,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` If we had done as poorly, our unemployment rate would be up like theirs, not down from 10.8 percent to 5.5 percent,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` What would organized labor say then?'' `` Anyone who would copy <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in this way is no friend to <LOCATION> American