<HEAD>Artificial Nesting Beach Being Built for Kemp's Ridleys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nursery with an artificial nesting beach is being built at the <ORGANIZATION> Clearwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> with the goal of boosting the population of the imperiled <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> sea turtle. The $ 10,000 project will experiment with a first-of-its-kind beach that includes a gently sloping sand ramp and sea oats, said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellenberger </PERSON>, the center's executive director. The purpose: to encourage female <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> sea turtles to crawl ashore and lay their eggs. Only about 400 to 600 reproducing females of the species remain. Eight <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> turtles, including both sexes, live at the marine center. These 6-year-old turtles are ready to reproduce, and center officials hope they will breed and nest in captivity. <PERSON> Kellenberger </PERSON> said an attempt at using an artificial beach is a new approach. `` We're hoping that if they're confined to an area where they really have no choice but to nest here, then they will,'' he said. The tank will be partially filled with water and the turtles will be placed there together. At one end of the tank will be a beach area created by putting sand on a fiberglass liner atop a wood platform. A gently sloping sand-covered ramp will enable the turtles to crawl ashore and nest there when they are ready. The <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> species was decimated by poachers who waited for the arrival each summer of the egg-laden females at their only natural nesting area on a <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> beach at Rancho Nuevo, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Poachers sought turtle meat, widely considered a delicacy, and eggs. The nesting beach has been protected since 1966, but the turtles have not yet recovered to their former numbers partly because they are frequent victims of shrimpers who unwittingly drown them in their nets. The cream-colored <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s Ridleys are the smallest of the sea turtles, weighing about 100 pounds. They are found throughout the coastal waters of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and often forage in the <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area. Scientists do n't know exactly why the <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s Ridleys females lay their eggs on only one beach or whether enough of them can be persuaded to nest elsewhere.
