<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Face Manslaughter Charges in Death of Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Christian Science couple pleaded innocent Monday to charges that they caused their son's death by failing to seek medical treatment because of their religious beliefs. <PERSON> David </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ginger </PERSON> <PERSON> Twitchell </PERSON>, formerly of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hyde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> section, appeared in <ORGANIZATION> Suffolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on manslaughter charges stemming from the April 8, 1986, death of their 2 -LCB- - year-old son, <PERSON> Robyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Twitchell </PERSON>, dressed in a dark blue leisure suit, and his wife, who wore a lavender pantsuit with lavender-colored plastic flowers in her hair, stood close to each other and held hands as they both entered not guilty pleas before Trial Magistrate <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. A pretrial conference was set for June 1. The Twitchells, who have two other sons, <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON>, 6, and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>, 7 months, were released on their own recognizance. In response to a motion filed by the prosecution, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamlin </PERSON> imposed a gag order on all parties in the case pending a hearing Thursday on the matter. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mundy </PERSON> requested the order for attorneys in the case, complaining about the published remarks made last week by one of the two defense attorneys, <PERSON> Rikki </PERSON> <PERSON> Klieman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mundy </PERSON> said <PERSON> Klieman </PERSON>'s statements violated the canon of ethics and `` could poison the pool of prospective jurors.'' <PERSON> Klieman </PERSON>'s remarks, published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATI