<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSMarrow     05-02 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Marrow,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say AIDS May Hide In Bone Marrow Cells</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The virus that causes AIDS can invade the bone marrow and infect cells there even when the virus can not be detected in blood samples, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> scientist said Monday. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases, a part of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>, said he and other researchers found that the bone marrow, which is the body's blood-making organ, can become a quiet haven for the deadly AIDS virus `` Our study shows that it -LRB- the bone marrow -RRB- can be a reservoir,'' he said. `` It -LRB- the AIDS virus -RRB- can reside in the marrow, but not be detected in the peripheral blood.'' The finding adds to the types of cells in the body known to be attacked by the virus that causes AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome. In addition, the finding demonstrates just how challenging it will be to develop an antiviral drug or vaccine to defeat the AIDS virus, said <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>. In order to effect a cure, some way will have to be found to seek out and destroy the virus wherever it hides. `` It is going to be very difficult to eliminate each and every viral particle in the body,'' said <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, because the virus takes refuge in cell groups and apparently can live there in a latent state for years without causing any clinical signs of infection. The virus, called the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, was first thought to infect only T-lymphocyte cells that have a protein on the cell surface called CD4. Researchers later learned that the virus also could invade some brain cells and another type of blood cell, the monocyte. Now, said <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, researchers have confirmed that the virus also can reside in the cells of the bone marrow. This is important because the bone marrow is the factory that makes the various types of blood cells. In routine blood examinations, the test for AIDS involves a search for antibodies to the virus since the virus itself often is not found in the blood. <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said it is yet to be absolutely confirmed, but there is a suggestion that the HIV lives in a type of bone marrow cell that is the immature form of the monocyte. And unlike the T-lymphocyte, the virus does not kill the bone marrow cell, but reproduces within the cell. Researchers are still trying to understand what causes the latent virus to suddenly start reproducing and become an active infection after living in the body quietly for years. <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said there is some suggestion that the triggering mechanism may be the response of the immune system to other infections. This may start a process that, in effect, turns on the virus. <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> reported on the research during a lecture at a joint meeting of three organizations of physicians and clinical researchers. AIDS is a contagious, fatal disease that kills by attacking the T-cell lymphocytes, a key part in the body's immune system. When the T-cells are killed, the body is unable to protect itself against disease and death usually results from opportunistic infections. The AIDS virus most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons. As of April 21, AIDS had been diagnosed in about 59,500 Americans, of whom more than half, or about 33,000 have died since June 1981, according to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
