<HEAD>Inmates Give Up Hostage and Control of Cell Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inmates freed a guard they held for 17 hours and gave up control of the largest cell block Monday, ending the eighth serious disturbance at <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION> prison in less than two years. The government's Scottish Office said guard <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON>, 25, appeared to be well. He was held in C hall, the largest cellblock, where about 100 inmates barricaded themselves inside. Soon after his release, a fire engine went into the prison to put out a small fire, the office said. It announced two hours after <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON>'s release that the 100 inmates had surrendered a few at a time. `` There has been some damage to C hall, how much remains to be quantified,'' said a spokesman, who in keeping with British practice was not identified by name. How many of the 100 inmates were directly involved in the hostage-taking was not known, the spokesman said. During the siege, convicts had waved a guard's cap from a window and set fire to pieces of what looked like a guard's clothing. <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON> was seized Sunday. Soon afterward banners were hung from a window protesting about the legal system. Guards said prisoners also wanted an investigation of conditions, a better chance at parole and segregation of young prisoners and those awaiting trial. <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION> prison now holds 449 men, 11 over capacity, but the population has gone as high as 600 in recent months. Protests at <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION> since August 1986 include the burning of an entire cellblock; holding of a rooftop by three inmates for 41 hours, ended by an assault squad of six guards; a hunger strike, and destruction of cell furniture. Other protests at Scottish prisons have occurred in <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peterhead </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>. Most British prisons were built in Victorian times and are notoriously overcrowded and unsanitary. About 51,000 people are imprisoned in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, almost 20 percent above capacity and the highest proportion of population in the 12-nation European Economic Community. About 19,000 prisoners are held two and three to cells designed for one.
