<HEAD>Walesa Joins Strike at Lenin Shipyard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-21 UPDATE with steel workers heartened by Gdansk
strike, yard operations at minimum, Nowa Huta strikers may talk
with management. Picks up 22nd graf pvs, Poland's latest ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> proclaimed a strike Monday at the huge <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where Solidarity was born in 1980, in a major escalation of the weeklong labor turmoil in communist <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. It was the fourth strike in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in a week, the worst wave of labor unrest since the government's December 1981 military crackdown on Solidarity. The news heartened steelworkers in southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, who no longer were the country's only workers still on strike. `` We feel better now,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciesielski </PERSON>, a member of the steel strike committee. Authorities were reported mounting a nationwide roundup of regional leaders of Solidarity. A Solidarity communique signed by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and issued late Monday said, `` A strike wave is covering the country. They are not just local conflicts. They are across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> because the cause is the economic crisis and the lack of convincing reform policies that would offer prospects for the future.'' Workers want pay raises of 50-60 percent to balance prices, which have risen 42 percent this year because of reductions in subsidies by the Communist government. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, still works as an electrician at the Baltic coast <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> yard employing 12,000 workers. He did not launch the strike but addressed strikers later and announced his support, according to various activists. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> led the 1980 work stoppage at <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> which shook the communist government to its roots and gave rise to Solidarity, the first independent trade union federation in the Soviet bloc. Solidarity was suppressed and outlawed under martial law. Monday evening, Solidarity's chaplain, the Rev. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, presided in the shipyard at a prayer service attended by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, a newly formed strike committee and hundreds of workers. About 3,000 workers were occupying the yard late Monday, enough to shut down operations, said Solidarity adviser <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>. The shipyard has a payroll of 12,000 workers. The government press office in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> at first confirmed the strike. But on Monday evening government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> called The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and said there was only a rally by several hundred people at the shipyard. `` It would be rather difficult for me to say the entire shipyard is working in that atmosphere but, generally speaking, the shipyard is working,'' he said. <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> said police arrested nine regional representatives on the 13-member <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Two commission members, including <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, were free and whereabouts of two more were a mystery, he said. Union activists said the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> strike began with a march around the shipyard by dozens of workers after a breakfast break. The march grew to 200 people and ended at the main gate. There, while shifts were changing at 2 p.m., the Solidarity activists encouraged workers to strike, union supporters said. `` The strike action ... undoubtedly is in response to <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s call -LRB- on Sunday -RRB- for protest actions in support of the striking <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> steelworkers,'' said <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojciechowicz </PERSON>, a Solidarity activist in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. The workers formed a strike committee led by <PERSON> Alojzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Szablewski </PERSON>, said a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brygida </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, a Solidarity stronghold near the shipyard. Management agreed to talk to the strike committee Tuesday, <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, chairman of the outlawed but still active labor federation, said through spokesmen he stayed off the strike committee to coordinate Solidarity activities nationwide. The strike by thousands of steelworkers at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> steel works in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> entered its eighth day Tuesday. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s latest labor trouble began April 25 with a wildcat action by transit workers in <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION>. It was settled the same day with pay raises of at least 50 percent. Thousands of workers at the <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> heavy machinery plant in southeast <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> struck on Friday and ended the action Saturday after promises of higher pay. About half the 3,500 workers at the Dolmel electronics plant in <LOCATION> Wroclaw </LOCATION>, southwestern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, stopped work from about 10 a.m. Monday to the end of the shift at 2 p.m., government and opposition spokesmen reported. <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinior </PERSON>, a Solidarity leader, said it ended when management promised a raise. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> urged the Polish government to negotiate with workers and declared, `` The use of force ... can not contribute to national reconciliation.'' Police surrounded the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard and checked the papers of people approaching the gates, a witness said. Banners declaring `` Sit-In Strike'' and `` <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shipyard </LOCATION> on Strike'' were draped on the main gate. Police detained <PERSON> Bogdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Solidarity </LOCATION> leader, in nearby <LOCATION> Sopot </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, the Solidarity chaplain. According to <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Gwiazda </PERSON>, a Solidarity leader, the shipyard strikers demand minimum pay of 60,000 zlotys a month -LRB- $ 150 -RRB-, reinstatement of fired union activists, amnesty for strikers and recognition of a local Solidarity chapter. Average monthly pay now is about 45,000 zlotys -LRB- $ 112 -RRB-. In August 1980, employees of one department of the Lenin shipyard stopped work to protest the dismissal of <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Walentynowicz </PERSON>, a crane operator and activist in the free-union movement. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, a little-known union organizer who also had been dismissed, vaulted the shipyard fence and took charge of the strike. In two dramatic weeks, the workers won guarantees for the first independent union in the Soviet bloc and broad social political concessions. Solidarity claimed 10 million members at its height.
