<HEAD>Dalkon Shield Claimants Representatives Differ on Robins
Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Guerry is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some representatives of former <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> users urged rejection Monday of the latest reorganization plan involving <PERSON> A.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>, manufacturer of the defective contraceptive device that injured thousands of women. `` After an agonizing decision-making and education process, we have found that the plan is unfair, inadequate and contrary to the law,'' <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference. However, another representative of the victims, Atlanta-based attorney <PERSON> Guerry </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said the plan offered the best deal yet for the more than 196,000 women harmed by the intrauterine device. The $ 3.2 billion reorganization plan _ the sixth plan developed since <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> filled for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1985 _ is part of the Manhattan-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement to take over the beleaguered company. The $ 3.2 billion plan includes $ 2.3 billion to be put in a trust fund for the victims. The plan was presented in a mailing last week to all claimants against <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>, including the 196,000 former Dalkon Shield users who have injury claims pending against <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> as well as banks and stockholders. All claimants are to mail in ballots by July 11, with the final resolution of the case scheduled for July 18. In order for the plan to be approved under an arrangement set up in March by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> <PER