<HEAD>Strikes End Following Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A two-week national strike over gasoline price increases ended Monday after negotiations between government and unions, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. The strikes had paralyzed medical and banking services. After talks with eight union leaders, the government agreed to labor's main demand that four detained union leaders be freed, Labor Minister <PERSON> Aboubacar </PERSON> <PERSON> Umar </PERSON> said in a statement. He made no mention of a second union demand that there be no further gasoline price increases. There was no immediate comment from union leaders, nor were the names of those being released immediately made available. <PERSON> Umar </PERSON> acknowledged that the rising cost of living in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most populous nation with an estimated 100 million people, was a sensitive issue among workers. Student protests began in the north-central city of <PERSON> Jos </PERSON> on April 11, the day after the government increased gasoline prices by 3 percent. Demonstrations turned violent April 13 when thousands of university students and <PERSON> Jos </PERSON> residents clashed with police, with six people killed. The unrest quickly spread to other campuses around <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and labor unions joined the protest in defiance of government threats. The government raised the price of gasoline and diesel fuel in what was expected to be the first of a series of increases. The action followed <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> recommendations to make gasoline prices higher to help reduce <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>'s $ 1.5 billion budget deficit. Many Nigerians have considered low gasoline prices as their right since the boom days for oil-exporter <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> in the mid-1970s. Even with the increases gas sells for about 40 cents a gallon. The <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> has reported the government was holding many union officials, including the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> and the assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> and Midwives. Last week the news agency reported the president and secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railwaymen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> were arrested, though rail workers did not join the strike. The news agency said 11 union leaders in <LOCATION> Kano </LOCATION> were released on bail Friday. A judge said they could get three years in prison if convicted of taking part in walkouts. The government dismissed thousands of civil servants in the strikes called April 19 involving banks, government and medical services.
