<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has paid nothing to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for six months on the $ 502 million owed to it, the bank announced Monday. As a consequence, the bank's loans to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> have been placed in a `` non-accrual status,'' which means the bank will no longer include on its own statements the interest and other charges due from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> until money is actually received. The bank, owned by 151 countries, is the biggest single source of aid money for the Third World. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the largest shareholder. `` Placing loans in a non-accrual status is an accounting action which does not reduce in any way the country's obligation to the bank or the bank's ability to assist the country in formulating policies to help redress its economic difficulties,'' the announcement said. Last Nov. 30, the bank stopped disbursing loans to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, as it does to any borrowing country whenever payments on earlier loans are more than 75 days overdue. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s financial situation has been deteriorating for almost a year because of the political crisis there, and it's been aggravated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions taken to try to oust strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who was indicted earlier this year in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug-trafficking charges. The situation became critical Feb. 26, the day <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> engineered the ouster of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> for issuing an order firing the general. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has 118 banks, and has been a major Latin American financial center, but the banks have been closed to the public by government order since March 4 because of cash shortages following months-long runs on accounts and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> freeze on Panamanian assets. Some Panamanian and foreign banks reopened April 18 but only to accept deposits.
