<HEAD>AIDS and Anti-Smoking Programs Among Top Items at WHO conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1988 assembly of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> opened Monday and high on the agenda were programs to check the spread of AIDS and an anti-smoking campaign. About 1,200 delegates from <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION>'s 166 member countries will elect a successor to Dr. <PERSON> Halfdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> as director general of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency. Dr. <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakajima </PERSON>, 59, a Japanese specialist in pyschopharmacology, was designated for the post last January by the 31-member Executive Board. Confirmation by the assembly, scheduled for Wednesday, is a virtual certainty. <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON>, head of the agency since 1973, did not seek a fourth five-year term. Delegates at the two-week assembly will consider a proposed zero-growth, two-year budget of $ 639.9 million. Not included in the budget is funding for <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION>'s Special Program on AIDS, which officials have said would require $ 66 million this year. The number of AIDS cases was officially reported last week as exceeding 88,000, but the actual number is known to be much higher. WHO officials have urged further implemtation of the agency's campaign against smoking as `` the major avoidable cause of ill-health. AIDS, acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a fatal disease in which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers. It can be transmitted through sexual contact; transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, or sharing contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes. AIDS can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth.
