<HEAD>Rebels Kill 13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> rebels attacked Moslem settlements in southeastern <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and killed 13 people, military officials said Monday. The slayings raised to 36 the number of deaths blamed on the insurgents in the past week, officials said. The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said two villages in the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tracts </LOCATION> area were raided Sunday night, apparently by the same band of armed rebels. The victims included six women and four children, they said. At least nine people were injured in the attacks. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chakma </ORGANIZATION> tribes, descendants of the <ORGANIZATION> Mongols </ORGANIZATION>, have been seeking an independent homeland since 1974. They say their tribal culture is being overwhelmed by the influx of Moslem settlers from other parts of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. An estimated 4,000 people have died in rebel attacks and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> army actions against the insurgents. An estimated 50,000 tribal members have fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to escape the violence. Military officials said rebels on Sunday attacked <LOCATION> Karmangipuri </LOCATION> village, 2 miles from the Indian border, and killed three women and two children. The rebels fled after soldiers from a nearby camp opened fire, they said. There was no word of injuries to the insurgents. In the second attack, the rebels stormed <LOCATION> Malangipara </LOCATION> village, about 10 miles from the frontier. Eight people, including three women and two children, were killed, the officials said.
