<HEAD>Bank Robber Slain After Threatening Hostages With AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A police sharpshooter killed a gunman holding six people inside a bank on Monday after the man threatened to inject his hostages with blood he said contained the AIDS virus, police said. Police said they got the man drunk so they could get the hostages out safely. The man seized six bank workers during an attempt to rob the branch of <ORGANIZATION> Banorte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Massoro </LOCATION>, about 1,875 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>. Police surrounded the bank after security guards saw a man threatening a teller with a revolver. Police and a journalist negotiated for eight hours with the robber, who said he escaped from <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> prison and was a carrier of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the fatal disease that destroys the body's immune system. The man, who identified himself only as `` <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>,'' was shot after he drank several bottles of beer provided by police, said Officer <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazareno </PERSON>. `` We gave him lots of beer to get him drunk. We hoped that way we'd be able to get the hostages out safely,'' <PERSON> Nazareno </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone. `` We had no choice but to kill him. He was threatening the hostages with a syringe full of blood and a revolver.'' The robber had demanded a getaway car, a second revolver and a rifle before he would free the hostages. He also wanted to be allowed to escape with $ 75,000.
