<HEAD>Sir Hugh Rankin, British Eccentric, Dies at 88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sir <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>, who has died at the age of 88, was an aristocrat turned communist and a man who claimed records in pastimes ranging from playing golf to crawling under trees. His death on April 25 deprived <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> of what The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> on Monday called `` an extraordinary character whose eccentricity was remarkable even by the rarefied standards of the baronetage.'' <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>'s self-composed entry in Who's Who takes up four times as much space in that 1,972-page tome as Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s. It is strewn with superlatives, ranging from oldest surviving member of the 1st Royal Dragoon Guards that fought in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> in 1920-22 to holding `` an amateur record amongst golfers of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in having played on 382 separate courses of <LOCATION> UK </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eire </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>'s pursuits ran from sheep-shearing in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> between 1928 and 1931 to riding bicycles to the top of mountains to exploring old Roman roads. `` Wife and himself are only persons who have crawled under dwarf fir forest for last -LCB- mile of most northerly known section of any Roman road in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, terminating opposite end of <LOCATION> Kirriemuir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Golf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Course </LOCATION>,'' his Who's Who entry revealed. <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> was born in the Tunisian desert on Aug. 8, 1899, the son of big-game hunter Sir <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>. Christened <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhys </PERSON> <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>, he was educated at upper-crust <PERSON> Harrow </PERSON> high school but ran away to work in a <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> shipyard, joined the dragoons and became a champion cavalry swordsman. He received a disability discharge after he was shot by a Irish sniper. At 46, he changed his name from <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> to <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON>, one of several such alterations he would make, including the addition of <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> during his Moslem period. He went from Christian to Moslem to <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION>. In 1935, he became president of the British <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> but resigned weeks later after a rowdy society meeting. `` They were very rude ... and knew nothing of law and order or methods of procedure,'' he was quoted as saying. From 1944, according to Who's Who, he was `` a practicing Non-Theistic Theravada Buddhist'' who `` performed Holy Buddhist Pilgrimage Nov. 1944, the second Britisher to do so.'' <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> served as an army captain in World War II, but according to the Telegraph regretted fighting for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, saying: `` If a revolution comes _ and come it must after the next world war _ I'll do my damnedest to see it succeeds. In 1950 he was elected to <ORGANIZATION> Perth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> declaring himself `` a blood-red militant communist in every possible way.'' Fifteen years later he claimed to be the only baronet living on social welfare. He said he would take any job `` except being a butler. I hate snobbishness.'' His first wife, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, died in 1945. He is survived by <PERSON> Robina </PERSON>, his second wife. A death notice in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> died in a hospital and was cremated in a private service. Cause of death was not disclosed.
