<HEAD>Gilbert and Sullivan's Original Company Lives Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> D'Oyly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> has been revived and is once again ready for the road with the rollicking songs of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> that made it famous a century ago. The company went out singing on Feb. 27, 1982, with a performance of `` H.M.S. Pinafore'' at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Adelphi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridget </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Oyly </PERSON> <PERSON> Carte </PERSON>, the founder's granddaughter, was in that audience. She died in 1985 and her will left the bulk of her $ 7.8 million estate to trustees who had run the company until its demise. The new company in the northeast town of <LOCATION> Sunderland </LOCATION> opened a 10-day run of `` Iolanthe'' and `` The Yeomen of the Guard'' on April 28. The <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> operas, an art form as distinctly English as bowler hats and tea and crumpets, remain hugely popular throughout the world. Productions of such hits as `` The Mikado,'' `` The Pirates of Penzance'' and `` H.M.S. Pinafore'' regularly appear on stages from elementary schools to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. `` We are riding the crest of a wave,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, the company's general manager. `` If you look around the West End -LRB- of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -RRB-, audiences are going for entertaining musicals and we are going for a lively style.'' A three-month tour through seven other cities in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> follows the <LOCATION> Sunderland </LOCATION> premiere, and the company also hopes to book a run in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` We are already talking about taking the company to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said. `` Inquiries began coming in from agents as soon as we announced on March 1 that we were back.'' The <ORGANIZATION> D'Oyly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> thrived for 107 years on the works of librettist Sir <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwenck </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and composer Sir <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, who collaborated on 14 operettas over 25 years. The style was burlesque, poking satirical fun at politics, the law and society with outrageous puns and far-fetched rhymes. Some Gilbertian phrases entered everyday speech, such as `` things are seldom what they seem,'' `` the upper crust,'' `` a policeman's lot is not a happy one,'' `` language that would make your hair curl'' and `` blow your own trumpet.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Oyly </PERSON> <PERSON> Carte </PERSON> founded the company in 1875 to stage the operettas and built the Savoy Hotel and the neighboring Savoy Theater from the proceeds. Royalties flowed in from thousands more productions abroad, but there was widespread pirating. In 1879 alone more than 150 unauthorized productions of `` H.M.S. Pinafore'' played in 60 cities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> who edits The W.S. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Journal </PERSON> for <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> fans worldwide. D'Oyly Carte hit back by staging his own `` H.M.S. Pinafore'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1879, and in 1880 he had five companies touring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said the new 103-member company plans two operas a year and has new costumes, new sets, a chorus of 32 and an orchestra of 33. <PERSON> Bramwell </PERSON> <PERSON> Tovey </PERSON>, the company's music director and formerly music director of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION>, has re-examined the surviving operetta scores and revived long-forgotten notations and directions. `` For years, the old company clung to one directional format and maybe that led to its running out of steam,'' said <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>. `` Also, as copyright on each work expired after 100 years, the fall in royalties coincided with rocketing costs.'' The original company lost $ 446,500 in 1981 and had to cancel a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour. The government-funded Arts Council refused an appeal for help, pronouncing the D'Oyly Carte style `` wooden and tired.'' <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said $ 945,000 was budgeted for the new `` Iolanthe'' and `` Yeomen.''
</TEXT>
