<HEAD>China's Industrial Boom Threatens Rural Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Along with a new prosperity, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s industrial boom of the past decade has filled rural skies with smog, poisoned wells and blackened streams. The mushroom-like growth of small rural factories that burn coal and lack money or know-how to clean up their wastes has made environmental pollution a nationwide problem. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership, which long claimed that only profit-driven capitalist industries polluted the environment, has begun to construct an environmental protection system. The first environmental protection law was passed in 1979. Several others setting standards for air and water purity have been approved since then. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> was created in 1984, replacing a lower-level committee on the environment. But the chemists, technicians and enforcers in the new system are stretched thinly across the vast rural interior. The estimated 20,000 workers, most without college degrees and with a minimum of special training, have the power, on paper at least, to shut down factories, impose heavy fines, move industries from harmful locations and deny permission for construction of new ones. In reality, however, they often must compromise when strict enforcement of standards could mean shutting down a town's main taxpayer, or when the money to build treatment facilities is lacking. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, with 100 staffers, mainly analyzes pollution data, leaving local agencies to do the enforcing. `` We want to maintain the beauty of mountains and rivers,'' said <PERSON> Tang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shidi </PERSON>, head of the environmental office in <LOCATION> Panzhihua </LOCATION>, a small steel town surrounded by thickly forested mountains in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province. `` But on the other hand we have to support economic development.'' He told a visitor to his office that he makes recommendations to local authorities when a new factory or office is built, but acknowledged they were not always followed. `` We have a principle to give active support -LRB- to development -RRB-... and distribute industry rationally,'' said <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuncheng </PERSON>, a deputy department chief at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> But he acknowledged, `` Factories that provide most of the finances for localities and cause serious pollution problems are difficult to deal with.'' Encouraging rural industry has been a key element of the government's post-1978 development drive. Small local factories, now numbering 15 million, have raised rural incomes and absorbed the surplus rural labor force. These factories now account for more than a quarter of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s industrial output, which has more than tripled in the past decade to $ 372 billion <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said 40 percent of rural factories have pollution problems, including 10 percent with `` serious'' problems. Most could be resolved fairly easily if funds were available, he said. Government funds, however, fall far short of the need and are unlikely to increase at a time when farmers, teachers and the army all are clamoring for more money from a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> already in the red. According to the national agency, the state and industry spent $ 1.35 billion last year to fight pollution. Officials estimated it would take three times that just to clean up <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, a major city. Most of the money was spent in cities, which are among the most smog-ridden in the world. The official statistics on pollutants are daunting. Only one fourth of the 36 billion tons of waste water discharged from factories each year is treated. Few factory smokestacks have scrubbers to keep pollutants from rising into the air. <PERSON> Tang </PERSON> said that until a few years ago the <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that supplies <LOCATION> Panzhihua </LOCATION>'s drinking water ran black because a coking plant dumped water laden with coal dust into the river. Now, he said, the waste water is filtered, but the river still is threatened by discharges from a paper mill. The official media have reported other examples. In April, two villagers in rural <LOCATION> Shaanxi </LOCATION> province in north <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> drowned in industrial waste when the dam burst in a reservoir holding toxic chemicals from a mineral processing facility. Wells in the arid region were poisoned, destroying the local residents' water supply for perhaps years to come Ninety percent of a 14,825-acre pine forest in <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> was destroyed by acid rain from nearby sulfur processing plants. Rural pollution also spills over from cities. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said more than 200,000 acres of farmland are buried under 7.5 billion tons of industrial waste from city plants.
</TEXT>
