<FIRST>s a BC-APN--BuyingbyMail Adv15-3Takes   05-02 1100</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Buying by Mail, Adv 15-3 Takes,1121</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos, 1 cartoon. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Take a phone book, some census data, ZIP codes and auto registration lists. Add a computer, credit cards and 800-prefix phone numbers and you have the main ingredients for an enterprise that's one of the wonders of the Western world _ direct-mail marketing as refined, with amazing ingenuity, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Here's an intriguing report on how the numbers magicians do it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 In the late 1940s, construction of an underpass in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> effectively sealed off <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>'s novelty shop from the outside _ and buying _ world. To keep on eating, he broke the blockade by placing an ad in House & amp; Garden offering tubes of whiskey-flavored toothpaste. He sold 100,000 before the year was out. A bottle opener in the shape of dentures sold even better. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> had rediscovered a sales tool as ancient as the Babylonians: direct mail. Instead of waiting for the customers to come to you, go to them. Some 6,000 to 10,000 catalog retailers _ the figure varies _ do just that, 11.8 billion catalogs a year, according to trade groups. They range from titans such as L.L. Bean in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> to Lands' End in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> anywhere to <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Selman </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> who sells glass paperweights from a $ 15 catalog including a toadstool-shaped antique you can have for $ 27,000. The average American home gets 50 catalogs a year. A burdened letter carrier delivered 324 catalogs to this writer between last Labor Day and Thanksgiving. Last year 88 million Americans _ 51.2 percent of the adult population _ bought something by phone or mail. Direct mail has had a 15 percent annual growth -LRB- 30 percent for upscale catalogs -RRB- since 1970, compared to 5-10 percent for store sales. This is 8.3 percent of the nation's general merchandise sales. Direct mail is a high-tech, almost scientific, business which undoubtedly has the brains to overcome April's 30 percent third class postal hike by becoming even more so. Little of this would have been possible without the computer, the credit card and the 800-prefix telephone number. And above all, the mailing list. The mailing list stems from four of the more mundane items on this part of the planet: the phone book, census reports, ZIP codes and your car registration. Mailing list compilers can get more info from these bare numbers and names than a Biblical exegete could from the Dead Sea Scrolls. <ORGANIZATION> Donnelley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION>, one of the big compilers, says it has more doctors of philosophy interpreting the data than the neighboring <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> hospital has doctors of medicine. Babylonian catalogs came on cuneiformed clay tablets. After <PERSON> Gutenberg </PERSON> invented movable type, <ORGANIZATION> Aldus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manutius </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> had a catalog of books he published of Greek and Latin authors. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> _ who else? _ put out a catalog of 600 books in 1744. American colonials bought everything from lace cuffs to musket balls by mail from the Mother Country. But <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> is the direct father of today's direct mail. His 1872 catalog promised farmers savings of up to 40 percent by eliminating the middleman for items ranging from harnesses to parasols. The first compiler was not far behind. He probably was <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, clerk of <LOCATION> Story </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, who discerned that the registrees of <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>'s new tin lizzies were not only farmers but the wealthier of the breed. Such names might mean money. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> got rights to the names and opened the M and <ORGANIZATION> F </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mailing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> with his brother-in-law. <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON>, another visionary, bought them out in 1917. This vision comes true daily at <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON>'s computer operation in <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. There the names and addresses from the nation's 2,700 telephone books are `` laboriously converted to computer language,'' says <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON>'s director of marketing services An average directory takes six weeks to computerize. But what's in a name? Not a whole lot until those computers start comparing notes with other computers. Census data, for instance, tell how many people live at a phone address. It gives particulars on value of home, income. The name begins to take on some flesh. Compare those results with motor vehicle registrations, compiled by the R.L. <ORGANIZATION> Polk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Taylor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. Two cars at the same address Maybe mom works. An RV? Somebody goes camping. Station wagon? Kids. Sports car? A carefree young in heart if not in fact, a spender. Add some input from ZIP. Admittedly these can be misleading, says <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Heely </PERSON>, a mailing list executive at <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION>, N.Y. The same ZIP code in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> contains the wealthy living in high-rises along the lakefront and the decidedly unwealthy only a few blocks inland. `` ZIPs are not homogeneous,'' says <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisshahar </PERSON> at <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON>'s computer facility in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. So some firms like <ORGANIZATION> Claritas </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> dissect who lives where within a ZIP and divides the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into 250,000 neighborhoods. `` When I got out of college, I moved into an apartment with orange-crate furniture and tacked posters on the wall for decor,'' says <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Claritas </ORGANIZATION>. `` I've moved up and away, but the new tenant probably still has orange crates and tacked posters. Birds of a feather flock together.'' All the easier, then, to identify the flock. This computerized database from national sources _ about half the states will sell vehicle registration lists _ is then inspected, rejected and detected as closely as a 280-pound woman discus thrower from behind the Iron Curtain. Almost everybody buys mailing lists from everybody else to try to find out who <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> are behind the door at 000 Main Street, <LOCATION> Centerville </LOCATION> and just what it is they want to buy. Do they subscribe to The New Yorker? Upscale. Money magazine? Strong evidence of loose change. National Geographic? Travelers, armchair or actual. Field & amp; Stream? And live in rural <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>? And own a camper? <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> are going to hear from <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Orvis </PERSON>. If they buy a sleeping bag and a fly rod, L.L. Bean and <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> wo n't be far behind. Word in direct mail, through list renting, moves fast. `` It's mind-boggling how many sources of data there are,'' <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> says. Credit card applications. Mortgage loans. Alumni directories. Charitable donations. Building permits. Voting lists. Computers cross-reference all this to draw a profile.
