<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: a profile.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Many hospitals sell lists of new mothers. That's grist for the baby catalogs. And, in time, grist for kitchen appliances, toys, back-to-school wear, home computers, brides and eventually _ particularly if the addressee has had the same phone for 30 years _ empty nest catalogs. To keep all this straight, lists are continually subjected to merge-purge, eliminating duplications, merging the newly born and purging the newly departed, since even direct mail can not reach beyond the grave. <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steaks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, say, will take a hint from this list, one from another and make a very educated guess as to who's entertaining a lot, having first, of course, cross-checked with the vegetarian list Maybe it will be a <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> owner in an upscale ZIP code with a bouncing new mortgage on a showplace address who subscribes to Gourmet and Gentleman's Quarterly and recently bought a crystal table set from <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s by mail. `` When a customer makes his first purchase, we generally do n't make money,'' says <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> president <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> `` But if we give him good service and a good product, he becomes a member of our family. It's a process of time.'' `` You test, test, test,'' says <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>. `` If you use a tool list for golfers, you'll lose your shirt. You use a lot of little sample mailings. You do n't go for broke on one mailing or you will. `` The thing about direct mail is that it is measurable. You spend X dollars for a mailing, and you get Y back. In face-to-face retailing you can make a lot of mistakes before they catch up to you.'' To help avoid database generalities, <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON> periodically sends out questionnaires to the public with free coupons to entice a return. More food for the computer. Success in direct mail is not assured. Reasons for failure are emphatic. `` If you rent 20 lists and 19 bomb, you know you sent your catalog at the wrong time, or it was lousy,'' Heely says. It wo n't be because you rented duds. For reasons related to the Golden Rule, list renters do n't trade off lemons. A list of heavy buyers means higher fees to the renters. The more people buy, the more their habits, desires and depth of pocket becomes known and targeted by more catalogs. To the ever-growing number of two-earner families, this means broader chances for convenience shopping. No traffic jams on the way to the mall or parking hassles once there. No tugs-of-war at bargain counters. No sassy or dumb clerks. Instead, the catalog house has a friendly, knowledgeable voice at the end of an 800 number to answer any problem and assure the customer he or she is n't buying a blind pig in a blind poke. `` It's a lot less expensive to keep the customer happy than to try to find a new one,'' says <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Caugherty </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a trade group This is no more than <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> guaranteed when he assured his customers, `` who live remote, by sending their orders and money to the said <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, may depend on the same justice as if present.'' A catalog buy is an act of faith based on a picture of something seen but never touched. Buyer satisfaction is deferred. `` If you do n't receive the goods promptly, the perceived need for it goes away, and the emotional reward goes away, too,'' says <PERSON> Jo-Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> catalog consultant. So one of the first commandments of direct mail is thou shalt fill orders promptly if not sooner. Years ago, entry into direct mail was almost as easy as licking a stamp. <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, a 24-year-old housewife, scraped up $ 2,000 in the early 1920s, placed $ 495 worth of ads for matching purses and belts and offered to monogram them free. <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> did $ 115 million in sales last year. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thalheimer </PERSON> started up his Sharper Image catalog by writing clever copy and offering oddball items such as a suit of 15th century armor for $ 2,450. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Comer </PERSON>, a former ad copywriter, started Lands' End as a yacht supplier, then tacked downwind to become one of the biggest clothing mailers. <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steaks </ORGANIZATION> was a local food supplier until 1952 when <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s father heeded friends' requests to mail meats to their friends. The stampede was on. Mom and Pop still might, just conceivably, start a catalog today over the kitchen table. `` But they better have $ 500,000 up front and be able to sweat it out for two years,'' says <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Heely </PERSON>. `` It's a very crowded mail box,'' says <PERSON> Jo-Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>. She helped <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, an Irish tobacco company, spend over $ 5 million with the help of marketing psychologists and all the sci-fi of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> to prepare their recent debut into direct mail with an up-up-scale catalog full of enticing photos of wares to equip your own Buckingham Palace by. `` The day of the dinosaur catalogs like <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s -LRB- recently abandoned -RRB- are over,'' she says `` Catalogs today are aimed at lifestyles.'' `` Mass marketing is dead,'' pronounced <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>. `` Now it's databased Magazines have a lot of wasted circulation. TV is too broad.'' This is both an opportunity and a challenge for the mailing list. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steaks </ORGANIZATION> aims at a broad market of buyers of high quality -LRB- average catalog purchases are somewhere between $ 35 and $ 50 -RRB-. A paperweight catalog has a far narrower focus. <ORGANIZATION> Claritas </ORGANIZATION> helps by breaking down ZIP codes into categories. It tells you where to find such socio-economic groupies they identify as: Money and Brains, Furs and Station Wagons, Pools and Patios, Young Influentials, Towns and Gowns -LRB- academics in non-metropolitan areas -RRB-, God's Country -LRB- well-educated frontier types -RRB-, <LOCATION> Coalburg </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Corntown </PERSON> -LRB- `` Terre Haute and <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> surrounded by rich farmland and peopled by solid, blue-collar citizens raising sturdy <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyerish </PERSON> children in decent front porch houses'' -RRB-. They'll also tell you, for a price, where to find Shotguns and Pickups, <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Rae-villes </PERSON> and Tobacco Roads. At the brush of a computer button Heely brings up data on Woodworkers Supply of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>: 62,833 catalog purchases in the last six months, 173,930 for 1987. An average list, rented for one time use with the owner's veto over content, goes for around $ 80 per thousand names. Throw in another $ 10 if you want a breakdown as to gender a `` recency'' of purchase. Of that the broker, who mediates between landlord and rentee, gets about 20 percent, the manager who has been handling the list, gets 10, the renter pays maybe $ 3.50 to run off his list. The rest is gravy in his pocket.
