<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: his pocket.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Lists and listers pinpoint like a B-1 bombsight. They can tell you that there is a correlation between someone with a propensity for elective surgery and the amount of cash and spare time the cutee has. Computer modeling, applying a myriad of demographic and lifestyle overlays on the primary database, are producing what Ms. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> calls `` a young science.'' It has to be to marry the tastes of an endlessly varied buyer and an endlessly fanciful seller. Where but in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> could <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> otherwise sell 6,000 busts of King <PERSON> Tut </PERSON>? How else could you find buyers mailing and phoning for every kind of fitness machine, stereo woofer, subliminal Weight Control tapes, two-ounce bottles of quail scent to train <PERSON> Bowser </PERSON> to the hunt, a 24-room purple martin house with guard rails for baby birds -LRB- $ 289 -RRB-, videotaped tours of <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> games in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> or Civil War battlefields, $ 29.95 music box dolls that play `` Thank Heaven for Little Girls,'' a real steam launch for $ 61,500, 42-inch-high stuffed leather rhinosceri -LRB- $ 495 plus $ 12.95 shipping -RRB-, fur coats, mutual funds? Who are these customers who hold 600 million credit cards and once flooded L.L. Bean with 100,000 phone calls in a day? And what are the catalogs that impel them to lick stamps and dial phones? `` It is the merchandiser's dream to identify the core group of 20 percent who buy 60 percent of the nation's goods,'' says <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>. The 20 percent is not always whom you might expect. Catalog buyers are not sit-by-the-fire-thumbing-a-catalog couch potatoes. More likely they are working couples with limited time to shop. They are yuppies, but also over-50s, who have some discretionary income now the kids have gone. The upscale could well be semi-rurals who are 1,500 miles from <PERSON> Nieman </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON>. L.L. Bean's primary constituency is suburban Rural folk can buy lumber jackets and gas lanterns down at the general store. The market is, potentially, anyone who can dial a phone. In 1967, 653 businesses had 800 numbers and handled 7 million phone calls. Today there are 535,000 toll-free numbers, 6.3 billion calls to them and even an 800 number for information on 800 numbers. Today's catalog is only a distant relative to yesteryear's <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> version that was a backhouse fixture. Banana Republic's is a safari through suburban <PERSON> bush </PERSON> clothing together with a written one from some exotic trek. <LOCATION> Patagonia </LOCATION> has rock climbers and sky divers scrambling over the pages of its sportswear, implying that here is the garb of real he-persons. <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>'s handsome tool catalog elevates photos of hammers, saws and wooden planes almost to fine art. `` Catalogs are first and foremost a photographer's medium,'' says <PERSON> Jo-Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>. `` But it has to be more than a pretty picture. It has to have a tone and personality, not just ticky-tacky boxes.'' `` The creative part gets more attention, but it's only 20 percent of success,'' says Chambers. `` The rule of thumb is that 40 percent is the right product and 40 percent is the targeting.'' Bean's no-nonsense pictures, town-meeting typeface and laconic cracker-barrel prose combine to say `` granite solid value.'' Some tool wholesalers, on the other hand, intentionally print on poor paper with indifferent illustrations so the home hobbyist thinks he is getting bargains straight from the close-out sale. The fact that there are 51 million videocassette recorders in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is not lost on the catalog industry. Country Curtains will provide a cassette so you can see right on your own TV set what their products will do for your windows. Selling by VCR is an idea whose time has only just begun. Computerized shopping by TV has long been said to be right around a corner that never seems to arrive. <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>, however, has just launched an electronic catalog in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburbs which enables the viewer to scan, linger over and buy illustrated items from some 50 suppliers, including a supermarket. All you have to do is turn on the cable catalog channel and manipulate it with a Touch Tone phone. The system will even play selections from records you might want to buy. For the retailer who wants to know what is selling, which is the name of the game in the game of names, <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>'s system, called Telaction, `` can tell if people looked at the blue shoes as well as the black they bought or how long someone looked at a dress even if she did n't buy it,'' says <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Telaction </LOCATION>. The cost of finding a customer via catalog is rising with the cost of technology, the cost of paper, the cost of mailing. <ORGANIZATION> DMA </ORGANIZATION>, whose more than 2,000 members have just been hit with the postal hike, is looking into alternative delivery systems. The industry is not happy with a joint survey by <ORGANIZATION> DMA </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON>, the publisher, that the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> failed to deliver four to 14.1 per cent of third class mail in 1983 and did no better when resurveyed last year. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> says it will tighten up procedures. One man's junk mail is another's expensive mailing list. Another problem for direct mail is the matter of privacy. The industry takes considerable pains to stay on the right side of a sometimes fine line. If you do n't want any catalogs, you can ask <ORGANIZATION> DMA </ORGANIZATION> to get you off the lists. More people, however, tell <ORGANIZATION> DMA </ORGANIZATION> they would like to get more catalogs than want none. A Consumer Reports survey found almost nine people in 10 were `` mostly or completely'' satisfied with their shopping by mail or phone. And <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>? After 45 million catalogs offering everything from `` Go Away'' doormats to records of three minutes of silence, he has retired to the golf course where he may reminisce about the year his Game Room offered a Christmas card bearing greetings from The First Family. Inside were a fig-leafed <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> and Eve posed in their Garden. `` It seemed a cute idea,'' he says, as have catalogers since the days of the <ORGANIZATION> Babylonians </ORGANIZATION>. `` But it did n't sell worth a damn,'' which undoubtedly some Babylonian also said.
