<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ With foreign investment at record levels and tourists swarming over the countryside, the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> nations of southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are starting to catch up with their industrialized neighbors to the north. There are some persistent problems to be sure, but one chief of state predicts the region will become `` the motor of the European Community.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After decades of instability and stagnation, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s southern nations are enjoying a surge of economic growth that hints at a potential American-style Sun Belt in the Old World. Following World War II, a succession of shaky governments led <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, while <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> were ruled by dictatorships or military-backed governments. Their economies grew by fits and starts. Now, for the first time, all five countries _ three of them led by English-speaking economists _ have governments or coalitions likely to lead them into the 1990s. Growth rates are generally higher than the European norm and foreign investment has reached record levels. `` The center of gravity of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has moved south,'' says Portuguese Premier <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> won a landslide victory in the 1987 elections. `` The southern nations will now become the motor of the European Community.'' In the 1980s, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> joined the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, marking a more forceful <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> presence in the trade bloc, with <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> knocking on the door for membership. `` The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> would like to turn the south of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> into a developed area resembling the northern countries,'' says <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Pergola </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s Sicilian-born, Harvard-educated minister for European Community Relations. `` This could create a Sun Belt like in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in this area.'' The Brussels-based Community forecasts that the population in its southern tier will grow faster than in its northern areas. Industrialization, drawing its manpower from the higher birth rates, may thus trigger economic growth similar to that in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that led to a migration from the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> to the southeastern Sun Belt states. Symbolizing the area's new dynamism are <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s multimillion-dollar preparations for the World's Fair in <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION> in 1992 and the Summer Olympics in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> the same year <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> are cooling their disputes over <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil rights and the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> to focus instead on streamlining their old-fashioned economies. And <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the sick man of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in the 1970s, has become one of its economic superstars and now claims to have replaced <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as the fifth richest Western nation. Nowadays, 76 percent of Italian households have a car, compared with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 58 percent, while 81 percent have dishwashers, against 77 percent for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. But smart cars and flashy clothes are not <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s only visible signs of prosperity. Italian entrepreneurs were involved in 28 of 68 European mergers and takeovers completed over the past two years. Businessmen are anticipating an economic free-for-all in 1992, when Common Market currency and tariffs finally come down. More than 320 million Europeans will trade goods and services in a single market, fulfilling the visionary plans of the Community's founders when they signed the treaty of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in 1957 Among them is <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedettti </PERSON>, a 53-year-old engineer who transformed the <ORGANIZATION> Olivetti </ORGANIZATION> typewriter firm into a computer giant and is battling for control of the 166-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s largest holding company. <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnelli </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> automakers, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest private company, is credited with spearheading <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s economic revival in the early 1980s. Holdings controlled by the <PERSON> Agnelli </PERSON> family range from communications and media properties, food processing and biotech industries to mutual funds and robot makers. Illustrating newfound confidence in southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, two leading West German banks _ <ORGANIZATION> DeutscheBank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bayerische </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vereinsbank </ORGANIZATION> _ last year took over Italian branches of <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> respectively. Although <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s five-party coalition government still plays political musical chairs, the economy purrs on. Two days after Premier <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Goria </PERSON> resigned on March 11, for the third time during his seven-month tenure, the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> stock market recorded its largest gain since the start of the year. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapalombara </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor, argues in his book `` Democracy, Italian Style'' that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s most glaring problem _ political instability _ is more apparent than real, and is in fact a positive measure of the country's heady spirit for survival and change. Coming up fast on the west of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> rim are <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s newest members. Both recorded 4 percent growth rates last year, double the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> average, contrasted with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s near zero growth last year. `` <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> form the area of greatest economic growth in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and are the countries that exhibit the best economic prospects for the next five years,'' says <PERSON> Pedro-Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuczynski </PERSON>, a Peruvian banker with <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, foreign investors last year poured $ 7.9 billion into the economy _ twice the 1986 amount _ to fund one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s fast-track economies, moving toward what the Spaniards call `` El Horizonte'92'' -LRB- Horizon'92 -RRB- `` I see an important new axis, from <LOCATION> Turin </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, bringing the center of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> southward,'' says <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Cebrian </PERSON>, the editor of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pais </ORGANIZATION>. `` <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> are coming together in a way we would have thought unbelievable only a few years ago,'' he says. The <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> Olympic Games and the <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> World </LOCATION>'s Fair in 1992 will create new housing, high-tech communications, and rail and road networks, at an estimated cost of $ 8.9 billion. The streets of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> are now choked with shiny new cars, triple-parked. Auto sales increased by 29 percent last year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Spanish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Makers </ORGANIZATION>. Using skilled <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> labor at lower cost than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is building an advanced microchip plant near <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. And at some rchards in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> computers are used to keep track of the orange crop. Reaching across continents, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has signed a $ 3 billion accord with <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> to form joint-venture companies financed by both countries.
