<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>ROME: both countries.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` We lost the industrial revolution, but we're going to win the post-industrial revolution,'' says Spanish banker <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Sola </PERSON>. What triggered <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s development was the smooth transition from General <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s 40-year dictatorship to the pro-business socialist government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>. In neighboring <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s poorest member, another political switch has spurred economic growth. Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> has brought stability in the wake of 16 years of revolving-door governments. Many wealthy Portuguese, who left the country after a 1974 leftist revolution that toppled a 42-year dictatorship, have returned to dance in fashionable <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> nightspots and to present their daughters at lavish debutante balls. <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, a 48-year-old former economics professor, is pushing ahead with privatization of dozens of large state-owned companies, including tobacco, banking, media and insurance interests. `` The degree of confidence in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> is very, very high,'' the premier says. The first state-controlled company to be put on the block as part of <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>'s privatization program is EPSI, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s largest producer of polyethylene and polypropylene The Italian <ORGANIZATION> Enichem </ORGANIZATION> company is at the top of the list of prospective buyers. Cheap labor, which compares favorably with costs in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, has attracted foreign manufacturers and brought unemployment down to 6.6 percent, the lowest in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> after <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>. A $ 2-an-hour minimum wage brings in high-tech industries like <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION>, which recently launched a $ 43 million expansion of an electronics plant at <LOCATION> Oporto </LOCATION> that employs 1,000 people. Tourism is also booming, with around 10 million foreigners vacationing in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> every year to make the industry a $ 1-billion-a-year business. At the other end of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, tourism is still <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s biggest foreign exchange earner A record 8 million tourists spent $ 3.2 billion last year. Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s Socialist government, in a reversal of former policy, now wants to broaden the country's economic base and attract foreign capital into <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> firms through freer financial markets. Reforms of the banking system are laying the groundwork for a money market that will allow American brokerage houses to buy seats on the booming <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> stock market. Western European investors, taking advantage of new measures permitting their profits to be repatriated, last year poured more than $ 52 million into the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> exchange last year. `` <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> is changing at last,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Costopoulos </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Creditbank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s biggest private bank. Greeks can now apply for home mortgages and bank interest rates are high enough to attract private depositors. `` Overall modernization of the economy is the basic condition for our survival and growth,'' says National Economy Minister <PERSON> Panayotis </PERSON> <PERSON> Roumeliotis </PERSON>, who coordinates economic policy. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> and Turkish Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> have reached a `` no-war'' agreement and set up a hot line telephone between their capitals to defuse tensions between the two <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members. Bankers and businessmen are firmly behind the current Greek-Turkish rapprochement. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, which in the 17th century camped 300,000 men before the gates of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, firing cannons into the city in order to enter <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, applied to join the Common Market in April 1987. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> says it wo n't automatically block the application. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, the only Islamic nation among the five southern <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries, is making a bid to replace war-torn <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> as a banking center for the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. At the same time, its new seaside resorts are luring Western tourists for bargain vacations. More than 3 million foreigners spent $ 2 billion in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> last year, a 60 percent earnings increase over 1986. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> official, says that his export drive and free-market policies _ including the privatization of state monopolies _ brought growth of 7 percent last year that will enable <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s economy `` to skip a century.'' Luxuries like whiskey, instant coffee and French champagne are now snapped up in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, where the per capita income is half that of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. Massive investment in energy, transport and communications have transformed many towns into huge construction sites. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> is now planning a third bridge over the Bosporus waterway, reflecting the country's determination to link itself with <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> absorbs more than 40 percent of all Turkish exports, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is home to 1.4 million Turkish workers and their families. But with a 67 percent inflation rate, a currency crunch and a huge foreign debt, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> still has a long way to go to reach the prosperity of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries. For the other southern European countries, the worldwide October stock market crash also highlighted persistent problems. _ <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> is facing wildcat strikes in transport and industry, a 12 percent unemployment rate and a runaway national debt And the south of the country, still plagued by crime syndicates like the Mafia, lags economically far behind the north. _ In <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, stagnant exports, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s lowest productivity and a huge public sector deficit keep growth rates low _ In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, the Socialists are troubled by <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s highest unemployment _ 21 percent in 1987 _ and union protesters filled the streets of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> when the government suggested that state and private employers not grant wage hikes of more than 5 percent _ In <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, the per capita income of $ 2,500 is only half that of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and Premier <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> concedes that people still go hungry And if the pace of development ca n't be speeded up in southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the economic spurt that is ending <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> poverty may run out of steam in the competitive post-1992 market. `` Unless there's cohesion among the 12 EEC nations, development in the southern regions will be like quicksand,'' says <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pergola </ORGANIZATION>, the Italian minister. `` Cohesion must start at the bottom, the south, through new forms of financial engineering.''
