 <LOCATION> ROME </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Here are brief biographies of the leaders of five key nations in southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> ITALY </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Premier <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Goria </PERSON>, 44, who resigned March 11, has been asked by President <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON> to remain as caretaker premier until a new leader is chosen. Party leader <PERSON> Ciriaco </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Mita </PERSON> is currently trying to put together another five-party coalition. <PERSON> Goria </PERSON>, a former accountant from the northern city of <LOCATION> Asti </LOCATION>, was a surprise choice for premier when he took office on Aug. 1, 1987 at the head of the shaky coaltaly's 47th postwar government. <PERSON> Goria </PERSON> was <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s youngest premier ever. <PERSON> Goria </PERSON> previously served as treasury minister and was credited in that post with loosening the country's restrictive foreign exchition that was <PERSON> Iange </PERSON> controls and with helping to bring double-digit inflation to its present level of about 5 percent. He is married and has two children. <LOCATION> SPAIN </LOCATION> _ Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, a 46-year-old <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION> labor lawyer, took office in December 1982 following a landslide victory of his <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He had no previous government experience but was head of the parliamentary opposition after <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> returned to democracy in 1977. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is married to sch <LOCATION> ROME </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ World War II left the nations of southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> bombed-out and poor, devastated by six years of combat while a few neutral countries led by dictators watched from the sidelines. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> was brought to its knees by the Nazi occupation and the Allied invasion, while right-wing dictators kept a tight grip on <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> was plunged into civil war between Communists and nationalists. Moslem <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> was reeling from abrupt change wrought by wartime contact with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> struggled back on track after 21 years of rule by Fascist dictator <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> with elections in 1946. Funds from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marshall Plan laid the groundwork for industrialization. The Christian Democrats, in power through much of the postwar period, presided over dramatic economic expansion by the 1960s that was termed an `` economic miracle.'' But in the 1970s, political instability and worker unrest brought economic crisis and fueled terrorism led by the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigades </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, the pro-German fascist regime of General <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> won the bitter civil war of 1936-1939, but watched World War II from neutral sidelines. In the'60s and'70s, <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> backed the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, traditional landowners and industrialists but suppressed free-market business initiatives. After <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s death in 1975, the country quickly blossomed into an ebullient democracy under a constitutional monarch, King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> also watched from the sidelines under the dictatorship of Antonio de <PERSON> Oliveira </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> which lasted 42 years until 1974. The country veered left after a 1974 revolution, but stabilized in the 1980s under business-minded, centrist governments. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> recovered economically from the devastating 1946-49 civil war thanks to <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> Plan funds. Political instability in the 1960s after years of right-wing government triggered the 1967 colonels' dictatorship, which collapsed after the 1974 invasion of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. A referendum that year abolished the monarchy and made <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> a presidential republic. The socialist government of the 1980s has moved gradually toward centrist, pro-business policies. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> remained a neutral dictatorship for much of World War II, then declared war on <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1945. The economically backward country became a firm ally of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> aid helped cut down state capitalism in favor of free enterprise and Westernization in the 1950s. A short-lived military takeover in 1960 ushered in a period of political and economic problems that led to street violence in the 1970s by Marxist revolutionaries, right-wing `` Gray Wolves'' and separatist Kurds. The military took over again in 1980, but a pro-Western democracy was restored in parliamentary elections held in 1983.
