<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ In June, the 500,000 th Steinway piano, designed by artist <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON>, will be unveiled at a Carnegie Hall concert <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Steinway </PERSON>'s main competitor, reaches the 500,000 mark every 2 -LCB- years on its assembly line in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. But at Steinway's plant in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, most things are still done the old-fashioned way. That's what makes a Steinway a Steinway.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a box-shaped, soundproof room, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Parada </PERSON> stands before a piano keyboard pulled from its shining 9-foot body. <PERSON> Parada </PERSON> plinks at the keys, listening carefully, making adjustments instinctively. No music pours from the instrument. Parada is not a pianist. Instead, he `` turns music boxes into Steinways,'' spending 24 hours with the inner workings of each piano, creating concert grands for artists from <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Horowitz </PERSON> to <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. `` The piano must allow an artist to develop his talents. It is not like an automobile, where it works the same for everybody _ you turn the wheel right, the automobile goes right,'' explains <PERSON> Parada </PERSON>, who does things the old-fashioned way at <ORGANIZATION> Steinway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons. In fact, everything's done much the same way it's been done since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Engelhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinway </PERSON> arrived from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1853 and switched from cabinetmaking to keyboards. The Steinway piano is still hand-strung, fussed and fawned over, individually numbered, tuned and retuned by highly skilled specialists like <PERSON> Parada </PERSON>. It still takes one full year to create the Steinway concert grand, `` the piano by which all others are judged,'' the product of more than 100 patented piano-making techniques. It remains the choice of the great pianists _ <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Horowitz </PERSON> _ as it was the choice of <PERSON> Ignace </PERSON> <PERSON> Paderewski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Liszt </PERSON> a century ago. `` It's the only piano for me,'' says <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nero </PERSON>. `` I was 13 when I started in competition at the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION>, 14 when I started at Juilliard, and it's been Steinway all the way.'' In June, the 500,000 th Steinway, designed by artist <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON>, will be unveiled at a Carnegie Hall concert <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION>, its top competitor, reaches the 500,000 mark every 2 -LCB- years on its assembly line in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The Steinway does n't come cheap either: The price list runs from $ 7,500 to $ 40,000 for the 9-foot concert grand. <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION>'s least expensive piano costs about $ 2,700, while its concert grand prices are about the same as Steinway. How has Steinway survived 135 years, outlasting an assortment of competitors while keeping its reputation for quality? `` A Steinway is a Steinway only because we do n't cut any corners,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinway </PERSON>, 70, one of the last two family members still in the piano-making business. `` We make quality, nothing but the top quality we can make. `` My great-grandfather started that when he started the firm 135 years ago. I often say we're probably thickheaded and stubborn. We stick to our principles. But it works.'' `` The Steinway manufacturing process relies on tradition,'' offers <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Garlick </PERSON>, an antique piano aficionado now employed as <ORGANIZATION> Steinway </ORGANIZATION>'s national field service manager. `` That tradition has carried on, although we do n't ignore technology.'' Instead, an exacting process which combines the innovative and the antiquated is used to create 3,400 Steinway pianos each year at the company's 11-acre Queens factory. In one part of the plant, a worker hand-trims pieces of veneer for the piano's outer surface with a 120-year-old machine. Later in the process, a newly developed machine perfectly shapes its soundboard to fit the piano body. `` Even that is not a production-line concept,'' says <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, president of the firm since <ORGANIZATION> Steinway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Musical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, bought it three years ago. `` It's letting technology do something even better than we could do it before. One man still handles that job alone.'' There are many answers as to what makes a Steinway a Steinway: the input of the artists, the commitment to quality, the genius of 19th-century piano meister C.F. <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinway </PERSON>. But those responses may miss the forest for the trees, which provide the Steinway wood.
</TEXT>
