<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Some people go through life with a sure touch for the practicalities of everyday life. Others flounder. For them, former TV reporter <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> has written a guide designed to keep them out of the many traps that open up in a consumer society.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KAY BARTLETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Who among us was raised with an innate knowledge of which telephone company gives us the best deal? Who, in fact, ever dreamed that picking a telephone company would be a way of life in 1988? And if you `` would n't buy a used car from that man,'' whom would you buy one from? And how do you negotiate with him when you're not even really sure what rack and pinion means? What about the jungle of financial jargon that everyone else seems to understand _ like CD's, <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s, deferred annuity bonds, <LOCATION> Keoghs </LOCATION>, municipals, etc.? It was simpler when people just went to the bank that gave the best toaster. If you already had a toaster, the next toughest choice was whether you wanted the Revere Ware pots or a non-brand that had pretty yellow flowers on it. These are things that almost everyone, at some point in life _ just starting out, after a divorce, recently widowed _ must learn to deal with without getting stung in the process. `` You are n't born with this knowledge. Kids of people who own businessess or are in the financial world might know some of it, but most of us do n't,'' says <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>, a former national consumer affairs correspondent for television, and author of `` <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>'s Guide to Living on Your Own,'' due in bookstores early this summer. `` This book is not for people who see an ad on television and send $ 5 away and expect to get a diamond ring in return. They deserve what they get. This book is for reasonably intelligent people who must face these kinds of things for the first time and are n't aware of the pitfalls. `` This book is not about the things your mother never told you, it's about the things your father never told you,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>. Like taxes, audits, how much insurance you need, which health club to join, how to pick a telephone company and how to deal with the media if you've gotten yourself into a mess that would incidentally make a good story. A lot of the advice comes from <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>'s nearly 17 years in radio and television, first teaching art on cable TV, then covering the courts in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and later as the consumer affairs expert there and ultimately for CBS. She often got tips from viewers who had been ripped off by one scheme or another. As a local reporter, she named names and products. `` That's the job of the local reporter, but I do n't do that in the book,'' she says. `` This is more of a household encyclopedia that would be applicable anywhere.'' She explains, for instance, some of the oldest tricks in the books, such as the bait and switch ruse, and how not to go for the bait. It's a practical book. The section on health clubs, for instance, warns against paying the annual membership fee to clubs that have n't opened yet. Some have gone under before they got going. Others, she warns, may be on shaky financial ground, so check them out before handing over your check for a year's membership Also figure out what you really need. Are you paying for fancy exercise machines that you're not likely to use. Or a swimming pool, when what you really want is the racquet ball court? She advises going to <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION>'s or schools to see if you might get the facilities you want much cheaper. Or, go to a club that has only the facilities you actually intend using. It will probably be cheaper.
</TEXT>
