 She confesses to being a victim herself, joining health clubs to drop that extra 20 pounds that always crept back on. She finally calculated that her demanding schedule, working long days, made it impractical; her visits turned out to cost her $ 40 a session. Her book tells you what questions to ask up front and urges the timid to push for answers to key questions, especially, `` What is this going to cost me?'' `` Healthy skepticism is important,'' she says. `` A financial planner or an accountant should be able to explain things to you without talking down to you and telling you to ` just trust me.' `` Ask him or her about fees, about how much of his income is derived from commissions, ask for references, look for possible conflicts of interest.'' She tells how to find out what the car dealer paid for the car he is selling you, the toll-free 800 number to call to find out whether the model of used car you're considering has ever been recalled, how to spot cosmetic cover-ups on a used car. <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON>, 43, and recently remarried, says her book draws on files she had kept as a television consumer expert. `` I spent a lot of time on the telephone updating things, and re-interviewing people, but basically it was years and years of reporting that went into the book,'' she says. If you're going to try the media, she tells you how. First, do all the work yourself. The local reporter or columnist does n't have time to unearth every single aspect of your case. They get hundreds, maybe thousands of letters from irate consumers seeking to enlist the newspaper in their cases. You, the abused, must document your claim, agree to be interviewed, and, if you live in a multimedia town, do n't ship out carbons to every reporter in town. Pick the one you like best, offer an exclusive story, and hope for the best. It helps if the story is interesting and has broad appeal. <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> had an unusual career trail. She was accepted by the <ORGANIZATION> Peac