<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vibraphonist <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who just turned 75, is leading a swinging band of 17 musicians mostly in their 20s, following the beat of another generation. `` We're doing big business on the road,'' says <PERSON> Hamp </PERSON>, as he is known to his friends. `` We play every night. We pack the house. I do n't have to play rock' n' roll. I play what I always played, like ` Beat Me Daddy, Eight to the Bar.''' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who was in the first racially integrated group in jazz _ <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>'s quartet _ wrote his most famous composition `` Flying Home'' in 1937. He estimates he has played it 300 times a year for 51 years and it `` still stops the show.'' `` I like to play with this band,'' says <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who recruits his musicians from among college graduates who majored in jazz. `` The guys are all interested. Everybody tries to play better than he played last night. That makes it fun. `` I'm trying to play better than I played last night, too.'' The band spent its annual stint in February at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lionel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION>, where some 15,000 high schoolers came to seminars. It opened the Jazzport at <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s South Street Seaport with two two-hour concerts on both April 1 and 2 and played a benefit for jazz radio station WBGO-FM at Town Hall on April 7 After a birthday bash at <PERSON> Regine </PERSON>'s here on April 19, the band left the next day _ <ORGANIZATION> Hampton </ORGANIZATION>'s 75th birthday _ on a tour of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who plans to campaign for the Republicans, will play jazz festivals this summer and appear at the Hollywood Bowl and <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION>. He's invited to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> for two weeks and on a jazz cruise for eight days. The grin, the unrestrained energy, buoyant personality and showmanship are still <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>'s hallmarks _ along with his melodic and swinging performing style. `` When I was a kid, I always wanted to put on a show,'' he recalls. `` I liked to get in the moonshine at night, doing like I'm on the stage I always liked to be taking bows.'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, says that when his father joined the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> his mother moved him to her family home in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> where he was raised by his grandmother. `` We used to go to the Holiness Church every time the church door opened,'' he recalls. `` There was a swinging band there _ trumpets, saxophones, guitars. We sat down in one of the front pews next to where the band was. When the sister beating the bass drum would get happy and start up and down the aisles, I took the mallets and started beating the bass drum. It was my introduction to music.'' Not only has he stayed with music, <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> says, `` I also stayed with the Bible and religion all the time.'' A framed picture of his grandmother, <PERSON> Livinia </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, rests on the grand piano in <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> apartment. `` I was crazy about my grandmother,'' he says. When the family moved to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where the schools were tough, his grandmother sent him to a Roman Catholic school in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis </LOCATION>. There a nun taught him how to play the snare drum, and how to twirl the sticks, toss and catch them. Back in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, he joined <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Hite </PERSON>'s band as a drummer. At age 15 he followed <PERSON> Hite </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and two years later they auditioned to back <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> at <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> liked us so well he took us recording with him,'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> recalls. `` There was a set of vibes in a corner. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> said, ` Do you know how to play it? Move it out here in the middle of the floor and play something for me.'
