 `` I had been in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Defender Newsboys Band in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. They had a xylophone; it's got the same keyboard. I played drums in the marching band and timpani and xylophone in the concert band. We had a good bandmaster, Maj. <PERSON> Endicott </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who had graduated in music from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heidelberg </ORGANIZATION>. He taught me German harmony. Anybody interested, he would teach them.'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> had studied <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>'s records, so on that October day in 1930 he romped through <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>'s trumpet solo in `` Big Butter and Egg Man'' on the vibraphone. `` It knocked <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> out,'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> says. They recorded eight songs that day. On the first one, <PERSON> Eubie </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>'s `` Memories of You,'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> played vibes while <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> sang and the drums while <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> played his trumpet. The <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Hite </PERSON> <PERSON> Band </PERSON> backed <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> for nine months at the <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> became known. When the engagement ended, <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> assembled his first band. They traveled, in four cars and a trailer for his drums and vibes, from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, B.C. `` I always played good dance music and played jazz for a show. I built up a following,'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> says. `` I play a lot of dances now. They always ask me to make return engagements. Young people dance, too. I'm just back from a teen-age affair in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. There were 5,000 kids there. We were supposed to quit at 10:30. At 12:30 they were yelling for more and stomping on the floor.'' In the early 1930s, <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> traded touring for a job in the Paradise Nightclub across the street from the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> train station. They'd leave the doors open, <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> says, and sailors arriving to paint the town would come in. Beer was 25 cents a pitcher and there was sawdust on the floor. `` I had a good band there,'' <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> says. `` <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> was at the Palomar Ballroom. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> was with him. Naturally <PERSON> John </PERSON> would ask where he could hear some good jazz. He heard us and he brought <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> down. Lo and behold, I'm on the bandstand playing and I hear a guy playing clarinet beside me. I could tell it was <PERSON> Benny </PERSON>'s famous clarinet. It was Aug. 19, 1936. I'll never forget. We played like that about two hours straight. People were calling people and they were coming from all over town. That place was packed and jammed. We was blowing. `` <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> asked me to come the next morning to a recording date. I went and we did ` Moonglow' and ` Dinah.' Those records got so popular, <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> kept calling me to come to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. We thought he was kidding. `` The Paradise took the sawdust off the floor and put tablecloths on the tables. It was $ 1.25 to come in. After that jam session, you could n't get in, even with the price of admission. We got super-famous overnight, because <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> had come and christened us.'' On Nov. 11, 1936, <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> joined the <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> Quartet at the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Hotel in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` Everything was segreg