</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On her 17th birthday last fall, <PERSON> Linzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> got a plum of a present, the title role in `` Carrie,'' the new Broadway musical about a girl with telekinetic powers. At the time, Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> was a student at the <ORGANIZATION> Italia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>, a drama school in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Her acting credentials were meager: a British touring company of `` Annie'' and a small part on a television series. But the next day she was the Cinderella story in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> tabloids. `` Unknown lands lead in major show co-produced by the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` It did n't sink in at all until I settled down and started rehearsing,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says now. It has been a turbulent and fast-paced few months. `` Carrie'' is based on the <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> novel that most people remember as a movie with <PERSON> Sissy </PERSON> <PERSON> Spacek </PERSON> playing the troubled teen-ager. In the film, <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> is taunted and tormented by other high school students and her mother before she gets revenge on prom night. `` I was told right from the beginning not to try and base myself on <PERSON> Sissy </PERSON> <PERSON> Spacek </PERSON>,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> recalls. `` The musical tries to follow the book rather than the film because the show really is more of a tragedy than a horror story.'' `` Carrie'' is a unique collaboration of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and British theater people. With the blessing of actors' unions in both countries, the show has a joint Anglo-American cast. The director is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hands </PERSON>, artistic head of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. The music and lyrics were written by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitchford </PERSON>, the men who wrote `` Fame.'' <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, Broadway's recent `` Sweet Charity,'' did the choreography. The show was to co-star <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> as <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON>'s bizarre and vindictive mother, but <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, dissatisfied with her role, left after the show's engagement in <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the home base of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> was so nice,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` She's so motherly and was always lovely to me. I think she did n't want to be nasty, which is what the part requires.'' <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>, who played the gym teacher in the movie version of `` Carrie,'' has now taken over the role of the mother. `` She came in and said, ` Let's get into this,''' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` The score has n't really changed a lot since then, just the way that it is being done has. It's becoming a little weirder now. Before it was very melodic. Now it's stranger.'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> is from a small town near <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Her father is a toolmaker and her mother a secretary. Neither had any theatrical aspirations. Their daughter, the second of two children, did. `` When I was very young, I had a lot of energy,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` I was always a real pain until I started dancing and got rid of some of that energy. She was sent to the local dancing school and got jobs in community productions. At the age of 14, she was accepted by the <PERSON> Italia </PERSON> <PERSON> Conti </PERSON> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and her parents took out loans to pay the expensive tuition. `` I'm paying them back now out of my salary,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` They did so much for me.'' While at the school, she auditioned for `` <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON>,'' singing `` On My Own'' from `` Les Miserables.'' After a second audition, she got the job. Her parents came to see the musical in <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION> and were surprised at her performance. `` They knew that I sang well and obviously they were very confident in me or they would n't have let me go to the theater school in the first place,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` But more than anything, they were shocked with the acting I was doing. They had never really seen me act.'' The young actress worked closely with Hands, best known on Broadway as the man who staged the RSC productions of `` Much Ado About Nothing'' and `` Cyrano de Bergerac,'' with <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sinead </PERSON> <PERSON> Cusack </PERSON>. It was n't until the show moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and started to rehearse again that Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> began to understand her character. `` I've just suddenly come to realize that the whole thing about <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> is that she really is quite an intelligent person,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` She does n't have to be ugly and she does n't have to be awkward. She can be quite beautiful in her own way. She's just different.'' When Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> first started doing the role, she wondered how she could keep up the intense pace required by it. Now she is getting used to it. `` I take everything as it comes and even if the show is n't a success, it's still a great achievement for me and a great experience,'' Miss <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON> says. `` I listen to everybody's advice. I'm not saying that I always take it but if I listen to it all, then I can make my own decisions. I'm learning so much and so quickly. I have to.''
</TEXT>
