<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Slaves Freed 100 Years Ago but Racial Strain Remain in Brazil</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note May 13th anniversary.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LISA GENASCI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALVADOR, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On May 13, 1888, Princess Isabel of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> signed the Golden Law and 780,000 slaves went free, three centuries after blacks first came in bondage from <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. A hundred years later the Brazilian government is commemorating the event with tributes to what it calls `` racial democracy.'' Blacks, however, maintain that widespread prejudice and inequality leave them little to celebrate. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> has designated May 13 a national holiday. The government, the media and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> have begun nationwide campaigns aimed at portraying <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s multi-racial society as integrated. But while millions of Brazilian blacks and whites live and work side by side in apparent harmony, many here contend that `` racial democracy'' is a myth. `` Abolition of slavery here was merely a legal act. It has meant little in reality,'' said <PERSON> Arnaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Beltrami </PERSON>, spokesman for the Brazilian Bishops council, which in the world's largest <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nation is given great importance. The Golden Law, already approved by the national legislature, was signed by Princess <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> while her father, Emperor <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, was out of the country. The 780,000 slaves joined millions of other blacks already released from bondage and they were left to fend for themselves without education, training or jobs. It happened 25 years and 134 days after <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s Emancipation Proclamation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> As the slavery issue helped set off the Civil War in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, abolition in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, without compensation to slave owners, was a factor in the ouster of <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON>'s monarchy and the establishment of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> as an republic. Today, blacks and mulattoes make up about 80 million of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 143 million people They are prominent in sports and entertainment _ among them the soccer great Pele, singer-composer <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Nascimento </PERSON> and actor-vaudevillean Grande Othello. But political leaders, army generals, corporate executives, diplomats and bishops are almost exclusively the descendants of white Portuguese colonizers or other white European immigrants. The 559-seat national <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has just seven black members. Help-wanted ads still specify that applicants should have a `` good appearance,'' meaning they should be white. Blacks are unwelcome in many restaurants, bars and upper-class apartment buildings, where doormen sometimes force them to use the service entrance. `` Blacks here are found in hillside shantytowns, working as maids or as manual laborers, in prisons and in juvenile delinquency centers,'' said <PERSON> Benedita </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s first black congresswoman and a former maid. To the casual observer, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is an astonishing blend of racial types. Centuries of racial mixing, starting with the Portuguese, native Indians and then African slaves, have produced a range of skin hues and hair types that the country's Portuguese language defines in 120 different ways. Much of Brazilian culture also comes from black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, including samba music, many typical national dishes such as `` feijoada'' black bean stew, cachaca sugar cane liquor, and popular voodoo-type spirit religions. President <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, in announcing the May 13 holiday, spoke of a mixed-race people `` living and growing in harmony.'' He held up <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> as a model for nations like <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. TV GLobo, the country's largest private television network, for several months has been broadcasting a public service announcement with well-known black performers and athletes wishing viewers `` Axe'' -LRB- pronounced ah-SHEH -RRB-, an African word meaning `` good luck'' and `` power.'' Another TV message sponsored by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> shows a black hand and a white hand slowly clasping while a voice says, `` Many races, one people.'' The government-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brazil </ORGANIZATION> is paying for a similar media campaign. But racial prejudice still runs deep. Paulo de <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, 18, lives with his father and four brothers and sisters in a crumbling Portuguese colonial-era house in <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, a city of 1.8 million, about 1,120 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> was <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s capital in the 17th century and as the principal slave port became a center of black culture. Paulo de <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> said he does not feel discriminated against, but he added that he often is stopped, searched and asked for identification by police officers. Twice he has been arrested on `` suspicion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
