<FIRST>s i BC-Brazil-Blacks Adv08-1stAdd   05-02 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Blacks, Adv 08-1st Add,0701</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>SALVADOR, Brazil: he said.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In a recent independent survey, 309 Brazilian youngsters 7 to 18 years old were asked to look at photographs of a white and a black person and to link certain characteristics to each. The survey indicated that 82.9 percent of the children considered the black man `` stupid,'' 85.7 percent found him `` ugly'' and 84.2 percent saw him as `` a thief.'' In comparison, the percentages, respectively, for the white were 17.1, 14.3 and 15.8. In <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>, a black businesswoman married to a white Swiss citizen told the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Jornal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> do </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brasil </ORGANIZATION> that when she tried to pay for dinner by check at a fashionable nightclub, the management refused to accept it, apparently in the belief the checkbook was stolen. `` They insulted me and threw me out,'' <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobrist </PERSON> told the paper. `` I called the police and ended up with the manager at the precinct station. They accepted my check only after the police chief called up my house and confirmed I was who I said I was.'' Blacks also lag behind whites in education and income. A government census showed blacks on average complete just 2.1 years of schooling, compared to 4.8 years for whites. And blacks earn 47 percent less than whites doing the same work, according to a 1985 labor union study. `` Blacks have never been integrated into <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> society as full citizens,'' said the black composer and singer <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Gil </PERSON>, who also is the <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION> state secretary of culture. `` We need to think about what Princess <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON>'s signature on a piece of paper actually meant for us, if anything,'' <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> added in an interview in his office in <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION>'s capital. Starting in the 1500s, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> brought in an estimated 3.6 million West Africans to work on sugar, cotton and coffee plantations and to mine gold and diamonds. The abolitionist movement grew after 1850, when the government outlawed slave trading. In 1871 the Free Womb Law declared that children born of slave mothers would be considered free. When <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> finally abolished slavery, it was the last country in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION> to do so, and under sharp international censure. `` The emancipation actually took the wind out of a growing abolitionist movement. Maybe our lives would be different if the law had not been signed just then,'' said the black historian and activist <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigues </PERSON>. He suggested <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> could have taken more time to prepare blacks for citizenship. But the documentary history of slavery in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> was virtually erased in 1891 when Finance Minister <PERSON> Ruy </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbosa </PERSON> had the records of slave trade burned on grounds that the country should look ahead and forget its `` African'' past. Possibly because of that, black consciousness today is dim and black pride almost non-existent. Few black rights groups or activists exist. Many mixed-race Brazilians seek to appear whiter and climb the social ladder. `` There is no such thing as ` black' here,'' said <PERSON> Januario </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> on Black Culture in <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>. `` People use any word but black to define themselves. They want to be as white as possible.'' Still, in this centennial year, awareness of discrimination is growing. At <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>'s famous pre-Lenten Carnival parades this past February, many of the poor, mostly black groups competing for prizes with floats and samba music chose racism as their themes, rather than the usual folklore motifs. The champion group, <PERSON> Vila </PERSON> <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON>, offered a tribute to <PERSON> Zumbi </PERSON>, leader of a 17th century slave revolt and a hideaway for runaway slaves. The runnerup was the <LOCATION> Mangueira </LOCATION> school, which sang of blacks `` free from the master's whip, but trapped in the slums.'' Many black groups said they do n't intend to celebrate the May 13 holiday but planned festivities for Nov. 20. That is the anniversary of the death of <PERSON> Zumbi </PERSON>, killed in 1695 by <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> troops who defended slave owners. `` We need to celebrate black strength, not a gift from white men,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
