<HEAD>India-Wars Editor's Note</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The following is for use with a package of three stories:
BC-India-Wars-Gurkhas, b0603; BC-India-Wars-Sikhs, b0604, and
BC-India-Wars-Buddhists, b0605.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Armed conflicts are besetting the government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, a nation troubled as well by a host of other problems that stem from its very own diversity. In addition to a conflict in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, where militant Sikhs are fighting to forge their own nation in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>, another group of fierce fighters, the Gurkhas, are waging battle to separate from Marxist-led West Begali state in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s East. Farther east, refugees from a little-known, 11-year war by <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas are spilling across <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s border from the <LOCATION> Chittigong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> as bloodshed mounts there. Associated Press reporters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> recently traveled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s three hotspots and filed the accompanying reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
