<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>India's Gurkhas, Famous as Soldiers, Fight for Their Own State</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Companion stories are BC-India-Wars-Sikhs, b0604 and
BC-India-Wars-Buddhists, b0605.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DARJEELING, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The severed heads of a school principal and a journalist were left hanging in plastic bags in a town square set among lovely, wooded hills. Their foreheads were smeared with vermilion _ a Gurkha mark of revenge. The killings in April were among the most brutal in the two-year campaign by Gurkhas, famed as soldiers in the British and Indian armies, for the creation of a separate Indian state called <LOCATION> Gurkhaland </LOCATION> around this once-tranquil vacation retreat. <PERSON> Subash </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghising </PERSON>, 52-year-old leader of the <LOCATION> Gurkha </LOCATION> agitation, has been negotiating with Indian government officials, but in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he seemed in no mood to compromise. `` We want blood for blood, an eye for an eye, and we will settle for nothing less than a homeland for the Gurkhas,'' he said at his well-guarded headquarters in Darjeeling, which also is famous for its tea. So far, Ghising's repeated trips to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> have swayed Indian officials to offer the <LOCATION> Gurkha </LOCATION> area some governmental power and development funds, but not to make it <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 26th state. The killing goes on, with at least 275 deaths recorded since the agitation started in April 1986. Some officials of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> state, which now governs the area, say privately the dispute has the potential to lead to more dangerous demands for a separate country, as militant Sikhs have done in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. The Gurkhas, who are Indians of Nepalese descent, want 2,250 square miles around Darjeeling, an area slightly larger than <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, as a Gurkha state within <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. They say their hilly homeland is different from the flatlands around the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>, and that they are ethnically distinct from the Bengalis The Gurkhas say about 1.4 million Gurkha people live around Darjeeling and 4.6 million live elsewhere in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. They first came here in the 1850s to make their way as soldiers or as workers on tea plantations. Ghising, a former army corporal, teacher and bantamweight boxer, says government force can only aggravate the problem. `` By provoking us, by killing or wounding our men, the government is creating wounded tigers,'' he said. `` You know what a wounded tiger does? It hunts for men and devours them.'' Nowadays, only police officers are seen at night outside the quaint, old houses built by the British who developed Darjeeling as a `` hill station.'' Fears have worsened since April 6 when school principal <PERSON> Dileswar </PERSON> <PERSON> Rai </PERSON>'s severed head was found in <LOCATION> Kalimpong </LOCATION>, 43 miles east of Darjeeling. He had kept his school open during a general strike called by Gurkha militants. The severed head of <PERSON> Nirmal </PERSON> <PERSON> Rai </PERSON>, a reporter for a local newspaper, was found at the same place April 12. The journalist, who was not related to the principal, was accused of being a police informer. The government's response to the violence has been building up a force of more than 4,000 security forces and paramilitary police who often open fire with mortars and machine guns. `` We are fighting a very well entrenched enemy and the terrain is in their favor,'' said <PERSON> Raj </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanojia </PERSON>, a police superintendent in charge of anti-insurgency operations. Amid the violence, the tea and tourist trades are suffering. A backlash by Marxist-controlled unions has forced 30,000 Gurkha laborers to flee from tea estates to refugee camps in Darjeeling and the adjoining state of <LOCATION> Sikkim </LOCATION>. Gurkha insurgents have felled at least 2,000 pine trees to block roads. More than 600 homes have been burned by insurgents or Marxists who support the <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION> government. More than 250 government buildings have been set ablaze, including two stations of the `` Toy Train,'' built in 1879 by the British and so called for its tiny cars and narrow-gauge track. The Gurkha campaign also has triggered fears for the security of the seven strategically important northeastern states near <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, with whom <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has a long-standing border dispute. The northeast, an area about the size of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, is connected to the main part of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> by a narrow land corridor called the <LOCATION> Siliguri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Neck </LOCATION> in the envisoned <LOCATION> Gurkhaland </LOCATION>. Ghising, the Gurkha leader, now brushed aside the question of secession. `` We are Indians and we will remain Indians,'' he said. But Ghising, who also is the author of more than 20 racy, potboiler novels in the Nepali language, made it clear he is not going to give in without achieving his goals. He sits in an office guarded by tough-looking <PERSON> Gurkas </PERSON> with their traditonal curved, 14-inch kukri knives. Behind him is a green <LOCATION> Gurkhaland </LOCATION> flag emblazoned with a kukri and three stars. He reeled off his demands: _ Recognition of Nepali as an official Indian language _ More government jobs for Gurkhas _ Better education and more industry `` If we do not get statehood for <LOCATION> Gurkhaland </LOCATION>, the Indian government will regret it,'' he added. `` They have seen only a flash of Gurkha retaliation, Gurkha courage, Gurkha dedication, but if we are pushed, we will start a full scale, non-stop retaliation.'' About 48,000 retired Gurkha soldiers live in Darjeeling, and Indian officials fear they could join <PERSON> Ghising </PERSON>'s campaign. Above the town, a giant graffiti painted on a mountain slope shows blood dripping from a kukri knife. Below it reads: `` Welcome to <LOCATION> Gurkhaland </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
