<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Killing Goes on in Sikh War for Independent Homeland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Companion stories are BC-India-Wars-Gurkhas, b0603, and
BC-India-Wars-Buddhists, b0605.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The killing goes on as it has for six years and the prospects for peace talks have grown slimmer in the war waged by Sikh militants for an autonomous homeland in the Indian state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. In an apparent move to open peace talks, Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> freed a radical Sikh priest from jail, but then he said he would talk only within the framework of the Indian Constitution. The militants responded that they will not negotiate until the government accepts their demand for the independent Sikh nation of <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION>, a concept that is very much outside the Consititution. `` We will continue tofight in the same manner until we get Khalistan,'' said <PERSON> Jagir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Panthic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, an underground umbrella grouping of militant Sikh groups. `` It is not a demand,'' he said in an interview. `` It is our right.'' Sikhs make up 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Sikh militants claim they are being subjugated by Hindus, who form 80 percent of the population. The Sikh agitation has claimed at least 735 lives this year and the violence has worsened recently. More than 350 people have been killed in the six weeks since <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> freed the radical Sikh priest <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON> from jail. The killings blamed on <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> militias have raised fears that the government would turn a harsher face toward <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. At the same time the priest was freed, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> pushed through <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> a bill that would allow the government to clamp emergency rule on <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, severely limiting individual rights. <PERSON> Jagir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was asked in the interview if he expected a government move to drive out the radicals who have taken refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> holy place in <LOCATION> Amitsar </LOCATION>. `` We are ready for an attack,'' he said. He characterized the militants' attitude with a <LOCATION> Punjabi </LOCATION> proverb: `` A brick will be replied to with a stone.'' Indian officials seek to play down the possibility of a raid on the temple. An army raid in 1984 left more than 1,200 people dead, most of them Sikhs, and the desecration of the shrine angered the entire Sikh community. Five months later, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s mother, was assassinated by Sikh bodyguards in an act of revenge. Police officers in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> see little hope that conciliatory moves by the government would end the violence. `` These people kill nearly 10 people every day,'' said <PERSON> Izhar </PERSON> <PERSON> Alam </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district police superintendent. `` We must take strong action.'' He added this should include sending security forces into the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, where about 100 armed militants are believed to have taken shelter. <PERSON> Alam </PERSON> also said police alone could not raid the temple complex. `` Other forces will have to be included,'' he said. `` The militants have AK-47 automatic rifles and carbines. All we -LRB- the police -RRB- have is .303 rifles and pistols.'' The biggest impediment to any plan to raid the militants' sanctuary is a threat held out by <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>, the freed priest `` If the government enters the temple, they will be laying the foundation for <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION>,'' Rode said. He spoke at a meeting April 13 of about 40,000 Sikhs in south <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. It was his first major appearance since his release and there were reports he would encourage moderation among the militants and that a peaceful approach would come from the meeting. But most speakers urged more agitation. While Rode did not directly support moves for <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION>, he called for continuing a movement to `` free Sikhs from the bonds of slavery.'' `` His demands are the same as ours,'' <PERSON> Jagir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said a day later. Rode, named to the most influential Sikh religious post shortly after his release, denies entering into any deals with authorities. He says the only way for a solution is for the government to talk directly to the Sikh militants. Even moderate Sikhs believe the government should make the first move for peace, such as freeing hundreds of Sikh youths jailed as suspected militants. <PERSON> Devinder </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a farmer at the mass meeting of Sikhs, said the government first has to prove it wants a settlement. `` People in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> distrust the government,'' he said. `` We have been let down too many times. Let them offer something first.''
</TEXT>
