<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Little-Known Buddhist Bush War Still Rages inside Bangladesh</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Companion stories are BC-India-Wars-Gurkhas, b0603, and
India-Wars-Sikhs, b0604.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELONIA HILLS, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Makeshift Buddhist pagodas dot the jungle across the border from here in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. But the rumble of military vehicles and, sometimes, bursts of gunfire shatter the tranquil setting, reminders that a little-known bush war that began 11 years ago still rages. The hymns of monks are silenced as terror flashes through the refugee camps filled with Chakma tribespeople on this side of the border. The Chakmas, descendants of the warlike <ORGANIZATION> Mongols </ORGANIZATION> who once surged across <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, are fighting the <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> government to hold onto their land, their <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> religion and their age-old customs against an influx of Moslem settlers. Chakma guerrilla leaders say at least 4,000 people have died in the cycle of killings and bloody reprisals since the Chakmas took up arms in May 1977 and killed 40 <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> policemen in their first ambush. The battle is vicious, unequal, unremitting and rarely reported. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> seldom allows foreign reporters to visit the Chakmas' ancestral homeland in the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> Tracts <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> does not permit foreign journalists to travel to its border states housing the refugees, but Indian reporters can make the trip with police permission. The <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> Tracts, which roll over 5,138 square miles in southern <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, border <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and the northeastern Indian states of <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mizoram </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Belonia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> is the region in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION> state that faces the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> Tracts. In camouflage uniforms of war, <LOCATION> Bangladeshi </LOCATION> soldiers move from village to village in the deep woods and jungles of the hill tracts, often firing at random to frighten away the Chakmas, sometimes to kill them, said <PERSON> Bakul </PERSON> <PERSON> Chakma </PERSON>, a refugee at the <LOCATION> Takumbari </LOCATION> camp 10 miles from the border. The battle, often fought at midnight on jungle paths traveled by elephants and reptiles, pits 20,000 Bangladeshi soldiers and 40,000 paramilitary troops and policemen against 4,000 guerrillas. In the past two years, more than 50,000 tribespeople have fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION> state to avoid the fighting. `` We tried enough persuasion. When nothing worked, we took up arms,'' said <PERSON> Priti </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Chakma </PERSON>, a leader of the tribespeople's `` <PERSON> Shanti </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahini </PERSON>,'' or Army for Peace `` What option do we have other than killing those who want to finish us?'' the 41-year-old guerrilla said in an interview arranged on condition the location not be disclosed. In 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights organization, said it had received `` increasing reports of arbitrary arrests, torture and extrajudicial executions'' of tribespeople in the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> Tracts by Bangladeshi troops. President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s government in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> has denied the allegations. It says it wants to develop the area and has pledged the local currency equivalent of $ 90 million to help tribesmen come down from the hills and join mainstream society. Islam is the official religion of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, and about 80 percent of its 105 million people are Moslems. The remainder are Hindus, Buddhists and Christians. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s government in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, about 200 miles northwest of the hill tracts, says it is absurd for the Chakmas to demand 11 percent of the land in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> when they make up less than 0.5 percent percent of the population. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> is one of the world's most densely populated nations. Most of the 600,000 tribespeople in the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> Tracts are Chakmas. The others are Mogs and Tripuraies. So far about 300,000 Moslems have settled in the area and thousands of Chakmas have been evicted from their homes in the deep woods and moved to what the <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> government calls `` ideal villages.'' `` The so-called ideal villages are nothing but concentration camps,'' charged <PERSON> Bimal </PERSON> <PERSON> Larma </PERSON>, a Chakma guerrilla. In addition to land, the Chakmas are demanding autonomy, but this has been rejected by the government. The tribespeople, who speak a mixture of Tibetan-Burmese dialects, fear they will become a minority in the hills where they have lived for centuries. Their political wing, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, charges that some tribespeople have been forcibly converted to Islam and that Moslem settlers are encouraged to marry <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> girls. `` We have no similarities at all with the Moslems,'' said refugee <PERSON> Ranjit </PERSON> <PERSON> Narayan </PERSON>. `` We love pork; they despise it. We worship <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON>; they follow Islam. Unless forced, we do not kill, but they kill us at the slightest provocation.'' <PERSON> Narayan </PERSON>, 54, fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1986 with his wife, four sons and a daughter. `` I have seen my neighboring villages being burned, women raped and men killed. I told my wife, ` We ca n't stay here anymore. Let us go.''' he said. They walked four days to reach <PERSON> Takumbari </PERSON>, the largest of seven refugee camps in <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION>. The camps, which house 50,586 refugees, have no electricity. The houses are made of bamboo and roofed with dry leaves. Since <PERSON> Takumbari </PERSON> was set up two years ago, it's population has swollen to 15,510. In that time, 546 people have died of disease and 549 children have been born. The Indian government gives each adult and teen-ager a daily ration of 14 ounces of rice and about two ounces each a day of lentils and dry fish, plus 20 paise -LRB- about one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cent -RRB-. Children under 12 get half-rations. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> has accused <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> of aiding the Chakma rebels. `` This is absurd. We have enough problems of our own,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tripura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burman </PERSON> said. `` We are helping the Chakmas on purely humanitarian grounds. `` We can not push them back, it would mean certain death for them.''
</TEXT>
