<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Zelly and Me''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Once upon a time in Hollywood the `` woman's picture'' held sway. <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women flocked to matinees and sobbed and sympathized with the plight of such stars as <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON>. No more. Movie matinees are largely populated by small fry and weary shoppers in malls. `` Zelly and Me'' arrives a few decades late. It is patently a woman's picture: the writer-director, co-producer and leading performers are women. However, despite the best performance yet by <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossellini </PERSON>, the film can not escape a pervading preciousness, and its chances of finding a wide audience of both sexes seem slender indeed. The Zelly of the title is <PERSON> Mademoiselle </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Rossellini </PERSON> -RRB-, the European nanny whose life is devoted to her young charge, the orphaned <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> -RRB-. They live in a mansion presided over by <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>'s autocratic grandmother, Coco -LRB- <PERSON> Glynis </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> -RRB-. Zelly and <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON> occupy a fantasy world of stuffed animals, all with special names and identities, and they share a devotion to the legend of <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Arc -LRB- filmgoers will recall that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossellini </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Ingrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergman </PERSON>, portrayed <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Arc on the screen -RRB- For reasons that are n't quite clear, <PERSON> Coco </PERSON> punishes the child for faultless infractions. The punishments become more severe, even sadistic. <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>, whose parents were killed in a fiery plane crash, burns herself in retaliation. The nanny helplessly watches <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>'s torment, finding solace only in day-off meetings with the neighbor in another mansion -LRB- <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> -RRB-. When Zelly is fired by the enraged grandmother, the pair dream up a scheme to spirit away <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>. The conclusion brings happiness to no one. `` Zelly and Me'' is the first feature film by <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Rathborne </PERSON>, and it appears at least partly autobiographical. Her attention to the details of girlhood becomes almost unbearably cloying, and only in the latter portions does the film gain any momentum. Within the confines of a largely ineffectual role, <PERSON> Rossellini </PERSON> performs with an inner radiance hauntingly like her mother's. <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>, absent too long from the screen, is effective in a seemingly unrewarding role. <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> is a gifted young actress, fully capable of occupying the screen by herself. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, director of `` Blue Velvet,'' makes his acting debut as the neighbor who is not what he seems. He seems stiff in the role, needful of the direction of, say, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> release was produced by <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>. The rating is PG; small children might be frightened by the girl's punishment. Running time: 87 minutes.
</TEXT>
