<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION> _ At the start of `` Weeds,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Umstetter </PERSON>, doing a life sentence for armed robbery, attempts suicide twice _ once by leaping from his cell block at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION>, and once by a crude attempt at hanging himself. `` Depressed, are you?'' asks his cell mate. `` Well, I needed a little vacation,'' replies the droll <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolte </PERSON>. That's about as deep as the explanations get in `` Weeds,'' a flat, humorless film based on a play by a real-life ex-con who, like <PERSON> Umstetter </PERSON>, was confined to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state penitentiary. In the film, <PERSON> Umstetter </PERSON> decides to channel his rage and frustration into creativity. With only a 6th grade education, he reads <PERSON> Dostoevski </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON>, Nietszche and <PERSON> Genet </PERSON>. Borrowing a bit too liberally from his readings, he writes a play about prison life called `` Weeds.'' It's produced in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> and, unaccountably, there happens to be a rich, beautiful critic in the audience named <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Binghamton </PERSON>. Equally unaccountably, eyes meet and, presto, it's amore. <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>, writes a rave review and campaigns successfully to free her new-found love from prison. It turns out, though, she is n't much of a critic since she failed to perceive that the play is largely plagiarized. Later in the movie, she catches <PERSON> Umstetter </PERSON> in bed with a younger woman. There's a touch of chagrin from this person who has freed her lover from a life in prison. But in a moment or so, it's forgotten <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON>, in short, is incredibly dimwitted. The movie winds on episodically, with <PERSON> Umstetter </PERSON> forming a traveling acting troupe made up of his old jail buddies. They take it on the road, finally making it to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> drama critic takes the wind temporarily out of their sails. But by this time the play is not the counterfeit it started out to be. It's so real, in fact, that they produce it in a prison and cause a riot. Presto! Instant headlines and fame, and the bright lights of <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. Sure. Right. `` Weeds'' is rated `` R'' for strong prison language and some nudity. _ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> Education Writer.
