<TEXT>
 `` House of Games'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION>, VHS @ Beta, $ 89.99, Rated R -RRB- `` House of Games'' is set in the seedy underworld of con artists, and the movie is _ deliberately _ something of a con itself. Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>, who wrote and directed this 1980's film noir, repeatedly confounds the viewer by staging increasingly elaborate confidence games. It's often difficult to be sure who's conning whom, and that's what makes the movie such creepy fun. <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Crouse </PERSON> plays Dr. <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, a psychiatrist who has just made a lot of money writing a book but who is clearly unhappy, maybe even clinically depressed. On an impulse, she decides to help a patient who is a compulsive gambler and visits the House of Games where she encounters <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>, the ringleader of the con artists, played by <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Mantegna </PERSON>. She is strongly attracted to <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> and also to the excitement of his dangerous profession. In a series of plot twists she moves from victim to accomplice to aggressor, drawn ever deeper into a web of deceit that seems certain eventually to destroy her. <PERSON> Crouse </PERSON>, who is married to <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>, is fascinating in a role tailor-made for her, while <PERSON> Mantegna </PERSON> has just the right oily charm for his part. All in all, `` House of Games'' is an original, diverting film and well worth a look for those who missed it in theaters last year. _ By <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
