<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Hairspray'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ various artists. `` Dirty Dancing'' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ various artists. `` More Dirty Dancing'' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ various artists. `` Do You Love Me?'' by the Contours is one of peaks of rock' n' roll, matching depth of anxiety to banality of lyric in the finest tradition of the Clearasil generation `` You broke my heart,'cause I could n't dance ...'' Ah, what a world of pain recalled. Then there's that trick fade, before the Contours come booming back _ `` Work! Work!'' _ in an ecstatic finale. Great as it is, `` Do You Love Me?'' does n't rescue the `` Dirty Dancing'' soundtrack albums from the contempt of all prudent consumers. RCA has spread this collection on two compact discs, giving as little as 35 minutes of retread listening in a format that would hold twice as much. So they're charging $ 25 or more for what is essentially a $ 2 record in the oldies bin. The real sin, though, is the mixture of old and new. Oldies, as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Waters </PERSON> says, are `` the only known remedy to today's Hit Parade of Hell.'' The soundtrack collection from Waters' first mainstream film, `` Hairspray,'' is the better buy. The title track, despite its satirical intent, is absolutely faithful to the old sound. But again, the exasperated consumer wonders, why no instructions for dancing the <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> along with `` The Madison Time'' by The <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> <PERSON> Combo </PERSON>? Through such indifference, the old tribal wisdom is in danger of being lost. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Naked'' -LRB- Sire -RRB- _ Talking Heads Too often on `` Naked,'' it's impossible even to guess what the Talking Heads are talking about. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s oblique lyrics are frustrating because there are snatches of wonderful imagery that leave the listener begging for more details. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s eccentricity probably is n't the only reason it's hard to find a plot in `` Naked.'' The Talking Heads recorded the basic tracks before <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> began to work on the tune or words, reducing his flexibility as a composer. But while the record's melodies and lyrics are less than fluid, rhythmically `` Naked'' is a marvel _ so lively it would make even <PERSON> Tipper </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> want to dance. The Talking Heads brought in studio musicians to create a denser sound than on their last two records. As a result, instruments dart in and out of the arrangements, almost always serving to enhance the syncopation. The band and its co-producer, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Lillywhite </PERSON>, achieved a full but remarkably clean sound. Most momentous is the satirical `` -LRB- Nothing But -RRB- Flowers,'' in which <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> provides a fresh perspective on urban sprawl by describing with mock horror a place where `` highways and cars were sacrificed for agriculture.'' `` Mr. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>'' and `` Totally Nude'' are also made for the dance floor, while the best of the slower songs is the darkly melodic `` <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>,'' about a fat man, a little girl and a gun. What happens? We do n't know. The song, like too much of `` Naked,'' is clothed in ambiguity. _ By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Tracy Chapman'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Elektra </ORGANIZATION> @ Asylum -RRB- _ <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> One of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s best kept secrets was a young poet-songwriter-folksinger named <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. Not any more. With the release of her self-titled debut LP the world has a new musical gift. Her rich contralto with its melancholic underpinnings sweep us back to the early 1970s _ to <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. Her lyrics, with a deadbolt look at poverty, racism and inequality take us back even further _ to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Odetta </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Seeger </PERSON>. The LP opens with `` Talkin' Bout a Revolution,'' a song that tells of `` standing in the welfare lines, crying at the doorsteps of those armies of salvation, wasting time in the unemployment lines, sitting around waiting for a promotion.'' The a cappella `` Behind the Wall,'' talks of a domestic fight: `` Last night I heard the screaming, then a silence that chilled my soul.'' As an undergraduate at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> performed in coffee houses and clubs. She was something of a mesmerizing hit for locals who flocked to hear her. Her debut LP, with its range from folk to pop ballad to reggae, is likely to enchant even more. _ By <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editor </ORGANIZATION>.
