<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Arts For Human Survival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The singing of whales, the howl of wolves and the trilling of a Grand Canyon wren filled the 800-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in the university city of <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>. It was a new kind of music for the venerable <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> building, within the walls of <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. When the six casually dressed American musicians recently emulated the sounds of the wild on drums and tambourine, the audience was so intrigued they got up from their seats to look over the choir rails. From among the medieval tombs came music that `` celebrates the environment,'' as band leader <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON> described it. Winter, who lives in <LOCATION> Litchfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, calls the animals and birds whose sounds he incorporates in his group's compositions, `` our members at large. The Paul Winter Consort combines classical jazz and folk instruments drawn from the European and African roots of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> culture. The result is daring, fascinating and never dull. `` I have never heard anything which was so unexpected and so charming at the same time,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> teacher who wandered into the concert without being invited. The group played in the cathedral for participants from 60 countries at a conference of religious leaders and legislators discussing how they can use their influence to help solve problems of the planet, from the threat of nuclear war to pollution and poverty. `` I can feel his music; it's not just something to listen to,'' said <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Head </PERSON>, a business consultant from <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, who was helping to run the conference. The two-hour concert ended with Winter putting out the lights and inviting the audience to howl like the wolves. They did. `` It breaks the ice,'' he said with a smile. Winter and his group are artists-in-residence at the Cathedral of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> the Divine in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, whose Dean <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> was co-chairman of the conference and invited the group to <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Halley </PERSON>, the group's pianist, is the cathedral organist and music director. Winter plays soprano saxophone, <PERSON> Rhonda </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> plays flute, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Friesen </PERSON> plays the cello and <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Velez </PERSON> are the percussionists. Winter said in an interview he was first inspired to put animal sounds in his music when he heard recordings 20 years ago of whale songs made off the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. He and his musicians have played in 33 countries and made 10 visits to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where they toured wilderness areas. `` I think the only composer who imitated natural sounds before us is the Frenchman, <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> <PERSON> Messiaen </PERSON>, who notated the songs of all French birds,'' Winter said. Thanks to <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>'s enthusiasm for the arts, the <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> conference had the rare treat of an arts program to itself, with music, songs and sculpture. It was coordinated by <PERSON> Naj </PERSON> <PERSON> Wikoff </PERSON>, a 38-year-old sculptor who presents more than 200 drama, dance, music and poetry performances a year at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> the Divine. The conference had its own anthem, a 2 -LCB- piece called, `` Alpha Code: The Beginning,'' composed by American concert pianist <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Janis </PERSON>. `` The conference is every man's struggle,'' <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said. `` The music starts with a prayer, then an SOS, and then the prayer is taken up by more and more people and becomes an expression of triumph over the problems. `` I call it a response to a distress signal from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, because that's what the conference is about.'' <PERSON> Wikoff </PERSON> said no one should see anything unusual in a conference grappling with global crises listening to music. `` Arts celebrate the human spirit and always have done,'' he said. `` The arts transcend society. People need not only food and a bed but a sense of hope and beauty.''
