<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Romancing Nelson Algren</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This city, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> once said, `` has literally become my trade.'' <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>, the winner of the first National Book Award, lived among the ethnic patches of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Side </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, bringing to life the roar of the elevated trains and recording, in his mind and in notebooks, the travails of the people. He hung out in the police precincts, seedy bars and brothels. Drug addicts, gamblers and migrant workers had his ear. The night often was his turf and his fiction breathed the night. `` It is n't hard to love a town for its greater and its lesser towers,'' <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> wrote. `` But you never truly love it till you can love its alleys, too.'' The city he loved did n't always return the sentiment. Poles, offended with his sketches of the city's underbelly in `` Never Come Morning,'' pressured some library branches to keep the book out of circulation, <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> and his literary companions maintained. But today, seven years after he died at age 72 in <LOCATION> Sag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, there's a romance brewing and it might finally stick. A large exhibition room at the library's downtown Cultural Center is the setting for `` Writing in the First Person: <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>,'' a rich tribute to a master of urban realism. First edition books and original manuscripts are paired with <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>'s first stabs at writing, including handwritten short stories, a mock newspaper's front page and summaries of neighborhood baseball games. His Army draft card is displayed with his honorable discharge, as well as his <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> birth certificate _ March 28, 1909 _ and papers showing his name change from <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahlgren </PERSON> <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> to <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>. Pictures and personal letters document his affair with French philosopher <PERSON> Simone </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON> who accompanied him on trips down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and to other countries. <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> admired <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> and the affection was mutual. `` You should not read it unless you can take a punch,'' <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> says in a well-worn letter, offering his endorsement for an upcoming book. `` Mr. <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> wrote, `` boy, you are good.'' The exhibit, which opened in late February, was scheduled to run through May 21 but has been extended for three weeks. Most of the items were purchased from local collectors or are on loan from <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which has the largest Algren archive. Besides the exhibit, there also have been public readings. Hundreds turned out to hear Pulitzer Prize winner <PERSON> Studs </PERSON> <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON>, another product of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s literary school of realism and a close friend of <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>, read from <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>'s books, including the poetic `` <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, City on the Make.'' `` He was a wheel on fire,'' <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> recalled in a interview. `` I like the idea that he was honored. It's time he was given his place.'' <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> when he was 3, graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> with a journalism degree in 1931. His first published works, mostly short stories, stemmed from his experiences in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> where he traveled by freight train after college. <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> said he once wandered into a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> college and began typing a story on an unattended typewriter. He decided to take the typewriter with him to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to finish the story, but was arrested for theft and served five months in jail. Back in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, he was an editor for the Works Progress Administration from 1936-40. Finally, `` Never Come Morning,'' about a Polish prizefighter tagged with a murder charge, was published in 1942. It was a book that rankled Polish civic groups for its gritty descriptions of life in their <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> neighborhoods. `` He was never a coffee table man,'' <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> said, referring to <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>'s books. In 1947, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> and Letters awarded him $ 1,000 in recognition for `` Never Come Morning,'' and the <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> granted him $ 1,000 to work on a new novel _ arguably his best _ `` The Man With the Golden Arm.'' <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> received the first National Book Award in 1950 for `` The Man With the Golden Arm,'' a harrowing tale about <PERSON> Frankie </PERSON> <PERSON> Machine </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> card dealer, back from the war with a `` 35-pound monkey on his back'' _ morphine addiction. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Preminger </PERSON> made the book into a movie starring <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Preminger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> fought fiercely over the production and the bitter <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> experience was one the author would never forget. Another book, `` A Walk on the Wild Side,'' also was transferred to the big screen starring <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON>. He had his detractors. Conservative critics hit <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> for what they considered his penchant for glorifying hustlers, hookers and hobos. One once dismissed him as the `` bard of the stumblebum.'' `` Academics, the English departments, had become the arbiters of literature,'' <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> was never one who was in their favor. He sort of put them down and they knew it. They reciprocated by making him a nonperson. Now he's pretty much a person and that's kind of good. By the early 1970s, <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> had traveled to <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, writing dispatches for magazines and developing more books. At the same time, his ties to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> began to diminish. In 1973, he left for good. But anyone who 12 years earlier had read his afterword to `` <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, City on the Make'' could have predicted the move. The city that was once a writer's town, he said, was becoming just another town. `` <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> has progressed, culturally, from being The Second City to being The Second-Hand City,'' he wrote. `` The vital cog in our culture now is not the artist, but the middleman whose commercial status lends art the aura of status when he acquires a collection of originals. `` The word ` culture' now means nothing more than ` approved.' It is n't what is exhibited so much that matters as where: that being where one meets the people who matter.'' <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> tried to explain: `` To love a city, you have to smack it around, too. It was the ambivalent feeling he had.'' <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, to cover the murder case of boxer <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> `` Hurricane'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. A novel based on the case, `` The Devil's Stocking,'' was published posthumously in 1983. He settled in <LOCATION> Sag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and died, relatively poor, a few weeks before his May 1981 induction into the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> and Letters. Money was an irritating subject to <PERSON> Algren </PERSON>. Authors with less talent were wealthy, he complained, and <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> producers reaped millions without spreading the credit to creators. But in an interview published in 1964, <PERSON> Algren </PERSON> seemed to suggest that writing good fiction, not collecting cash, was his goal. `` I think anybody, anybody, if given the choice, would always take the privilege of having his work wanted by other people rather than the privilege of having more money than anybody.''
</TEXT>
