<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Domino Adv13-15   05-02 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Domino, Adv 13-15,0834</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv13-15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 13-15 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Making A Hard Day's Night Easier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's 2 a.m., and your baby is crying and wo n't sleep. What to do? Play the Beatles, of course, and within 15 minutes a hard day's night becomes much easier. Award-winning pianist <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Domino </PERSON> has turned the music of the Fab Four into an album of lullabies designed to send bawling infants straight to <LOCATION> Sleepytown </LOCATION>. `` A lot of adults say it works,'' says the 35-year-old musician from <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The album, `` Baby Road,'' is a takeoff of the <ORGANIZATION> Beatles </ORGANIZATION>' 1969 LP `` Abbey Road.'' It contains 12 songs, including 11 hits of the famed group and the title track written by Domino. The LP also parodies the `` Abbey Road'' cover, which showed the four <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> lads walking single file across a street. `` Baby Road'' shows four diapered tots strutting one behind the other across the road. `` These lullabies are dedicated to all children and their tired moms and dads,'' Domino writes on the album cover. Beatles' songs on the LP are `` Hey Jude,'' `` Yesterday,'' `` <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON>,'' `` Something,'' `` With a Little Help From My Friends,'' `` Norwegian Wood,'' `` For No One,'' `` In My Life,'' `` She's Leaving Home,'' `` Here, There and Everywhere'' and `` Good Night.'' `` I did n't try to compete with the Beatles, just be true to their music and not use a lot of hot licks,'' said <PERSON> Domino </PERSON>, who played with country star <PERSON> Waylon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> for four years. He got the idea for the album when his wife was pregnant. `` This is so much better than ` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Had </PERSON> a Little Lamb,''' he said. `` I tried to make them sound as simple as possible, but a lot of production was involved. `` I let the melodies come up by using the upper modes of the piano. The Beatles are very identifiable. You can play the melody and not be a slave to any original arrangement. `` I thought of their songs that could be acoustical and simple where you do n't tamper with the song and it brings it out. Some of the melodies worked and others would not.'' The only other musicians on the LP are <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, who played upright bass, and guitarist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. The selections are strictly instrumentals without any lyrics. `` A lot of the songs are better without words, like ` She's Leaving Home. People think of their daughter leaving or about an unhappy teen-ager,'' <PERSON> Domino </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. He said he chose `` Yesterday'' for `` the purity of the medley. It's a song you have to include when you do a Beatles' lullaby record. The sound is very simple: The guitar carries the rhythm and the piano plays the melody well and draws attention to the song.'' He said `` Hey Jude'' has a strong emotional impact on people, especially parents. `` The theme is take a sad song and make it better. The song means so much to a person because they think of the words. The song triggers memories and emotions and it makes parents so happy to be sharing them with their kids.'' Domino, who's been playing piano since age 5, says he rates `` Michelle'' as the Beatles' hit with the best melody. `` I would play it a lot before I recorded this,'' he recalled. `` I always loved playing it.'' Some Beatles' songs did not fit well. `` Help!'' was too uptempo for a peaceful arrangement. Domino was wary of the stringed instruments used in `` The Long and Winding Road.'' `` Let It Be,'' he said, `` had an identifiable arrangement and I was reluctant to tackle it.'' He hopes to do a follow-up project, which like the first will be on his own Golliber Records in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>. The next album will include some of the Beatles' songs he had to omit from the first. Domino, born and raised in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, had a featured part in the song `` One O'clock Jump'' which won a Grammy award in 1978 for the country group Asleep at the Wheel. After leaving the group, he played piano in the Broadway production `` The Best Little Whorehouse in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' He then joined <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>' band, but quit two years ago in order to spend more time at home. The `` Baby Road'' project has been more rewarding for him than playing on the road. `` I get great letters from parents saying they are glad I did this record,'' he said. `` It's been a lot of fun and much more personal. I save every letter I get.'' His 2 -LCB- - year-old son, <PERSON> Will </PERSON>, who helped inspire the project, has a favorite song on the LP: `` Something. But it's a winner by default. `` He'd fall asleep so quickly he never listened all the way through,'' <PERSON> Domino </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 13-15</NOTE>
