 The economy reversed a three-month slowdown in April as production and new orders picked up sharply, according to a survey of purchasing managers. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purchasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managers </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday its index of economic activity rose to 54.9 percent last month from 53.3 percent in March. The index had declined the first three months of the year, indicating a slowing in economic growth. A reading above 50 percent generally indicates economic expansion, while a reading below that benchmark indicates the economy is declining, the group says. __ <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The government's economic indicators are pointing to continued growth. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday its Index of Leading Indicators rose 0.8 percent in March after a revised 1.3 percent gain in February. In another report, the government said sales of new homes rose 4 percent in March, the second consecutive monthly advance. Earlier in the week, the government said the overall economy expanded at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first three months of the year. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, called the string of upbeat reports `` terrific news on the future state of the economy.''
