<HEAD>Grain Millers at Archer Daniels Midland Reject Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the grain millers union at <ORGANIZATION> Archer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daniels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have voted by a 3-1 margin to reject the agricultural company's three-year contract proposal. But the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 103 also agreed to work under the old contract terms while negotiations continue, an official said. The old contract expires today. According to Local 103 President <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON>, members needed about four hours to examine the numerous differences between the current pact and the proposal. Hood categorized the 44-page document as containing `` excessive concessionary demands.'' After turning down the proposal, the local agreed to have a federal mediator set the next meeting between management and the union. The move was also acceptable to <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION>'s negotiator, <PERSON> Hood </PERSON> said. Hood refused to comment on pay, insurance or other `` financial issues.'' Key issues, he said, concerned `` creating a joint management-labor safety program, trying to eliminate rotating shifts, extending time off for work-related injuries and basic civil rights in the plant.'' He declined to elaborate on the civil rights issue. `` The company has made it clear that the reason for these concessionary demands is for increased corporate profit,'' <PERSON> Hood </PERSON> said. `` It is difficult for the membership to understand in the face of past and projected profits that the company needs these additional concessions.''
