<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-FishingRights     05-02 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Fishing Rights,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Award Attorneys' Fees to Tribes in Fishing Rights
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to award nearly $ 3 million in attorneys' fees to Indian tribes who won a lengthy court battle against <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state officials over fishing rights. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that struck down the award on grounds a federal law reimbursing lawyers who represent the winning side in civil rights cases does not apply to the Indians' lawsuit. Twenty-one tribes sought to recapture legal fees awarded by a federal judge who then was overruled by the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The Indians were supported by 33 other tribes who said their ability to vindicate treaty rights could be undermined if they are unable to recover legal fees won in court. The case acted on today stems from a 1970 lawsuit in which Indians asserted fishing rights in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state waters based on a treaty signed in 1885. Indians relinquished land under the treaty in return for guarantees of fishing rights. The treaty said the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> have the `` right of taking fish at usual and accustomed grounds and stations ... in common with all citizens of the territory.'' Federal courts ultimately ruled the treaty entitled the tribes to approximately half the harvestable fish in state waters that passed through recognized tribal fishing areas. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld those rights in 1979. Years of litigation over legal fees followed, leading in 1985 to a federal judge's award of $ 2.95 million to the tribes to be paid by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. But the 9th Circuit court threw out the award last year. The appeals court said the fishing rights case was not covered by a 1976 federal law reimbursing the prevailing side's legal expenses in civil rights lawsuits. The appeals court said, in effect, that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state officials did not violate deliberately the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>' rights by limiting their fishing harvest. The case was a dispute over the intepretation of the treaty, the appeals court said. `` It is not disputed that the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> had rights under the treaty,'' the appeals court said. `` Just exactly what those rights were was unknown until the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision -LRB- in 1979. -RRB- If the state of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> violates these now known and well-delineated rights, there would be an actual conflict between state and federal law which might give rise'' to a federal civil rights lawsuit. The appeals court added: `` That, however, has not yet happened and is not the situation here.'' Therefore, there is no basis for the award of legal fees, it said. Indians said the ruling could be devastating to their efforts at enforcing treaty rights. `` Cases to vindicate treaty rights affecting important resources of an area may take years to complete because of the extreme sensitivity of the issues,'' said a group of 33 tribes who supported the appeal by the <LOCATION> Washigton </LOCATION> tribes `` Such cases are especially draining on normally scarce tribal resources.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> Makah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribe </ORGANIZATION> vs. State of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 87-1390.
</TEXT>
