<FIRST>u f AM-OPECStandoff Bjt   05-02 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC Standoff, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Stance Illustrates Depth of Rift With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-OPEC, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s scuttling of an <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> plan for token cuts in oil production may signal a stiffened Saudi resolve to hold down world oil prices and punish archenemy <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The Saudis appear increasingly intent on frustrating <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s efforts to galvanize a consensus for oil production cuts that could send prices higher this summer The result may be more in-fighting for the fractious Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and perhaps an even deeper political paralysis. Prices fell sharply Monday after <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> decided to suspend talks on a proposed 2 percent cutback in oil production until June. Most industry observers had expected the <LOCATION> Saudis </LOCATION> to go along with the cutback, since it was so small as to have virtually no effect on <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> evenues. An eight-country majority supported the cuts, which were to be taken in conjunction with cutbacks by a group of six independent oil-producing nations. The fact that Saudi Oil Minister <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> stood fast against the cuts appeared to mean the cartel's most influential member is unwilling to accept any <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> action that could lay the foundation for an Iranian-led price increase. Last December the Saudis successfully defeated an Iranian proposal to raise <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s official price by $ 2.70 a barrel, to $ 20.70. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> relies heavily on oil export revenues to finance its 7 -LCB- - year-old war against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has helped bankroll the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> war effort. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mlotok </PERSON>, who monitored the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he expected oil prices to slump this week and then hold steady until <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s June meeting. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members had hoped that by cutting back a little on production now, when world oil demand is relatively weak, prices would rebound and then jump even higher this summer during the traditional peak season for fuel consumption. By preventing an accord at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting, the Saudis probably ensured that any summer price increases will be small, limiting the benefit for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` This was, for the <LOCATION> Saudis </LOCATION>, a clear political victory,'' said <PERSON> Bahman </PERSON> <PERSON> Karbassioun </PERSON>, a Vienna-based oil consultant and former member of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> staff. He said he believed the Saudis never had any intention during the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting of striking a compromise deal. `` It was a very well organized and well planned'' effort by the Saudis to deny <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> the agreement it badly wanted, he said. Last week, two days before the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting started, the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> government announced it was breaking diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. It accused <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> of engaging in terrorism and subversion. <ORGANIZATION> Kazempour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ardebili </ORGANIZATION>, the deputy Iranian oil minister, said after the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> announcement that it may have been intended to spoil the atmosphere of the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting. <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, speaker of the Iranian Majlis, or parliament, on Sunday said the Saudi stalling on oil production cuts amounted to `` flagrant treachery'' orchestrated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have been rivals for power and influence within <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> from the early days of the cartel, which was formed in 1960 but did not gain a grip on pricing until the Arab oil embargo of 1973. In 1986, however, the Saudis and Iranians appeared to reach a tacit understanding to work together following a price crash that sent oil below $ 10 a barrel. The fragile alliance began to unravel last summer after rioting at the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, killed 402 people, most of them Iranian. As long as relations between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> remain poor, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is likely to encounter major problems holding oil prices steady, let alone raising them to the official target of $ 18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> has covered <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1982.
