<HEAD>LTV's Profit Up 12.7 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported its profit rose 12.7 percent in the first quarter from a year earlier, boosted by gains from the company's reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws. The diversified steel and aerospace giant said Monday that its first-quarter profit increased to $ 163.9 million, or $ 1.16 a share, from $ 129.6 million, or $ 1 a share, in the first three months of 1987. The figure for the latest quarter includes a one-time special credit of $ 24.8 million resulting from the sale of two iron ore vessels. The rise in net income occurred despite a decline in first-quarter sales, to $ 1.88 billion from $ 1.91 billion a year earlier. `` The deferral of interest, pension and other costs while we are operating under the protection of Chapter 11 has greatly benefited both periods,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer. The company entered Chapter 11 protection from creditors in July 1986. Hay noted, however, that the deferrals of costs and expenses have resulted in claims which must be provided for in a plan of reorganization before <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> can emerge from bankruptcy. In January 1987, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> terminated and took control of the three pension plans of subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, assuming financial responsibility for $ 2.3 billion in unfunded liabilities. But in September, the pension agency returned trusteeship of the plans to <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, saying it took the step to curb abuse of the federal pension insurance program. It cited $ 252 million in profits the company reported for the first half of 1987 and <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s establishment of a new pension arrangement for its workers. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> has said it believes the agency's attempt to return trusteeship of the pension plans is illegal. Excluding the special credit for the sale of the vessels, the company said its operating income for the quarter rose to $ 151 million from $ 139.7 million a year earlier because of higher income from steel. Operating income from steel rose to $ 131.2 million from $ 101.1 million in the first quarter of 1987, while steel sales expanded to $ 1.3 billion from $ 1.2 billion. Income from <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s aircraft products division dropped to $ 11.3 million from $ 22.2 million, largely because of reduced activity following completion of the B-1B bomber program in the fourth quarter of 1987. Income from the energy products division rose to $ 2.6 million from $ 900,000 in the first three months of 1987.
