<HEAD>Management Group Says It Has Agreed To Buy Ms., Sassy Magazines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Managers of <ORGANIZATION> Fairfax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- said Monday they have agreed to buy Ms. and Sassy magazines from the company's Australian parent for an undisclosed price. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>, president and chief executive of the newly formed <ORGANIZATION> Matilda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON>'s vice president, said they expected to close the deal on May 20. <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> said no changes were planned at either monthly magazine. <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fairfax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, acquired Ms. magazine last September. Unconfirmed reports had placed the purchase price at between $ 10 million and $ 15 million. Sassy, a new magazine aimed at teen-age girls, was launched in March. <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> had previously estimated startup costs at $ 10 million. <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> was taken private in December, and <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> said the company decided to sell the magazines to pay off some of its debts. <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> said she and Summers held an option to purchase the magazines, and they decided to exercise it after arranging financing from an unidentified venture capital group and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. `` This financial deal provides us with the best opportunity for the growth of Ms. and Sassy, while maintaining their independence,'' she said. She said the `` working capital we have been able to secure is equivalent to what <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> would have invested had their plans remained intact.'' Ms., which was founded 16 years ago by <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinem </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Carbine </PERSON>, has recently increased its rate base to 500,000 copies a month from 450,000. No circulation figures have been released for Sassy, but <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> said the magazine has `` well and truly made its rate base of 250,000.'' She said other parties had inquired about the magazines, but she was unaware of any other firm bids for the two publications, which were put up for sale in the middle of March.
