<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   05-02 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Surplus Falls 7.2 Percent In Fiscal Year 1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A surge in imports caused <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade surplus to fall 7.2 percent to $ 94.3 billion in the 1987 fiscal year, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. The report confirmed the continuing strength of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy in spite of the strong Japanese yen, which hurts the competitiveness of Japanese products in domestic and overseas markets. Exports grew 10.5 percent to $ 233.4 billion, but imports grew even faster, rising 26.9 percent to $ 139.1 billion. Both figures, measured on a balance-of-payments basis, were records. The report did not provide a breakdown of where <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s imports were coming from. But other recent figures have shown that the biggest growth is from the newly industrialized countries of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. Growth of imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been sluggish. The trade surplus of $ 94.28 billion in the fiscal year ended March 31, although smaller than the 1986 surplus of $ 101.65 billion, was the second highest on record. The report demonstrated that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is still able to increase its exports at a double-digit pace in spite of the drag of the strong yen. At the same time, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s burgeoning consumer economy is sucking in more imports. Imports have also risen because Japanese exporters are getting more of their components from abroad. <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials noted that the composition of Japanese imports has shifted, with a larger share now consisting of manufactured goods rather than raw materials. Government programs aimed at reducing trade friction by limiting the economy's reliance on exports and encouraging domestic demand played a role in cutting the trade surplus. `` Although the higher value of the Japanese yen had an effect, the main cause of the fall in the trade surplus is the government's program to boost imports,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity `` These statistics show that the government's effort to change the country's industrial structure and reduce our dependence on exports has been successful,'' another ministry official said, also speaking anonymously. The country's current account surplus also plunged almost $ 10 billion during the fiscal year for its first decline in six years, the ministry said. The current account includes capital transfers and trade in goods and services to measure a nation's commerce. The ministry said the current account surplus registered $ 84.54 billion in fiscal 1987, down from $ 94.14 billion the previous year. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade, measured on a balance-of-payments basis, does not include freight or insurance charges on either imports or exports. Another commonly used trade measure, the customs-clearance basis, includes freight and insurance charges on imports. That boosts the value of imports and makes the trade deficit smaller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
