<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> continued high-level negotiations Monday in their dispute over increasing the sale of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> beef and oranges in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Neither side would disclose whether or how much progress was made in the round of talks Japanese Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> started last Wednesday with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. The two cabinet-level officials met both Monday morning and afternoon and tentatively scheduled another session for Tuesday, sources said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials would say only they continued to insist on removal of Japanese import quotas the two countries agreed to in a 1984 accord that expired last month. Otherwise, the issue will be pursued before <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, at its meeting Wednesday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, they said. Japanese officials said a major issue was `` timing'' of the removal. They declined to confirm <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> news reports of various Japanese proposals for a three - or five-year interval before full lifting of the barriers <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is the major customer for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm products but its domestic livestock and citrus producers have insisted on the quotas on imports of beef, oranges and orange juices as vital to their livelihood. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters have argued that as a result Japanese consumers are paying more than double the fair price for beef and oranges.
