<HEAD>National Office Vacancy Rises in First Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Continuing uncertainty about the health of the economy supressed demand for office space in the nation's central business districts during the first quarter, according to a study released Monday. The national real estate firm <ORGANIZATION> Cushman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Wakefield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said office vacancy rates jumped to 15.1 percent during the quarter from 13.8 percent in the previous quarter in the nearly 50 markets it reviewed. `` The uncertainty plaguing the financial markets and the economy's performance over the past eight months are beginning to affect the country's major real estate markets,'' said <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON> <PERSON> President </PERSON> and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirante </PERSON> II. <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> had the most vacant downtown space with a vacancy rate of 34.7 percent during the first quarter, up from 33.4 percent, although other oil-dependent cities showed some improvement from the previous quarter. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, had the second-highest vacancy rate of 28.8 percent, followed by <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, 28.1 percent; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, 26.9 percent; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, 26.8 percent; <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, 26.4 percent; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, 25.8 percent; <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, 25.5 percent and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, 25 percent. Among the cities with the lowest vacancy rates, <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> led the nation with a vacancy rate of 8.1 percent. <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> was followed by <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, 8.9 percent; <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, 10 percent; <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, 10.5 percent; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, 10.7 percent; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 10.8 percent; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, 10.9 percent; <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, 11 percent; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 12.1 percent and <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, 12.5 percent. A significant decrease in new construction helped vacancies in suburban markets ease slightly to 21.9 percent from 22.2 percent in the previous quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Cushman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wakefield </PERSON> predicted that office vacancy rates in central business districts would peak during the current quarter if economic conditions remain stable, and then resume a downward trend.
