<SECOND>BC-Weekly Steel, 1st Ld-Writethru,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 3.9 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd graf to make it 112 million tons a year sted a
week.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American steel companies put 95.5 percent of their production capacity into use last week, the highest percentage in nearly nine years, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. But the trade group noted that actual output was far below that of nine years ago because production capacity has been slashed due to competition from foreign mills. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers now have a maximum capacity of about 112 million tons a year, compared with just over 155 million tons when they operated at 96.3 percent of capacity in the last week of 1979, the group said. According to the group's latest report, steel production rose to 2.046 million tons in the week ended April 30, an increase of 3.9 percent from the previous week's 1.970 million tons. The capacity percentage was up from 91.9 percent the previous week. Estimated figures for the year to date put production at 33.653 million net tons, an increase of 27.6 percent from the 26.372 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations of <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987. Production so far this year used 90.7 percent of capacity, compared with 71.4 percent a year earlier. Net tonnage by district for the week ended April 30: <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, 276,000; <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, 204,000; <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, 127,000; <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, 170,000; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, 171,000; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 559,000; <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 203,000; Southern, 232,000; and Western, 104,000.
