<HEAD>Small Utilities Group Settles With Bondholders In WPPSS Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-four small utilities and cities in six Western states reached a $ 25.8 million settlement Monday with bondholders who sued them following <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>'s default on bonds sold to construct two nuclear power plants. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, lead counsel for the group, confirmed the agreement, the latest in a series of settlements totaling about $ 203 million involving defendant utilities, bond underwriters and legal firms. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said the 24 utilities, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, owned a combined interest of 6.5 percent in the two terminated plants, <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> No. 4 on the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation and No. 5 at Satsop, west of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said most of the $ 25.8 million would come from insurance coverage, although some of the utilities would have to pay out of their own pockets. While maintaining they did no wrong, by settling the utilities saved legal expenses from a case that could take years to resolve and avoided the possibility of losing their case in a jury trial, he said. The giant case stemming from the <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> bond default, the biggest in municipal bond market history, is to go to trial Sept. 7 in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> before Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. Dozens of individual cases were combined in the federal action. Eighty-eight utilities agreed to build the two WPPSS plants during the 1970s, but the plants were abandoned in 1982 after cost overruns and an assessment that the power from the plants would not be needed. The settlement Monday came on the eve of three days of hearings in federal court in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> before Judge <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> in the WPPSS case.
